<TITLE>Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<body background=chalk.jpg>
<H3><CENTER>Statistics Courses</CENTER></H3>


<PRE>
<BR>PSYC -125  Probability and  Statistics      
<BR>DeGhett, Terhune
<BR>
<BR>Psychology 125 is an introduction to elementary statistics for <BR>those students who need exposure to basic statistical concepts, <BR>but who may not intend to further pursue the formal study of <BR>statistics.  It is open to all students of the college.  <BR>Variability, uncertainty, describing data, sampling, hypothesis <BR>testing, correlation, and regression are among the topics surveyed.
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction:  lecture-demonstration
<BR>Prerequisites: High school algebra or equivalent
<BR>
<BR>Note:  1.  A course in statistics is a prerequisite for PSYC-290 <BR>Experimental Methods in Psychology (a required course for the major).
<BR>2. No credit may be earned for those who have received credit <BR>for any other beginning level statistics course.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>STAT-300  Statistical Methods             
<BR>Terhune
<BR>
<BR>Designed to follow from STA-100/PSYC 125, STA-300 provides a <BR>deeper examination of the assumptions that underlie basic <BR>statistical techniques.  It also introduces a few advanced <BR>statistical procedures.  During the first 7 weeks, t-tests and <BR>F-tests are covered in more detail than in STA-100, multiple <BR>regression and multiple correlation are presented, and the <BR>analysis of variance is treated extensively.  During the second <BR>half of the course, some basic nonparametric techniques overview <BR>of factor analysis and multivariate hypothesis testing.  The <BR>course is an applied statistics course and requires a working <BR>knowledge of elementary algebra.  It is not offered for credit in <BR>the Mathematics department.
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction:  lecture
<BR>Prerequisites: Intro to Statistics or an equivalent course
</PRE>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR NOSHADE> 
<BR>
