<H2><A NAME="Career Opportunities">Career Opportunities</A></H2><p>
Teacher Education is the study of how people learn and how to teach them.  At
SUNY Potsdam students can prepare for a career in teaching at the elementary,
middle school, or high school level.  A required academic major coupled with
teacher certification gives the Potsdam graduate an additional area of
knowledge and strength from which to draw upon for career options.  Certified
students may continue their studies at the graduate level in special education,
reading, instructional technology, elementary or secondary education.<p>
<p>
<H2><A NAME="The Study of Teaching">The Study of Teaching</A></H2><p>
SUNY Potsdam has a long and successful history -over 175 years - of preparing
teachers to instruct America's young people.<BR>


Students in Teacher Education begin by studying theories of how people learn,
how to most effectively present material to pupils and how schools are
structured.  Teacher Education majors learn to design courses of study, manage
a classroom, develop effective learning strategies, and design and assess
tests.  The faculty in Teacher Education may demonstrate team-teaching,
providing opportunities to participate in thematic cluster courses which
emphasize various aspects of classroom life.  There are opportunities to
observe teachers at work in public schools and to work with master teachers.
In the final year of study students have the chance to practice their skills as
a student teacher in a public school.<p>

<H2><A NAME="Field Experiences">Field Experiences</A></H2>
New York State requires appropriate field experiences before the student
teaching phase for those who plan to become teachers.  This is part of the
preparation for planning lessons and managing a classroom.  Some practicum
experiences will be required before student teaching.<p>

<H2><A NAME="Student Teaching Abroad">Student Teaching Abroad</A></H2>
SUNY Potsdam has access to a special student teaching experience in Lincoln,
England, for 16 students a year (fall semester only).  This program allows
highly competent students to meet the college and New York State certification
requirements in their area of specialization while acquiring first-hand
knowledge of the education system in Great Britain.  Other student teaching
experiences outside the United States are available through Moorhead State
University in Minnesota.
<p>
<H2><A NAME="Honor Society">Honor Society</A></H2><p>
Qualified education students may apply for membership in Kappa Delta Pi, an
international Honor Society in Education.
<p>
<H2><A NAME="Awards/Scholarships">Awards/Scholarships</A></H2>
The Teacher Education Department presents a number of academic awards and
scholarships each spring.  These include:
<p>
<DL><DT> The Frances Leitzell Award
<DT> Departmental Scholars Awards
<DT> Winton H. Buddington Award
<DT> Carbary Scholarship
<DT> Dowd Scholarship
<DT> Santway Scholarship
<DT> Eloa Pitz Memorial Scholarship
<DT> Annual Fund Scholarships
</DL>

<H2><A NAME="Coaching">Coaching</A></H2>
New York State interscholastic coaching certification is possible by completing
the following courses:
<DL><DT> Techniques of Coaching
<DT> Health and Sports Medicine
<DT> Philosophy, Principles, and Organization of 
<DT> 	Competitive Athletics in Education
</DL>

<H2><A NAME="Facilities">Facilities</A></H2>
The Teacher Education Department is located in Satterlee Hall, which houses an
extensive computer center.  The modern technology in the center is used in
education classes to create multi-media learning activities.  It also allows
access to the Internet and World-Wide Web.  
<p>
The Teacher Education math/science laboratory provides a learner-centered
environment to enable students to experience and develop contemporary teaching
strategies for use in the classroom of the 21st century.<p>
<p>
The Reading Center provides reading diagnostic services and instruction to
children in the region.  Teacher Education students may be placed in the Center
as part of their field experience.  This experience may involve designing
lessons to help children overcome reading difficulties. 
<p>
The Crumb Memorial Library has an extensive collection of materials supporting
the Teacher Education Program, including:  children's literature, curriculum
textbooks, published works and current periodicals.<p>
<p>
<H2><A NAME="Major Course Requirements">Major Course Requirements</A></H2>
<H3>ELEMENTARY EDUCATION</H3>
   
N-6 Certification - General Concentration<BR>

N- 6 Certification program majors must have an <i>approved </i>academic major.<BR>

(Please note: Art Studio and Dance are not acceptable.)

<p>
<B>Teacher Education Requirements</B>:<BR>

<DL><DT> 	Principles of Education 	
<DT> 	Mathematics - Elementary Methods	
<DT> 	Science - Elementary Methods	
<DT> 	Social Studies - Elementary Methods		
<DT> 	Reading and Language Arts I 
<DT> 	Reading and Language Arts II	
<DT> 	Foundations of Classroom Behavior
<DT> <b><i>Student Teaching Semester</i></b>
<DT>  Student Teaching Seminar: 
<DT> 		Issues and Ideas in American Education	
<DT> 	Student Teaching in the Primary Grades 
<DT> 	Student Teaching in the Intermediate Grades 
</DL>	
<B>Required Cognates</B><BR>

	<DL><DT> Drug Studies	
<DT> 	Writing and Critical Thinking	 
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> elective from composition,		linguistics <i>or</i> literature
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> elective from art, dance, drama <i>or</i>  music	
<DT> 	Probability and Statistics
<DT> 	One elective from Math Department
<DT> 	Child Development	
<DT> 	Issues of Exceptionality <i>or</i> The Exceptional Learner
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> course from the Biology Department
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> course from chemistry, geology or  physics
<DT> <i>		Note: one of the two science courses must be	accompanied by a lab.</i>
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> History course 	(U.S. History highly recommended)		
<DT> 	One <i>approved</i> elective course from two of the	following areas:		
<dd>		Anthropology, Economics, Politics, Sociology
<DT> 	Completion of the College's foreign language	requirements
</DL>

