<TITLE>Course Descriptions</TITLE> 
<body background=chalk.jpg>
<CENTER><H3>Upper-division Psychology  courses</H3></CENTER><BR><BR>

<PRE>
<BR>PSYC-301  Teaching of Psychology          
<BR>Staff
<BR><BR>
<BR>Psychology majors tutor students enrolled for PSYC-290 <BR>Experimental Methods in Psychology.  This course is an excellent <BR>opportunity for majors to further refine their background in the <BR>field of psychology by acting as laboratory assistants.  There <BR>is perhaps no better way to learn about a particular discipline <BR>than having to impart knowledge on the subject to students.  
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  seminar
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> by permission only
<BR>
<BR>This course is offered for non-liberal studies credit.
<BR><BR>

=============================================================
PSYC 321  Psychology of Adolescence       
<BR>Dodge-Reyome
<BR>
<BR>A survey of theoretical and cultural approaches to adolescence <BR>as a stage in the life process.  A consideration of differing <BR>views of adolescence as well as known facts about adolescents in <BR>our own culture and others.  Topical coverage will include <BR>theories of adolescence, cognition, sexuality, social <BR>relationships with adults and peers, school, deviance, <BR>subcultural patterns, adolescence as a commodity, social impact <BR>of adolescents, styles and fads, etc., (not necessarily in that <BR>order).
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> No information was provided. 
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Junior or senior status or age 21 <B>and</B> Child <BR>Development (strongly recommended)
<BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-322  Mental Retardation             
<BR>Reichhart
<BR>
<BR>This course is intended to introduce students to the causes of <BR>retardation, the assessment techniques used to diagnose <BR>retardation, the etiological classification and theories of <BR>retardation as well as the possible methods of amelioration and <BR>education available to retarded individuals.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B> lecture
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> three 1 1/2 hour exams - multiple choice and short <BR>answer essays
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC-220 Child Development
<BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-323  Adulthood, Middle Age and Aging      
<BR>Reichhart
<BR>
<BR>This course is designed to take the student beyond what are <BR>commonly called the developmental years.  Psychological and <BR>social aspects of personality development from early adult years <BR>to death will be explored through an examination of sex and <BR>mating patterns, family and work pressures, etc.  Theories of <BR>aging as well as the bio-physiological aspects of aging will <BR>also be discussed. 
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B> lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Based on seminar participation, a class presentation <BR>and two examinations.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Introduction to Psychology and Developmental <BR>Psychology.
<BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-330  Social Psychology               
<BR>Stillwell
<BR>
<BR>This course is an introduction to social psychology, or the <BR>study of normal, adult human behavior.  It does not attempt an <BR>encyclopedic review of the entire field.  The purpose, rather, <BR>it to stimulate the students to view the world as a social <BR>psychologist might.  The course involves the consideration, in <BR>some detail, of several key topics.  There include (but are not <BR>limited to): aggression, social influence, attitudes, behavior <BR>in groups, the self, social cognition, attraction, interpersonal <BR>relationships, stereotypes and prejudice. 
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>	Lecture & some discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>	4 exams (multiple choice & short answer), <BR>participation in 4 class presentation sessions, and a short paper. 
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B>	Introduction to Psychology and Experimental Methods
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-340  Learning and Memory             
<BR>Shearer
<BR>
<BR>This course is designed to be an introduction to learning and <BR>memory in both human and non-human organisms.  Major emphasis <BR>will be placed upon human research with topics covered including <BR>transfer, short-term and long-term memory, theories of <BR>forgetting, and theories of learning.  Traditional learning <BR>topics such as classical and instrumental conditioning, etc., <BR>will also be presented.  
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> 3 examinations willbe administered with each <BR>examination consisting of essay,identification, and multiple choice questions.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC-290 Experimental Methods in Psychology
<BR><BR>

=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-350  Educational Psychology          
<BR>Herman
<BR>
<BR>This course is designed to investigate and demonstrate what is <BR>known about human behavior in educational settings.  Topics <BR>considered are:  the effective teacher, role of motivation, use <BR>of tests and testing, exceptional children, learning, teacher <BR>roles, classroom management and control, left hemisphere-right <BR>hemisphere learning, discipline, child abuse, intelligence and <BR>intelligence testing.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion, 
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Both essay and multiple choice  tests.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Developmental Psychology or
<BR>Child Development or Adolescent Psychology and junior or senior
<BR>standing.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-366  Clinical Techniques for the Human Services Professions   			<BR>Herman
<BR>
<BR>The intent of this course is to provide undergraduates with an <BR>understanding of clinical processes which occur in mental health <BR>settings.  Techniques to be examined and demonstrated include:  <BR>contingency management, client-centered therapy, assertiveness, <BR>training, systematic desensitization, cognitive restructuring, <BR>research paradigms for the clinic, report writing, program <BR>evaluation, etc.  In addition such subjects as ethics, staff <BR>relations, and potential careers in the above fields will be <BR>discussed by the instructor.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion and demonstration
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Three written exams plus preparation of a videotape
<BR>demonstrating certain clinical techniques.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Theories of Personality and Abnormal Psychology <BR>are required.
<BR>
This is a special short term six-week course open to all students.  
<BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-370  Theories of Personality	
<BR>Stillwell
<BR>
<BR>The course will review the major theories of personality.  The <BR>student will be presented with a brief biographical sketch for <BR>each theorist, as well as some insight into how that theorist <BR>viewed the person.  The student will learn about the theorist <BR>through discussions of their research findings and clinical <BR>procedures where appropriate.  The presentation of each <BR>theoretical perspective will conclude with an analysis of the <BR>strengths and weaknesses of that point of view.  Some of the <BR>topics to be discussed in connection with the theories include: <BR>the healthy personality, freedom and choice, self-esteem, <BR>traits, and of course the "major" personality theorists such as  <BR>Freud, Skinner, Rogers, Jung, Bandura and Allport. 
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B> Lecture and some discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>	3 essay exams and one term paper
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> 	Introduction to Psychology and Experimental Methods
<BR><BR>

=============================================================
<BR>PSYC 375  Abnormal Psychology             
<BR>Codkind
<BR>
<BR>The course will deal with a consideration of the concept of <BR>"mental health" vs. "mental illness" and its meaningfulness, <BR>approaches to definition, the scope of the problem, whatever it <BR>is, treatment, it's nature and underlying assumptions, and the <BR>various syndromes that have been established by tradition.  <BR>Readings include a standard textbook.  Classes involve a <BR>combination of lecture and discussion, the relation proportion <BR>of each dependent upon student initiative and involvement.  <BR>Topics of interest to the students themselves can be pursued <BR>upon expression of such interest.  Evaluation of students is <BR>based on a series of identification/essay examinations and on a <BR>final essay examination.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Three class exams - ID and essay; Final - essays
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Child Development, Theories of Personality      
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-380  Animal Behavior                 
<BR>De Ghett
<BR>
<BR>The subject matter of animal behavior is a survey of the <BR>behavioral adaptations of the "animal world".  We will sample <BR>from both the invertebrates and the vertebrates.  Emphasis will <BR>be placed on those behaviors and behavioral systems that are <BR>found in animals in their natural settings.  The course and the <BR>subject matter covered will have an evolutionary theme.  Some of <BR>the topics to be covered are:  classical and contemporary <BR>instinct theory, biological constraints on learning, feeding <BR>behavior and predator-prey systems, strategies of reproduction <BR>and parental care, aggression, and the organization of social <BR>systems.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Essay exams and one term paper (a behavioral life-
<BR>history paper on an animal species of your choice.)
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Psychology majors must have PSYC-290 <BR>Experimental Methods in Psychology.  Non-majors must have <BR>junior-senior standing
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-381  Introduction to Biopsychology  
<BR>Gerstenberger
<BR>
<BR>All behavior is the result of changes which occur in the nervous <BR>system, be they temporary or permanent changes.  An <BR>understanding of the nervous system is, therefore, a worthwhile <BR>and meaningful objective for any student with interests in <BR>psychology, regardless of areas of special interest (social, <BR>clinical, experimental, etc.).  
<BR>This course introduces the student to <BR>
     1.  the basic neuroanatomy of humans and other animals<BR> 
     2.  the neurophysiological bases of behavior.  <BR>
<BR>In order to fully appreciate this area of study it is first <BR>necessary to understand the structure and functioning of the <BR>individual neuron, along with a working knowledge of the gross <BR>anatomy of the central and peripheral nervous systems.  Once <BR>this basic information is acquired, the course will center <BR>attention upon the neurophysiological bases of such <BR>psychological processes as learning and memory, motivation, <BR>emotions, sensation and perception, and states of consciousness.  <BR>Additional topics to be included are the neuro-  regulation or <BR>food intake, the coding specificity of neurons, hemispheric <BR>specialization, and sleep. 
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Three examinations will be administered, the tests being
<BR>composed of fill-in-the-blank,multiple choice, true/false
<BR>and short essay questions.
<BR><B>Prerequisite:</B> PSYC-100 Introduction to Psychology
<BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-382  Biopsychology Laboratory       
<BR>Gerstenberger
<BR>
<BR>This course provides instruction in research and laboratory <BR>techniques and methodologies employed in physiological <BR>psychology investigations.  Emphasis is placed upon the <BR>preparations for, and the actual recording of, human <BR>electrophysiological responses including the <BR>electroencephalogram (EEG or brain waves), the electro-oculogram <BR>(EOG or eye movements), and other responses such as galvanic <BR>skin resistance and temperature.  Physiological responses will <BR>be analyzed using both analog and digital processing methods <BR>with appropriate programming techniques being acquired.  Human <BR>sleep and waking states will be discussed in detail and <BR>polygraph recordings of a normal night's sleep will be performed <BR>and interpreted.  Applications of physiological recording in <BR>biofeedback, classical conditioning, and other areas of interest <BR>will be covered with students designing and completing a <BR>semester research project.  Neurosurgical lesioning techniques <BR>with the laboratory rat will also be performed.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  laboratory-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>  Students are required to read and discuss research <BR>articles relating to laboratory units with laboratory write-ups <BR>being submitted for each unit.  A semester research project will <BR>be designed and completed and a written research paper <BR>submitted.  Students will also be evaluated on the basis of <BR>quality of neurosurgical technique and participation in class <BR>discussions.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B>  Introduction to Biopsychology or 
<BR>BIO-360 Neurobiology.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-384  Cognitive Psychology         
<BR>Hui
<BR>
<BR>Cognitive psychology involves the experimental study of mental <BR>representation and processing in its various manifestations: <BR>attention, pattern recognition, learning, memory, reasoning,
<BR>problem solving, decision-making and language processing. 
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> No information given
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Introduction to Psychology and Experimental Methods
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-385 Sensory Psychology 1: Vision         
<BR>Hui, Terhune
<BR>
<BR>An organism must sense its environment and form impressions of <BR>it in order to interact with it.  Sensory and Perceptual <BR>Processes considers the ways in which these impressions are <BR>formed.  Physical energy in a variety of forms continully <BR>impinges on the organism's organs of sense, but in order to <BR>become psychological phenomena, the energy must be detected and <BR>processed by the various sensory nervous systems.  Complex <BR>patterns of electromagnetic energy become a landscape or a <BR>friend's face; vibrations of air molecules become symphony or <BR>the bark of a dog--all through the coding and processing <BR>provided by sensory-perceptual systems.  This course examines <BR>the processes by which physical stimuli are translated into <BR>psychological phenomena.  All senses will be covered, but vision  <BR>will receive the most attention.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-laboratory
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Grades will be determined by performance on<BR>
     1.  two written examinations that cover lectures, text, and<BR>
         readings,<BR>
     2. a term paper.<BR>
<B>Prerequisites:</B> Experimental Methods in Psychology
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-386  Sensory Psychology 2: Hearing
<BR>Terhune

<BR>A study of processes involved in Auditory Perception.  To <BR>understand how acoustic vibrations are transformed, encoded and <BR>perceived as tones, noise, speech, etc., necessitates an <BR>examination of topics from diverse areas such as physics, <BR>neurophysiology and psychology.  These topics include:  a review <BR>of sound and middle ear function; anatomy and electrophysiology <BR>of the inner ear and nervous system; psychoacoustic measurement <BR>of pitch and loudness; and a study of masking, critical <BR>bandwidths, frequency discrimination, binaural hearing and perception.  
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR>Appropriate demonstrations will be presented and, as time and <BR>circumstance permits, students may conduct basic experiments.
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Grades will be based largely on essay exams.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> HSA-337 or PSYC-381 or 392 or permission of instructor
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-390  Tests and Measurements          
<BR>Codkind
<BR>
<BR>This course is intended to serve as an introduction to the <BR>principles of psychological testing and assessment.  Topics <BR>covered will include basic statistical principles of test <BR>construction and evaluation, clinical techniques including <BR>interview and projective methods, evaluation and comparison of <BR>psychometric and clinical methods, and ethical questions in the <BR>employment of these methods.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion- demonstration <BR>with class participation
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Three class tests, term project & a final examination
<BR><B>Prerequisite:</B> A course in Statistics and completion of the <BR>Psychology Group II courses (6 hrs) or Statistics, PSYC-321, and <BR>3 hours from Group II.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-400  History and Systems of Psychology       
<BR>Codkind
<BR>
<BR>History and systems traces the history of psychology in terms of <BR>the issues which have been the most influential in generating <BR>psychology as we know it today.  Thus, after Descartes we will <BR>study empiricism, associationism, physicalism, etc., culminating <BR>in the arousal-activation model; Radical behaviorism, <BR>neofunctionalism, and a host of modern "small" theories will <BR>also be studied.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction: </B> lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>  There will be several midterm examinations <BR>including both essays and multiple choice item tests.  The final <BR>examination will be an essay covering the development of <BR>psychology thus far,and the future of psychology.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC-290, 340 and nine upper division credit hours.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-401  Seminar on Evolution (=GLG 401)           
<BR>De Ghett, Kirchgasser
<BR>
<BR>The modern theory of evolution is an idea that unifies and <BR>directs work in a large number of scientific fields.  <BR>Evolutionary theory has very broad implications and applications <BR>that every well educated person should be familiar with.  This <BR>seminar will explore these broad issues and look at the "big <BR>picture" that evolutionary theory portrays.  The instructors (De <BR>Ghett - Psychology and Kirchgasser - Geology) and the students <BR>will explore the paleontological, biological, and behavioral <BR>evidence for evolution and the impact it has had on the natural <BR>and social sciences.  We recognize that few students will have <BR>the perfect background for this material.  An inquiring mind, <BR>and eagerness to learn, and a willingness to discuss will go a <BR>long way.  After all, it did wonders for Darwin!
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  seminar-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> One term paper, class participation and being a <BR>discussion leader
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Junior-senior standing *and* permission
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-415 Research in Psychology  
<BR>Staff
<BR>
<BR>Guided research in an area chosen by the instructor.  Topics <BR>will be announced as the course is offered.  No more than 3 <BR>credits of Research in Psychology may be used as elective
<BR>in psychology, and no more than 6 credits may be taken in the <BR>student's career.
<BR><BR>
<B>Major type of instruction: </B> No information given
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Graded S/U
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B>  Junior or senior standing and permission of the instructor.
<BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-493  Seminar in Psychology          
<BR>Staff
<BR>
<BR>This course draws together students with a common goal (learning <BR>about psychology) who will choose different paths to achieve <BR>that goal.  This seminar provides junior and senior students <BR>with an opportunity for refining and assembling information in <BR>their area of interest.  It also provides an opportunity to <BR>share this information with other students while at the same <BR>time becoming acquainted with other topic areas within the <BR>discipline.  Student selection of topics will determine the <BR>content issues in psychology throughout the semester.  For the <BR>student with a good background in psychology this format will <BR>foster growth in your interest area, development of <BR>communication skills and intellectual stimulation that comes <BR>from participating in discussions with faculty and fellow students.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  seminar
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Grades will be determined on the basis of the <BR>individual seminar presentations, the participation in seminar <BR>discussions during the semester, and a term paper.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Junior or senior standing with at least 12 credit <BR>hours in psychology or permission of the instructor.
<BR><BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-494  Honors Seminar in Psychology          
<BR>Gerstenberger
<BR>The primary objective of this course is to have students <BR>increase their analytical and presentation skills in the field <BR>of Psychology with tasks that lead to a successful Honors <BR>Thesis.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  seminar
<BR><B>Evaluation: </B>Each student is responsible for leading 2 class <BR>discussions (2 separate 3-hour class periods).  Each student <BR>will also complete an American Psychological Association style <BR>paper that may serve as the proposal for an Honors Thesis.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Permission of the instructor
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-496 Honors Thesis Reseach 1
<BR>Staff
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  One-on-one contact with thesis committee 
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Progress toward completion of the honors thesis project.               
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC 494 (Honors seminar), STAT 300             
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-497 Honors Thesis Reseach 2 
<BR>Staff
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  One-on-one contact with thesis committee
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Successful completion of the honors thesis project.               
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Honors Thesis Research 1             
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-495  Theories of Human Development   
<BR>Smith
<BR>
<BR>This course will offer a comparative presentation of significant <BR>major historical and modern developmental theories, with <BR>specific evaluation of their relevance in the formulation of <BR>comprehensive psychological theory.  Theories certain to be <BR>discussed include those of the analytic, social-learning, <BR>cognitive, organic, structural, and behavioristic viewpoints.  <BR>Major theorists  studied will include Freud, Sears, Bandura, <BR>Werner, Piaget, Gesell, Erikson, Jung and Skinner.  There are <BR>three major purposes of this course.  The first is to <BR>familiarize you with the major constructs of each of the various <BR>theoreticians and theoretical viewpoints studied.  The second is <BR>to communicate which types of research are relevant to which <BR>theories.  Third, and as a way of breaking this course into more <BR>bite-size chunks, it is important to examine each theory against <BR>the key criterion of structuralist or non-structuralist content.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major types of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>  Three essay tests + short paper and unannounced <BR>short-answer quizzes.
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> Child Development
</PRE>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR NOSHADE> <BR>

