<HEAD><TITLE>Physics Courses</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=119 ALIGN=TOP SRC="Course_Descrip.GIF"><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Physics Course Descriptions</H3>

Courses are offered each semester unless otherwise designated.<P>



<B>PHYS-100 	Physical Science	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A course for non-science majors.  The intent is to help students develop some scientific literacy in the physics topics which are related to current science and technology.  Topics include motion, energy, electricity, heat, optics, the atom, the nucleus, and other modern topics.  Lab required.  Given as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-101 	College Physics I	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Part I of a non-calculus introductory course covering the ideas of mechanics, heat, wave motion, sound, optics, electricity, magnetism, atomic, and nuclear physics.  The course is intended for non-physics science, math, or computer science majors plus others who want a two semester course in basic physics.  Lab required.  Fall only.<P>



<B>PHYS-202 	College Physics II	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Part II and final part of the non-calculus introductory physics course.  The course continues through the topics listed for PHYS-101.  Lab required. Prerequisite:  PHYS-101.  Spring only.<P>



<B>PHYS-103 	General Physics I	4 Cr.</B><P>


	This is the first course in the sequence intended for physics majors, 3/2 engineering, and other science majors who want a more detailed introduction to physics with calculus as a corequisite.  Topics covered fall under the heading of mechanics; i.e. motion, Newton's laws, dynamics, work, energy, momentum, and rotation.  Lab required.  Corequisite:  MATH-151.  Fall only.<P>



<B>PHYS-204 	General Physics II	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Part II of the calculus-based sequence covering statics, wave motion, sound, heat, and thermodynamics.  Lab required.  Corequisite:  MATH-152. Prerequisite:  PHYS-103.  Spring only.<P>



<B>PHYS-305 	General Physics III	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Part three of the calculus-based sequence covering electricity, magnetism, and optics.  Lab required.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-204.  Fall only.<P>



<B>PHYS-306 	Modern Physics	4 Cr.</B><P>


	A course dealing with the important developments in physics of the twentieth century.  Topics include:  relativity, quantum, atomic, molecular, nuclear, and solid state physics. Spring only.<P>



<B>PHYS-195, 295, 395, 495 	Special Topics	1-12 Cr.</B><P>



<B>PHYS-198, 298, 398, 498 	Tutorial	1-3 Cr.</B><P>



<B>PHYS-320 Mathematics, Science, and Philosophy	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Selected writings by scientists and philosophers studied with concurrent progress in mathematical and scientific thought from ancient to modern times.  Credit not counted toward Physics Major or Minor.  Prerequisite:  one year of calculus.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-325 	Energy and the Environment	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Presents basic physical and quantitative concepts which are needed to understand energy and its environmental interaction.  The physical laws come from mechanics, heat and thermodynamics, electricity, and nuclear reactions.  A recurring theme is the extraction, transportation, conversion, distribution, end use, and dispersal of energy and the environmental impact of each step.  Credit not counted toward the Physics Major or Minor.  Prerequisite:  one FP or one FQ course. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-330 	Meteorology	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Components of the atmosphere, atmospheric dynamics, weather elements, weather phenomena and their physical courses, weather maps, weather predictions, operation and use of weather instruments.  Prerequisite:  one semester of college science or permission.  Fall or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-335 	Astronomy	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Topics include:  solar system structure and dynamics, stellar composition and evolution, binary and multiple-star systems, galactic structure and evolution, and theories describing the known universe.  Included also is the study of the evening sky, constellations, planetary movement, and astronomical instrumentation.  Prerequisite:  one semester of college science or permission.  Spring or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-350 	Elements of Special Relativity	2 Cr.</B><P>


	Basic principles of special relativity and their application to four-dimensional space-time and particle reactions.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-335 	Electronics	4 Cr.</B><P>


	This course involves (1) the study of electronic components and their function in electronic circuits, (2) the application of that information to the design of circuits, and (3) a study of the circuits themselves.  Topics include:  the theory, design, and function of common passive circuit elements, active discrete and integrated solid state devices, active vacuum devices, analog circuits, linear and nonlinear circuits, and digital circuits.  Lab required.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 or equivalent.  Spring.<P>



<B>PHYS-360 	Advanced Physical Laboratory I	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Advanced experimental work in electricity, magnetism, optics, and atomic, nuclear, and solid state physics.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 or permission.  Fall or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-361 	Advanced Physical Laboratory II	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Continuation of PHYS-360.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-306 or permission.  Spring or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-370 	Mathematical Physics	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Mathematical ideas and methods from linear algebra, multivariate calculus, and differential equations are studied and applied to physical problems.  Prerequisite:  MATH-152.  Spring.<P>



<B>PHYS-386 	Optics	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A study of geometrical and wave optics.  Topics include:  reflection, refraction, dispersion, diffraction, polarization, lenses, mirrors, optical systems, and fiber optics.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 or equivalent.  Fall or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-390 	Nuclear Physics	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A study of nuclear and particle physics.  Topics include:  natural and artificial radioactivity, nuclear detection devices, particle scattering, models of the nucleus, modern developments in particle physics.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 or equivalent.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-440 	Physics Laboratory Techniques	1-2 Cr.</B><P>


	Senior Physics Majors gain experience as supervisors of physics laboratories at various levels and/or serve as interns gaining experience in the college planetarium.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-103, 204, 305, 306 and permission.  Non-liberal arts credit.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-465 	Physics Research I	1-3 Cr.</B><P>


	Designing, performing, interpreting, and summarizing research project in a field of pure or applied physics.  Prerequisite:  Permission Fall and spring.<P>



<B>PHYS-466 	Physics Research II	1-3 Cr.</B><P>
	A continuation of PHYS-465.<P>



<B>PHYS-475 	Mechanics	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A study of classical mechanics following the theories of Newton, Lagrange, and Hamilton.  Topics include:  single and multiple particle motion, rigid body dynamics, moving coordinate systems, and particle interactions.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 and PHYS-370 or equivalent.  Fall.<P>



<B>PHYS-480 	Electromagnetic Theory I	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A study of electricity and magnetism which begins with electrostatics, proceeds through Maxwell's equations and ends with electromagnetic waves.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 and PHYS-370 or equivalent.  Fall or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-481 	Electromagnetic Theory II	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A continuation of PHYS-480.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-480.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-484 	Thermodynamics and 
		Statistical Mechanics	3 Cr.</B>

<P>


	A study of heat, thermodynamics, and statistical mechanics.  Topics include:  heat, heat engines, entropy and the second law of thermodynamics, thermodynamic potentials, phase transitions, and an introduction to statistical mechanics.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 and PHYS-370 or equivalent.  Spring or as needed.<P>



<B>PHYS-490 	Quantum Physics I	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A study of the phenomena which can be understood or described only with the quantum theory.  Topics include:  Bohr's theory of the atom, Schroedinger theory, single and multiple electron atoms, perturbation theory, Zeeman and Stark effects, collision theory, and selected topics from nuclear, elementary particle, or solid state physics.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-305 and PHYS-370 or equivalent.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-491 	Quantum Physics II	3 Cr.</B><P>


	A continuation of PHYS-490.  Prerequisite:  PHYS-490.  As demand warrants.<P>



<B>PHYS-494 	Physics Seminar	1-3 Cr.</B><P>


	Students study and discuss contemporary research problems and results in the fields of pure and applied physics.  Prerequisite:  22 semester hours of physics courses.  As demand warrants.
<P>

<P>



</BODY> 
