<TITLE>Course Descriptions</TITLE> 
<body background=chalk.jpg>
<CENTER><H1>Lower-division Psychology  courses</H1></CENTER><BR><BR>


<PRE>PSYC-100  Introduction to Psychology 
<BR>De Ghett, Gerstenberger, Hui, Reichhart
<BR>
<BR>PSYC-100 presents a basic introductory survey of the science of
<BR>psychology.  It examines what psychologists do, the methods they 
<BR>use, and the conclusions they draw.  Most major areas of modern
<BR>psychology are covered; biological foundations of behavior,
<BR>sensation, development, personality, social processes,
<BR>psychopathology, and psychotherapy.  Thus the course serves two
<BR>purposes--for the prospective major, it provides a foundation for
<BR>more advanced courses in the department, and for the interested
<BR>non-major, it offers a broad overview of contemporary academic <BR>psychology.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> Multiple choice tests
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> none
<BR><BR>
<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-198, 298, 398, 498 Independent Study in Psychology 
<BR>Staff
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction: 
<BR>Evaluation:                
<BR>Prerequisites:              
<BR>
<BR>
=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-220  Child Development              
<BR>All Sections except Section 4
<BR>
<BR>All sections offer the basic core material described below.  <BR>However, the method of evaluation does differ and is described <BR>by each instructor's name.<BR><BR>

<BR>A survey of the major issues, topics, and theories of child 
<BR>development with emphasis on the early years (up to 12).  The <BR>course is offered in the context of human development but draws upon
<BR>non-developmental and animal research to enable students without
<BR>prior psychology course to benefit as future teachers and parents.
<BR>Course content primarily addresses those areas of greatest normal
<BR>age related change (physical, personality, social,
<BR>cognitive-learning) but also introduces the methodological and <BR>practical aspects of child development and child study.
<BR>

<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture-discussion
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>
<BR>   Codkind:  (1) 3 multiple choice tests-short answer
<BR>             (2) 2 short papers
<BR>             (3) essay final

<BR>     Dodge-Reyome:(1) 4 objective exams
<BR>                  (2) 7 quizzes

<BR>     Smith:4 objective tests

<BR>     Reichhart:4 multiple choice tests and short answer essay exams

<B>Prerequisites:</B> none<BR><BR><BR>


<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC 270  Issues of Exceptionality        
<BR>Merchant<BR><BR>

This course is designed to introduce the student to the different <BR>types of exceptional children.  The major thrust of the course <BR>content is to examine and discuss the various issues confronting <BR>parents, educators, and the exceptional students themselves <BR>relative to providing education to exceptional pupils.  The <BR>course covers the historical development of education and <BR>legislation for exceptional children.  Topics such as <BR>curriculum, mainstreaming, assessment, individualized <BR>educational programs, and support services will be covered.
<BR><BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  lecture, discussion, group presentations
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> four examinations composed mostly of multiple choice
<BR><B>Prerequisite:</B> none
<BR><BR><BR>

<BR>=============================================================
<BR>PSYC-290  Experimental Methods in Psychology    
<BR>Shearer, Herman                     
<BR><BR>
<BR>This is a basic laboratory course in psychology, and is a <BR>required course for all majors.  Students carry out experiments <BR>with human subjects in the areas of learning, sensation, animal <BR>conditioning, memory, concept formation, etc.  Each experiment <BR>requires a formal written report.
<BR><BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  laboratory and lecture
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B>  one major exam plus evaluation of written experiments
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC-100 Introduction to Psychology and a course <BR>in Statistics 
<BR>
<BR><B>NOTE:</B> Your registration/advanced registration is cancelled unless 
<BR>you attend the first class meeting.
<BR><BR>
<BR>PSYC-290  Experimental Methods in Psychology      
<BR>Thaller
<BR>                    
<BR>This is a basic laboratory course in psychology, and is a <BR>required course for all majors.  Students carry out experiments <BR>with animals in the area of learning  Each experiment requires a <BR>formal written report.
<BR>
<BR><B>Major type of instruction:</B>  laboratory and lecture
<BR><B>Evaluation:</B> one major exam plus evaluation of written experiments
<BR><B>Prerequisites:</B> PSYC-100 Introduction to Psychology and a course <BR>in Statistics 
<BR>
<BR><B>NOTE:</B> Your registration/advanced registration is cancelled <BR>unless you attend the first class meeting.
<BR><BR>
</PRE> 
<BR>
