<HEAD><TITLE>Politics Course Descriptions</TITLE></HEAD> 
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=119 ALIGN=TOP SRC="Course_Descrip.GIF"><BR>
 
<BR>
Required courses are offered each semester, and most electives are offered every year or every other year. Also, a number of courses satisfy requirements in interdisciplinary programs such as Criminal Justice, Society and Human Services, Environmental Studies, International Studies and Women's Studies. Contact the department chair for more information.<P>



<B><CENTER>Introductory Courses</CENTER></B><P>



<B>POLS-100	Introduction to Politics	4 Cr.</B>

<P>


	Considers major perennial political problems. Introduces concepts and analytical techniques used in the search for appropriate responses to those problems. No prerequisite.<p>

<B>POLS-110	Introduction to U.S. Politics	4 Cr.</B><P>


	An introduction to the major political institutions in U.S. national politics and the behavior of individuals and groups involved with these institutions. No prerequisite.<P>

<B>POLS-126	Introduction to World Politics	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Examines the political, economic and social forces that have given rise to international conflict and global crises within past and contemporary world orders. Explores various perspectives on defining and addressing global issues. No prerequisite.<P>



<B>POLS-122	Bioethics and the Law	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Examination of the ethical and legal issues raised by developments in human biology and medicine. Topics discussed will include withdrawal of life support, abortion, AIDS and genetic privacy. No prerequisite. <P>



<B>POLS-125	(See WMST-100)</B><P>




<B><CENTER>Political Theory Courses</CENTER></B><P>



<B>POLS-300	Political Analysis and Methods	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Philosophical, theoretical and methodological questions concerning approaches to study of politics. Emphasis on political science as a science and methods and problems of scientific study of politics. Prerequisite: POLS-100. Spring only.<P>



<B>POLS-351	Political Thought I	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Political ideas from Plato to Machiavelli. Major shifts in emphasis and method throughout this period and continuity of certain persistent problems and approaches. Prerequisites: 2 courses in European History or Political Science, or 
permission.<P>



<B>POLS-352	Political Thought II	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Political thought from 16th century to present. Approach: same as POLS-370. Prerequisites: 2 courses in European History or Political Science, POLS-370, or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-353	Feminist Political Theory	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Explores feminist critiques of Western political theory and multiple feminist political theories from Western and non-Western perspectives. Prerequisite: POLS-100 or POLS-125 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-400	Political Science Colloquium	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Acquaints students with principles of performance and recording of research in discipline of political science. Prerequisite: junior or senior standing. 12-16 semester hours in Political Science recommended.<P>



<B>POLS-444	Politics of the Family	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Explores the relationships between family structures and other political structures to determine how family forms and ideals either facilitate or hinder political participation and democratization. Prerequisite: POLS-100 or POLS-125 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-445	Modern Ideologies	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Nature and development of concept of ideology. Main ideologies of modern world: democracy, liberalism, conservatism, Marxism, socialism, fascism, new left, etc. Prerequisite: POLS-100 or permission.<P>



<B><CENTER>U.S. Politics Courses</CENTER></B><P>



<B>POLS-210	Public Law	4 Cr.</B><P>


	An introduction to the U.S. legal system with emphasis on the criminal justice system. Recommended prerequisite: POLS-110.<P>



<B>POLS-314	Politics and the U.S. Economy	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Role of state in economy; debate over post-industrialization and political consequences. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-316	Power and Democracy in the U.S.	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Structure of power in U.S. society. Emphasis on social class, economic structure and political ideology in distribution of political power; assessment of implications for democratic theory and practice. Prerequisite: POLS-100 or 110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-318	Congress and the Legislative Process	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Structure, norms and procedural considerations that govern the legislative decision-making process. Primary emphasis on United States Congress. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-319	The U.S. Presidency	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Evolution of presidential office from Washington to Clinton. Formal powers of presidency; presidential elections and administration; relations among executive, legislative and judicial branches; and execution of presidential foreign policy. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-321	Politics and the Judicial Process	4 Cr.</B><P>


	A legal-political analysis of the institutions and factors shaping judicial behavior and decision-making. Emphasis is placed upon the federal political system, particularly the Supreme Court of the U.S. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-322	U.S. Political Parties	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Role of parties and pressure groups in U.S. politics. Emphasis on relationship between formal and informal elements within political system. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-323	Politics of Social Welfare	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Social policy in U.S. political economy. Emphasis on factors influencing development of modern social welfare state and effects on poor. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or POLS-125 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-412	Constitutional Law	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Study of the early formation of U.S. Constitutional law role of the U.S. Supreme Court, with emphasis on issue of federalism. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-413	Civil Liberties I: Expression and Religion	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Legal-political analysis of the development of national policy regarding the First Amendment with emphasis on Supreme Court decisions dealing with obscenity, libel, subversive speech and religious freedom. Required prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission. Recommended prerequisite: POLS-321.<P>



<B>POLS-414	Civil Liberties II: Race, Sex and Privacy	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Legal-political analysis of development of national policy in the areas of race and sex discrimination and individual privacy. Focus: Supreme Court's interpretation of the equal protection clause and the constitutional right to privacy. Required prerequisite: POLS-110 or permission. Recommended prerequisite: POLS-321.<P>



<B>POLS-420	Recent U.S. Foreign Policy	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Political process by which foreign policy is made; origins and character of Cold War; and role and interests of the United States in a post-cold war world. Prerequisite: POLS-110 or 120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-490	Legal Internship	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Students assigned to members of legal profession. Nature of work generally includes legal research, attendance at trials and drafting of briefs or legal memoranda. Students prepare term paper dealing with an aspect of the law to which they have been exposed. Prerequisites: POLS-321, outstanding work in law-related courses and permission.<P>



<B>POLS-491	Public Policy Internship	4 Cr.</B><P>


	During summer or regular semesters, students work as researchers and administrative assistants with policy implementing government and non-governmental agencies. Prerequisite: permission.<P>



<B>POLS-492	Legislative Internship	3-6 Cr.</B><P>


	Conducted in conjunction with New York State Senate and Assembly Internship Programs. Students spend spring semester in Albany as legislative interns to State Legislature, complete all requirements of internship program in legislature and an in-depth term project or paper. Prerequisites: POLS-100, 110 and one additional course in Political Science. Spring only.<P>



<B>POLS-494	Political Science Internship	6-9 Cr.</B><P>


	Conducted in conjunction with New York State Senate and Assembly Internship Programs. Taught in Albany. MUST be taken concurrently with POLS-492 for a maximum of 12 semester hours combined. (Non-liberal arts credit). Prerequisite: permission. Spring only.<P>




<B><CENTER>International or Comparative Politics Courses</CENTER></B><P>



<B>POLS-326	Politics of Advanced Industrial Societies	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Contemporary European political institutions and processes. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-327	Comparative Politics of 
		Developing Nations	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Political forces and patterns in Third World. Emphasis on political implications of alternative development approaches and conflicts. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-330	International Relations	4 Cr.</B><P>


	An exploration of epistemological, theoretical, research and policy trends in the field of International Relations; focusing on contemporary debates among realists, Marxists, post-structuralists and feminists. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-331	Politics and Global Economic Relations	4 Cr.</B><P>


	An examination of the politics of development and under-development and trends in global economic relations among developed and developing countries. Analyzes various perspectives on such topics as trade relations, multinational corporations, foreign aid and foreign economic policy-making. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-332	Women and Politics	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Explores impact of male-dominated politics on women and development of feminist politics from U.S., international and comparative perspective. Examines gender, race and class relations in politics of international relations, state, workplace, community and family. Prerequisite: POLS-100 or 110 or 120 or 125 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-335	Peace and Conflict Resolution	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Critically examines theories of political violence and explores alternative approaches to conflict management or resolution that can be applied to contemporary violence-prone situations and extant conflicts. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-336	Democracy and Authoritarianism	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Explores attributes and sources of instability in "old" and "new" democratic and authoritarian systems, analyzing systematic changes that might reduce alienation, broaden accountability, and enhance prospects for democratic stability. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-426	The Nature of Revolution	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Classic revolutions of modern times and investigation and application of models and concepts developed by social and behavioral sciences. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>



<B>POLS-431	The Military and Society	4 Cr.</B><P>


	Nature of militarism; assessment and comparison of determinants of civil-military relations. Prerequisite: POLS-120 or permission.<P>




<B><CENTER>Women's Studies</CENTER></B><P>



<B>WMST-100	Approaches to Women's Studies	3-4 Cr.</B><P>


	Introduction to women's studies. Examines gender relations and feminist perspectives. Explores how to learn from women's lives and uses gender as a category of analysis. Note: recommended that students take this gateway course first before taking electives in Women's Studies minor. Serves also as lower-division elective in Political Science as POLS-125.<P>



<CENTER><B>Other Courses</B></CENTER><P>



<B>POLS-195, 295, 395, 495   Special Topics	14 Cr.</B><P>



<B>POLS-198, 298, 398, 498    Tutorial	14 Cr.</B><P>

<P>



