<HEAD><TITLE>Sociology Courses</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=119 ALIGN=TOP SRC="Course_Descrip.GIF"><BR>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Sociology Course Descriptions</H3><BR>
 
Courses are offered each semester unless otherwise designated.<P>



<B>Note:</B>
	SOCI-101 is a prerequisite for all upper-division sociology courses.<P>



<B>SOCI-101	Introduction to Sociology	3 Cr.</B>
	Sociology as study of human behavior, social groups, socialization, stratification and social change; a consideration of basic social institutions. Every semester.<P>



<B>SOCI-102	American Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	American capitalism; nature of sexual, racial and economic inequality; contemporary American institutions: family, educational systems and systems of social control; and American culture. Spring and Fall.<P>



<B>SOCI-195, 295, 395, 495	Special Topics	3 Cr.</B><P>



<B>SOCI-198, 298, 398, 498	Tutorial	1-3 Cr.</B><P>



<B>SOCI-300	Introduction to Theory	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Origin and development of sociological ideas in 19th century and their expression in multiple orientations and viewpoints of 20th century American sociology. Every semester.<P>



<B>SOCI-301	Complex Organizations	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Theory and research findings relevant to formal organizations. Analysis of bureaucracy and decision-making in large scale organizations. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-302	Alcohol in Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	The past and present roles of beverage alcohol in societies throughout the world; theories of alcohol use and abuse; major controversies in the alcohol field.<P>



<B>SOCI-305	Sociology of the Family	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Family as social institution. Emphasis on structure and function of family; cross-cultural comparisons; analysis of contemporary American family systems.<P>



<B>SOCI-310	Racial and Cultural Minorities	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Factors involved in intergroup relations; principal minority groups in United States, research findings in prejudice and discrimination; programs aimed at amelioration of intergroup tensions. Every semester and summer.<P>



<B>SOCI-313	Third World Cultures	3 Cr.</B><P>


	This course introduces students to cultural variation and fragmentation among the area of the world referred to as the Third World. Geographically, the notion is identified with non-western cultures of Africa, Asia the Caribbean and Latin America. Emphasis is on how the Third World shapes and alters the lives of ordinary Americans at work and play. Whenever possible, faculty and students from Third World countries are involved in the course as guest speakers.<P>



<B>SOCI-314	Computer Applications 
		in the Social Sciences	3 Cr.</B><P>


	This course is designed to provide the knowledge and skills to understand and use contemporary computer technology in social science. Selected software types will be used to demonstrate computer usage in research and other social science work. Course topics include: data collection, presentation and management, using computers qualitative and quantitative data analyses, using and researching the internet, simulations and ethical issues in computing.<P>



<B>SOCI-315	Research Methods	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Research design in sociology: formulation of research problems, hypotheses, data-gathering techniques, measurement of variables and statistical analysis. Every semester.<P>



<B>SOCI-320	Work and Complex Organizations	3 Cr.</B><P>


	An examination of change in organization of work influenced by workers, management and global economic forces. Topics include: scientific management, human relations, employee involvement, deindustrialization, occupational hazards, gender and race relations, underground economy, influences of work in Japan, Sweden and Mondragon on U.S.<P>



<B>SOCI-325	Sociology of Social Services	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Organized and emerging public and private social service and social welfare efforts in terms of sociological and social science literature.<P>

 

<B>SOCI-330	Social Thanatology	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Sociological and social-psychological aspects of dying and death; demography of death and its consequences for society; changing attitudes toward dying and death; medical personnel and dying; suicide and euthanasia; problems in defining when death has occurred; and functions of funerals. Spring only.<P>



<B>SOCI-333	Technology and Society	3 Cr.</B><P>

		Pessimistic assessment of the technological society, its threat to the core values of western civilization that looks to extend individuality, freedom, equality and toleration. Attacks misuse of scientific and technological reason in the area of the social. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-335	Sociology of Aging	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Social processes and problems of aging. Changes in age structure of society and how it affects societal institutions. Issues of older individuals: health, finances, work, sex, death and social policy. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-340	Environment and Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	An examination of world-wide environmental crisis. Topics: energy, non-renewable resources, hazardous wastes, the ecological implications of technological change, agricultural and food issues, in the context of social systems, beliefs and institutions. Spring only.<P>



<B>SOCI-355	Individual and Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Social influences on individuals. Socialization and development of the self. Authoritarianism, symbolic interactionism, dramaturgy. Shaping of identity in post-modern society.<P>



<B>SOCI-360	Visual Sociology	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Study of sociological ideas through film. Provides understanding of history and theory of sociological and anthropological films. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-365	Sociology of Sex Roles	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Traditional sex roles in America: inherent advantages and disadvantages. Socialization processes through which children learn the culturally appropriate masculine and feminine behavior patterns. Spring only.<P>



<B>SOCI-380	Family Violence	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Violent phenomena in families. Theories of violence and extant research findings. Emphasis on child, spouse and elder abuse. Policies and programs which respond to family violence.<P>



<B>SOCI-390	Sociology of Mental Illness	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Social influences on field of mental illness and mental health. Definition, causes and treatment of mental illness. Emphasis on current theories of mental illness, client rights, emerging trends in therapy and relationship between mental illness and crime.<P>



<B>SOCI-400	Social and Cultural Change	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Socio-cultural forces accelerating or retarding social change. Emphasis on those which are operative in contemporary societies.<P>



<B>SOCI-401	Sociology of Rural Community	3 Cr.</B><P>


	People's clustering together in space; social/historical	 analysis of specific American types: the industrial town, "small" towns, suburbias; alternative communities as religious, political or cultural experiments.<P>



<B>SOCI-405	Religion in American Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Interrelationships of religion and American life; religious evolution; broadening value consensus; religion as cultural system; civil religion; institutional role versus prophetic role; religious organization.<P>



<B>SOCI-406	Advanced Data Analysis	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Emphasis on data analysis. File construction and maintenance, data interpretation and statistical analysis. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-415	Sociology of Education	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Social institution of education. Focus on functions and outcomes of educational process. Effects of major historical trends on nature of education. Inter-relationship with other social institutions. <P>



<B>SOCI-420	Social Class and Social Mobility	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Systems of stratification. Emphasis on contemporary American system; criteria and indices of position; changing patterns in social mobility; social class and behavior patterns. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-426	History of Sociology	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Selected topics in development of American sociology from a sociology of knowledge perspective. Prerequisite: SOCI-300. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-430	City and Society	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Factors associated with development of urban communities; characteristic urban institutions, suburban development; urban planning; ecological processes.<P>



<B>SOCI-435	Correction and Punishment	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Programs, processes, changing orientations and resistance to innovation in corrective system. Adjudication through probation, incarceration and parole; reintegration of offender; effects on inmates, administrations, policy makers and general public. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-440	Sociology of Revolutionary Change	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Sociological theories of revolution applied to study of concrete revolutionary circumstances. Emphasis on classes before, during and after revolutionary movements. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-445	Crime and Delinquency	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Introduction to major perspectives related to study of crime and delinquency. Focus: structural, socio-psychological and political-economy of these two facets of crime problem. Areas emphasized include: traditional and contemporary explanations; statistical estimates; behavior systems in crime and delinquency; critique of two systems of social control. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-450	White-Collar and Organized Crime	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Sociological examination of two pervasive forms of illegal behavior; focus: complex interrelationship of crime patterns to social, economic and political structures and cross-national aspects. Major emphases: analyses of recent research related to organizational facets of white-collar crime in corporate, professional and political dimensions; three major areas of organized criminal patterns, myths and reality of this aspect of the crime problem. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-455	Deviance and Social Control	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Social definitions of deviance, i.e., changing perspectives and concepts related to legal and non-legal nonconformity. Relevant changing justifications and arrangements for social control. Socio-historical case-study approach analyzes and describes various types of deviant behavior. Spring only.<P>



<B>SOCI-456	Political Sociology	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Political behavior. Emphasis on participation of individuals in political enterprise. Political socialization and public opinion formation; consequences of such phenomena as stratification, alienation and authoritarianism. Prerequisite: permission. As demand warrants.<P>



<B>SOCI-460	Population Studies	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Interrelationship of population structure and processes and socio-cultural phenomena; social demographic theory, methods and measurement applied to processes of fertility, mortality and migration; international population change. Spring only.<P>



<B>SOCI-465	Sociology of Health and Illness	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Aspects of illness behavior and interface of individuals and health care system. Fall only.<P>



<B>SOCI-470	Field Research/Practicum	1-6 Cr.</B><P>


	Field study of situations or problems of sociological significance within organizational settings, under supervision of faculty member. Prerequisites: SOCI-315, appropriate upper division sociology course work, and permission. SOCI-301 strongly recommended. May be taken twice, but no more than 6 semester hours counted for major. Every semester.<P>



<B>SOCI-472	Sociological Internship	 6 or 9 Cr.</B><P>


	Field work placement at an agency of student's choice under supervision of faculty member. A field study of organizational situations, problems and/or issues will be completed. Taken concurrently with SOCI-470. Prerequisite: SOCI-315, appropriate upper division course work and permission. (Non-liberal arts credit.) Every semester.<P>



<B>SOCI-475	Senior Seminar	3 Cr.</B><P>


	Methodology of sociological research; individual and cooperative investigation of selected topics; presentation and critique of findings. Prerequisites: senior standing and permission. Every semester.
<P>

<P>



</BODY> 
