<TITLE>Course Descriptions</TITLE>
<body background=chalk.jpg><CENTER><H3>Hearing Science</H3></CENTER>


<BR>HSAU-337 (PSYC 337)  Audiologic Principles in Hearing     
<BR>Merchant
<BR>
<BR>A study of acoustics, anatomy and physiology of the ear, <BR>theories of hearing, hearing disorder and their treatment.  <BR>Basic methods of audiometric testing with limited practicum and <BR>required observation in a clinical setting are included.
<BR>
<BR>Prerequisite:  none
<BR>Note:  This course is the prerequisite to all other courses in <BR>the Hearing Science sequence.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>HSAU-360  Environmental Noise             
<BR>Merchant
<BR>
<BR>An examination of the parameters of excessive noise, its effects <BR>on man and animal, instrumentation and methods of measurement, <BR>damage risk criteria, and existing regulations and laws relating <BR>to noise levels and exposure.  Practica and experimentation in <BR>noise measurements are a major part of the class activities <BR>utilizing noisy areas both on-campus and in the community.
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction:  lecture; demonstration; practicum
<BR>Evaluation: Five examinations; practica and experiment reports; <BR>comprehensive final examination
<BR>Prerequisites: HSA-337 Hearing Science I or permission.
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>HSAU-395 (PSYC-395)  Auditory Perception and Physiology   
<BR>Terhune
<BR>
<BR>A study of processes involved in Auditory Perception.  To <BR>understand how acoustic vibrations are transformed, encoded and <BR>perceived as tones, noise, speech, etc., necessitates an <BR>examination of topics from diverse areas such as physics, <BR>neurophysiology and psychology.  These topics include:  a review <BR>of sound and middle ear function; anatomy and electrophysiology <BR>of the inner ear and nervous system; psychoacoustic measurement <BR>of pitch and loudness; and a study of masking, critical <BR>bandwidths, frequency discrimination, binaural hearing and <BR>perception.
<BR>
<BR>Major type of evaluation:  lecture-discussion
<BR>     Appropriate demonstrations will be presented and, as time and <BR>     circumstance permits, students may conduct basic experiments.
<BR>Evaluation: Grades will be based largely on essay examinations.
<BR>Prerequisites: HSA-337 or PSYC-381 or 392 or permission of <BR>instructor. 
<BR><BR>            
=============================================================
<BR>HSAU-390  Topics in Audiology             
<BR>Merchant
<BR>
<BR>Students, in cooperation with the instructor, will select a <BR>topic within the hearing sciences to research and report.  <BR>Topics selected will be discussed among the students and weekly <BR>progress reports will be given to the class.  Near semester end, <BR>each student will present his/her topic orally before the class <BR>and invited faculty.  Stress is places on the use of <BR>audio/visual materials for presentations.  Students will be <BR>graded on the content and manner of presentations.
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction:  seminar
<BR>Prerequisites: none
<BR><BR>
=============================================================
<BR>HSAU-437 Advanced Audiological Principles and Practices
<BR>Merchant
<BR>
<BR>Advanced audiology theory, application of special auditory tests <BR>and study of testing equipment.  
<BR>
<BR>Major type of instruction: No information given.
<BR>Prerequisites: HASU-337/338 
<BR>
<BR>
<HR NOSHADE> 
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><A HREF = "PSYChome.html"><IMG Align=center SRC="/gif/logo.GIF"></A><BR><BR>

Return to Potsdam's <A HREF = "PSYChome.html">Psychology Department Home Page</A>.</CENTER>
</DOC>
