<BR>


<FONT SIZE=4><B><CENTER><!-- Anchor Point Tag -->
<A NAME="Direct Deposit">Direct Deposit</A></CENTER></B></FONT><BR>
<BR>
Most employees of the State University of New York College at Potsdam paid on a lagged, annual salary basis are eligible to, and encouraged to, participate in the State's direct deposit program.  Participants have their pay electronically deposited directly into their bank accounts.  Check stubs showing deductions and adjustments are still issued and are distributed to employees. Employees with low leave balances or poor attendance records, or who develop them, may be excluded from participation. Employees wishing to participate should contact the Office of Human Resources for an enrollment form.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER>
     <TR>
          <TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="http://www.potsdam.edu/PotsdamHome.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="SUNYPDM.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
<TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="HRindex.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="HRhomePage.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
          
         <TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="Payroll.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="BackToIndex.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
     </TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<BR>

<BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4><B><CENTER><!-- Anchor Point Tag -->
<A NAME="Agency Fees">Agency Fee</A></CENTER></B></FONT><BR>
On August 3, 1977, The Governor of the State of New York signed the "Agency Shop" bill which constitutes Chapters 677 and 678 of the Laws of 1977 and authorizes an agency shop fee deduction from the salary of State employees who are non-members of an employee organization which represents them for purposes of collective bargaining with the State of New York.  Since then, all employees appointed to the State payroll at the State University of New York College at Potsdam, except a small unrepresentated group of employees appointed to titles designated management/confidential by the New York State Public Employees' Relations Board (PERB), must pay an agency shop fee for representation even if they choose not to become dues paying members of the labor organization to which their positions have been assigned.  The agency fee is an amount equivalent to the dues required of members.
<BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER>
     <TR>
          <TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="http://www.potsdam.edu/PotsdamHome.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="SUNYPDM.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
<TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="HRindex.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="HRhomePage.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
          
         <TD><!-- Link Tag -->
<A HREF="Payroll.html"><IMG  Align=Top SRC="BackToIndex.GIF" border=0></A></TD>
     </TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4><B><CENTER><!-- Anchor Point Tag -->
<A NAME="Salary Schedules">Salary Schedules</A></CENTER></B></FONT><BR>
<BR>

<FONT SIZE=4><B><CENTER><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Minimum Wage">Minimum Wage</A></CENTER></B></FONT><BR>
Effective October 1, 1996, the minimum wage will be increased from $4.25 per hour to $4.75 per hour, and it will be increased again on September 1, 1997 to $5.25 per hour.  All employees earning $4.25 per hour will automatically be increased to $4.75 per hour effective October 1, 1996.  

<BR>
<BR>



Here you will find all salary schedules for SUNY Potsdam employees.  Note that for statutory salaries the hiring rate applies to every initial hire in the negotiating unit and salary grade at all State agencies for as long as the salary table is in effect.  It should also be noted that employees transferring between agencies at the same grade are appointed to the new agency at their current salary levels and steps.  Most classified service salary charts include 5 or 6 annual performance advancement steps which move appointees from the hiring rate to the job rate and longevity steps beyond the job rate on the 10th, 15th, or 20th year employment anniversary date.  In the charts shown here, the performance advancement amount is shown.  Not shown are the longevity amounts or steps.  Finally, it should be noted that there are more grades in the salary chart than actually shown, but, for the sake of brevity, only salary grades currently used at the SUNY College at Potsdam are included.<BR>
<BR>

<BR>
