<html><head><title>Middle School</title></head><body><H1><CENTER>TEACHER EDUCATION - MIDDLE
SCHOOL</CENTER></H1><p>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>(315) 267-2535   &#183;       Email to: <a href=mailto:mlynarhc@potsdam.edu>Teacher Education</a> </B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<HR><BR>
Contents of this page:<HR>

<UL><LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Career Opportunities">Career Opportunities</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#The Study of Teaching">The Study of Teaching</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Field Experiences">Field Experiences</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Student Teaching Abroad">Student Teaching Abroad</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Awards/Scholarships">Awards/Scholarships</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Coaching">Coaching</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Facilities">Facilities</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Major Course Requirements">Major Course Requirements</A>
<LI> <A HREF = "MiddleSchool.html#Faculty">Faculty</A>
</UL><HR>
Departmentally maintained files and links.

<p><HR>

<H3><A NAME="Career Opportunities">Career Opportunities</A></H3><p>
Teacher Education is the study of how people learn and how to teach them.  At
SUNY Potsdam students can prepare for a career in teaching at the elementary,
middle school, or high school level.  A required academic major coupled with
teacher education, gives the Potsdam graduate an additional area of knowledge
and strength from which to draw upon for career options.  Certified students
may continue their studies at the graduate level in special education, reading,
instructional technology, elementary or secondary education.<p>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="The Study of Teaching">The Study of Teaching</A></H3><p>
SUNY Potsdam has a long and successful history - over 175 years - of preparing
teachers to instruct America's young people.<p>
<p>
Students in Teacher Education begin by studying theories of how people learn,
how to most effectively present material to pupils and how schools are
structured.  Teacher Education majors learn to design courses of study, manage
a classroom, develop effective learning strategies, and design and assess
tests.  The faculty in Teacher Education may demonstrate team-teaching,
providing opportunities to participate in thematic cluster courses which
emphasize various aspects of classroom life.  There are opportunities to
observe teachers at work in public schools and to work with master teachers.
In the final year of study students have the chance to practice their skills as
a student teacher in a public school.<p>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="Field Experiences">Field Experiences</A></H3><p>
New York State requires appropriate field experiences before the student
teaching phase for those who plan to become teachers.  This is part of the
preparation for planning lessons and managing a classroom.  Some practicum
experiences will be required before student teaching.<p>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="Student Teaching Abroad">Student Teaching Abroad</A></H3><p>
SUNY Potsdam has access to a special student teaching experience in Lincoln,
England, for 16 students a year (fall semester only).  This program allows
highly competent students to meet the college and New York State certification
requirements in their area of specialization while acquiring first-hand
knowledge of the education system in Great Britain.  Other student teaching
experiences outside the United States are available through Moorhead State
University in Minnesota.<p>
<p>
<p>
<H3>Honor Society</H3><p>
Qualified education students may apply for membership in Kappa Delta Pi, an
international Honor Society in Education.<p>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="Awards/Scholarships">Awards/Scholarships</A></H3><p>
The Teacher Education Department presents a number of academic awards and
scholarships each spring.  These include:
<p>
<DL><DT> The Frances Leitzell Award
<DT> Departmental Scholars Awards
<DT> Winton H. Buddington Award
<DT> Carbary Scholarship
<DT> Dowd Scholarship
<DT> Santway Scholarship
<DT> Eloa Pitz Memorial Scholarship
<DT> Annual Fund Scholarships
</DL>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="Coaching">Coaching</A></H3><p>
New York State interscholastic coaching certification is possible by completing
the following courses:
<p>
Techniques of Coaching<BR>

Health and Sports Medicine<BR>

Philosophy, Principles, and Organization of Competitive Athletics in Education<P>

The Teacher Education Department is located in Satterlee Hall, which houses an
extensive computer center.  The modern technology in the center is used in
education classes to create multi-media learning activities.  It also allows
access to the Internet and World-Wide Web.  <p>

<H3><A NAME="Facilities">Facilities</A></H3><p>
The Teacher Education math/science laboratory provides a learner-centered
environment to enable students to experience and develop contemporary teaching
strategies for use in the classroom of the 21st century.<p>
<p>
The Reading Center provides reading diagnostic services and instruction to
children in the region.  Teacher Education students may be placed in the Center
as part of their field experience.  This experience may involve designing
lessons to help children overcome reading difficulties.  <p>
<p>
The Crumb Memorial Library has an extensive collection of materials supporting
the Teacher Education Program, including:  children's literature, curriculum
textbooks, published works and current periodicals.<p>
<p>
<H3><A NAME="Major Course Requirements">Major Course Requirements</A></H3><HR>

<B>MIDDLE SCHOOL EDUCATION</B><p>
The following required courses are common to all Middle School (N-6/7-9)
programs:
<p>
<DL><DT> Principles of Education
<DT> Reading and the Language Arts I
<DT> Foundations of Classroom Behavior
<DT> Student Teaching Seminar:  
<DT> 	Issues and Ideas in American Education
<DT> Student Teaching in the Primary <b><i>or</i></b>Intermediate Grades
<DT> Student Teaching in the Junior High/
<DT> 	Middle School
<DT> Drug Studies
<DT> Writing &amp; Critical Thinking
<DT> One elective from composition, linguistics, <b><i>or </i></b>
 	literature
<DT> One elective from art, dance, drama or music
<DT> Probability and Statistics
<DT> One math elective
<DT> Child Development
<DT> Psychology of Adolescence
<DT> Issues of Exceptionality <b><i>or</i></b>
 	The Exceptional Learner
<DT> One biology course
<DT> One course from chemistry, geology or physics
 (one science course must have laboratory)
<DT> History (American History strongly recommended)
<DT> Completion of the College's foreign language 
	requirement
</DL>

To obtain certification in a specific Middle School (N-6/7-9) area the
following specialized courses are also <b>required</b>:
<p><HR>

<B>N-6 &amp; 7-9 ENGLISH PROGRAM</B>

<DL><DT> (Literature/Writing major required)
<DT> Mathematics - Elementary Methods
<DT> Science - Elementary Methods
<DT> Social Studies - Elementary Methods
<DT> Secondary School English Program
<DT> Reading and Study Skills in the Secondary 
	School
<DT> One speech course
<DT> One approved elective course from <b>two</b> of the following areas:
<Dd> Anthropology, Economics,	Politics, Sociology
</DL>
<p><HR>

<B>N-6 &amp; 7-9 MATHEMATICS PROGRAM</B><p>
<DL><DT> (Mathematics major required)
<DT> Science - Elementary Methods
<DT> Social Studies - Elementary Methods
<DT> Secondary School Mathematics Program
<DT> Reading and Study Skills in the Secondary 
School
<DT> Elements of Geometry <b><i>or</i></b> 
 	Concepts of Geometry
<DT> One approved elective course from <b>two</b> of the following areas:
<DT> Anthropology, Economics, 	Politics, Sociology
</DL>
<p><HR>

<B>N-6 &amp; 7-9 SCIENCE PROGRAM</B><p>
<DL><DT> (Biology, Chemistry, Geology, <b><i>or</i></b> Physics major)
<DT> Mathematics - Elementary Methods
<DT> Social Studies - Elementary Methods
<DT> Secondary School Science Program
<DT> Reading and Study Skills in the Secondary 	School
<DT> One approved elective course from <b>two</b> of the following areas:
<DT> Anthropology, Economics, Politics, Sociology
<P>

RECOMMENDED ELECTIVES<p>
<UL><LI> <B>Geology majors</B>:  Astronomy, Meteorology
	<b><i>or</i></b>Genetics
<LI> <B>Physics or Chemistry Majors</B>:  One semester of Biology
<LI> <B>Biology majors</B>:  One semester Physics or  Geology
</UL>
<p><HR>

<B>N-6 &amp; 7-9 SOCIAL STUDIES PROGRAM</B><p>
<DL><DT> (Anthropology, Economics, History, Politics <b><i>or</i></b> Sociology major)
<DT> Mathematics - Elementary Methods
<DT> Science - Elementary Methods
<DT> Secondary School Social Studies Program
<DT> Reading and Study Skills in the Secondary 
School
<DT> Early U. S. History
<DT> Recent U. S. History
<DT> Recent Europe
<DT> Introduction to Cultural Anthropology
<DT> Micro or Macro Economics
<DT> U. S. Politics
<DT> Introduction to Sociology
</DL>
<p>
<p><HR>

