<H2><A NAME="Admissions">Graduate Admission Categories</A></H2>

<H3><I><B>A.  <A NAME="matriculated">Matriculated Students</A></B></I></H3>
<OL><LI> <B>Provisional Admission</B>:  Granted to qualified applicants who do not yet meet certain admission requirements; e.g., submission of satisfactory scores on the <B>last</B> portion of the New York State Teacher Certification Exams (NYSTCE) where required, undergraduate prerequisites, etc.<BR>
<LI> <B>Full Admission</B>:  Granted to applicants who have satisfied all admission requirements.<BR>
</OL>
In order to be considered as a matriculated student (Provisional Admission or Full Admission) applicants must fulfill the following criteria:<P>


<H4><A HREF = "gradprograms/gredprograms.html#MSED Program">Master of Science in Education</A></H4>
<OL><LI> submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university;<BR>
<LI> a minimal undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale of A=4.0); if the applicant's GPA is below the minimum, he or she will be required to take further course work to raise the GPA to an acceptable level;<BR>
<LI> a "Letter of Intent" written by the applicant expressing professional goals as applied to the program;<BR>
<LI> non-refundable processing fee of $50.00;<BR>
<LI> submission of proof of current provisional or permanent teaching certificate consistent with that of the proposed graduate study;<BR>
<LI> Admission to the <B>Special Education</B> program requires three letters of recommendation, including at least one which focuses on teaching performance.
</OL>
<H4><A HREF = "gradprograms/gredprograms.html#MST Program">Master of Science in Teaching</A></H4> <OL><LI> submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university
<LI> a minimal undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale of A=4.0); <BR>
<LI> if the applicant's GPA is below the minimum, he or she will be required to take further course work in order to raise the GPA to an acceptable level;<BR>
<LI> a "letter of Intent" written by the applicant expressing professional goals as applied to the program;<BR>
<LI> non-refundable processing fee of $50.00;<BR>
<LI> submission of three letters of recommendation including at least one which focuses on teaching potential;<BR>
<LI> a satisfactory score on the <B>last</B> portion of the New York State Teacher Certificate Exam (NYSTCE). <BLOCKQUOTE><B>Note</B>:  the ATS-W portion of the NYSTCE is required in order to be awarded the M.S. T. degree and to be recommended for certification.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</OL><P>
<H4>Master of Arts</H4> <OL><LI> submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university;<BR>
<LI> a minimum undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale of A=4.0);<BR>
<LI> a "letter of Intent" written by the applicant including professional goals as applied to the program indicated;<BR>
<LI> non-refundable processing fee of $50.00;<BR>
<LI> submission of three letters of recommendation
</OL><P>
<H4>Master of Music</H4> <OL><LI> submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university;<BR>
<LI> submission of two letters of recommendation;<BR>
<LI> non-refundable processing fee of $50.00;<BR>
<LI> a minimum undergraduate GPA of 3.0 (A=4.0).  Applicants with a GPA between 2.75 and 3.0 may be considered for Provisional Admission upon the recommendation of the Graduate Program Committee.  A student admitted into the graduate program with provisional status is limited in the amount of course work taken during the first semester (12 credits for fall or spring semester, six credits for summer session).  The student's progress will be reviewed by the Graduate Program Committee after one semester at which time the student may be considered for Full Admission, continue provisionally, or be dismissed from the program;<BR>
<LI> applicants must demonstrate competence in their area of concentration.
</OL><P>
<H3><B><I>B.  <A NAME="nonmatriculated">Non-Matriculated or Non-Degree Students</I>    </A> </B></H3> Granted to applicants who have an interest in graduate study but who have not yet applied for admission into a master's degree program.  A non-matriculated graduate student is limited to taking a maximum of 12 graduate credits on a non-matriculated basis.  Upon completion of the 12 graduate credits, if not before, the student is required to apply for formal admission to a master's degree program and must be granted Provisional or Full Admission before being allowed to register for further course work.
</UL>
</OL><H2><A NAME="FAID">Financial Assistance for Graduate Students</A></H1><P>

<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="assist">Graduate Assistantships</A></I></H3></CENTER>
Graduate Assistantships (GA's) are awarded annually to students who have demonstrated a high degree of academic excellence and professional competence.  A limited number of GA's with a stipend of $3,000 ($1,500/semester) and a tuition scholarship are available for the academic year based on the availability of funding.  Graduate Assistantships are awarded typically on the basis of merit, and it is assumed that GA's will be associated with their major departments and/or School to supplement their graduate degree program.<P>
Graduate Assistantships in <B>The Crane School of Music</B> are available to qualified full-time graduate students.  Upon completing the application materials for admission to the degree program, the applicant for a Graduate Assistantship in music must submit a separate letter of application, resume, and appropriate supporting materials (i.e., letters of recommendation, documentation of skill/experience/achievement in areas of expertise) to the Graduate Advisor in The Crane School of Music by March 15.  Assistantships will be awarded on the basis of student admission to the program, academic credentials, and skill/experience/achievement in the area of each designated assistantship.<P>
<B>Residence Life</B> assistantships are available each year for qualified applicants capable of serving as the director of a residence hall of some 200 students.  Remuneration consists of a stipend of $5,000, a board plan, a benefits package and a furnished apartment for the academic year.<P>
<B>Eligibility</B><BR>
Consideration is given only to applicants who plan to earn a graduate degree at SUNY Potsdam.  Assistantships cannot be awarded to part-time students or to non-matriculated students.<P>
Candidates for an assistantship must submit applications for both an assistantship and for a graduate degree program.  Official transcripts of all previous collegiate-level work and three letters of recommendation must be submitted.<P>
<B>Work Guidelines</B><BR>
Full-time graduate assistants receiving the stipend plus tuition scholarship may be associated with their major departments for an average of 20 hours each week.  Their responsibilities will be determined by each of the academic departments involved.<P>
The number of credit hours for which a graduate assistant is registered ordinarily shall be at least nine semester hours and shall not exceed 15 semester hours without the approval of the department and/or School.  Graduate Assistants who wish to take advantage of the full tuition scholarship must be registered full-time (at least 12 credit hours).<P>
<B>Applications</B><BR>
All inquiries and application requests should be directed to the Graduate Studies Office, SUNY Potsdam, Potsdam, New York 13676.  Applications and all supporting materials must be received by March 15.  If interested in a Residence Life assistantship, applicants must contact the Office of Residence Life, Sisson Hall.<P>
Announcement of awards will be made on or about May 1.<P>
<H3><CENTER><B><I><A NAME="reading">Graduate Reading Internships</A></I></B></CENTER></H3>
A limited number of graduate reading internships are awarded annually to students who enroll in the Master of Science in Education degree program in Reading.  Students who qualify for the annual stipend of $5,000 work in an elementary or secondary school 15 hours per week and gain practical hands-on experience under the guidance of the school's reading specialist.  Students graduating from this program become eligible for permanent certification in their area of certification and qualify for provisional certification (K-12) as a reading specialist.<P>
<B>Eligibility</B><BR>
Consideration is given only to applicants who plan to earn a graduate degree in Reading at SUNY Potsdam.  Candidates for an internship must submit applications for both an internship and for the graduate degree program.<P>
<B>Application</B><BR>

All inquiries and internship application requests should be directed to Dr. William Q. Davis, Teacher Education Department, School of Education, Satterlee Hall, SUNY Potsdam, Potsdam, New York 13676.  Applications and all supporting materials normally should be received between May 1 and August 20.  Selection of interns by the cooperating schools generally takes place during July and August.<P>
<CENTER><H3><I>SUNY Underrepresented Minority <BR>
Graduate Fellowship</I></H3></CENTER> This fellowship program was implemented to advance graduate educatrion for those minorities who continue to be underrepresented in SUNY.  To be eligible an applicant must be 1) a U.S. citizen or have permanent resident status; 2) a member of one of the following groups:  Native American, African American or Hispanic American; and 3) accepted for full time graduate study (registered for 12 graduate hours or more).  The fellowship includes both a stipend and tuition scholarship, amounting to a maximum of $10,000 for the academic year.<P>
<H3><CENTER><I>Graduate Opportunity <BR>
Waiver Program</I></CENTER></H3> This need-based program provides a tuition scholarship to former EOP, SEEK or HEOP students who are accepted and enrolled as full-time graduate students.  The waiver is typically awarded on the basis of merit.  Unfortunately, there is insufficient funding to support all eligible applicants.<P>
<H3><CENTER><I>Additional Financial Aid Programs</I></CENTER></H3> In addition to the above, graduate students may be eligible to participate in a number of other financial aid programs.  The following is a list of the major sources of additional assistance for graduate students.  Information may be obtained by contacting the Financial Aid Office, SUNY Potsdam, Potsdam, New York 13676.<P>
<B><A NAME="TAP">Tuition Assistance Program (TAP)</A></B><BR>
TAP is a State entitlement program which provides non-repayable grants.  To be eligible, a student must:  
<OL><LI> be a New York State resident and a U. S. citizen or permanent resident alien;<BR>
<LI> be enrolled full-time (registered for at least 12 credit hours per semester) and matriculated at an approved postsecondary institution. 
</OL> 
</OL>Awards are based on net taxable income.  The maximum award for graduate study is $1,200.<P>
Graduate students may receive TAP awards for up to four years of study.  However, no student may receive awards for more than a total of eight years of undergraduate and graduate study.<P><B><CENTER>TAP AWARD ACADEMIC STANDARDS*<BR>
Matriculated Graduate Students<BR>
SUNY Potsdam</CENTER></B><BR>

<CENTER><IMG  Align=Center SRC="tapaward.GIF"><BR></CENTER>
<BR>

<B>Note:</B>  TAP award payments will not be certified unless the specified number of credits and minimum grade point average is met or exceeded semester by semester as shown above.<BR>
<B>*</B>One waiver permitted by appeal to the Dean of Professional Studies and Graduate Programs (for serious illness of the student, serious illness or death in the immediate family, emotional difficulties, or other detailed and documented unusual personal circumstances).<P>

<B><A NAME="workstudy">Federal Work Study (FWS)</A></B><BR>
The Federal Work Study (FWS) program provides jobs for students with financial need.  Students at SUNY Potsdam may apply if they are matriculated and enrolled at least half-time.  Students select their own jobs based on interest and qualifications from approximately 300 positions throughout the College's various departments.  Employment hours per week may range from six to 20 hours and are paid at the federal minimum wage rate.<P>
To apply for FWS, students must file a Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).<P>
<B><A NAME="perkins">Federal Perkins Loan (formerly NDSL)</A></B><BR>
The Federal Perkins Loan Program is a low-interest, long-term loan for matriculated students who are enrolled in a program of study at least half-time.  To apply for a Federal Perkins Loan students must file the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).<P>
The current interest rate on the Federal Perkins Loan is 5%.  The loan is interest free while the student is enrolled in school at least half-time.  Repayment of the loan will begin six months after graduation or upon leaving school.  Normal repayment of the loan may be scheduled for up to 10 years.  If a student pursues loan consolidation of all federal loans, the repayment period will be extended.<P>
The Financial Aid Office provides information regarding cancellation of the Federal Perkins Loan for students who pursue public service as: teachers in targeted low-income elementary or secondary schools; special education teachers; teachers in any field of expertise determined by the state education agency to have a shortage of qualified teachers; full-time nurses or medical technicians; and/or full-time employees of a public or private nonprofit child or family service agency.<P>
<B>Ford Federal Direct Loan Program</B><BR>
The Ford Federal Diret Loan offers low-interest, federally funded loans directly to students through SUNY Potsdam.  Direct loans simplify the loan process and eliminate the need for an outside lender, such as a bank.<P>
<A NAME="direct"><B><H4>Direct Stafford Loan Graduate</H4></B></A> Students may borrow up to $8,500.  To qualify for funds, students must be matriculated and enrolled at least half-time.  The loan is subsidized by the federal government and will be interest free until the repayment period commences.  Repayment begins six monmths after graduation.  Eligibility is determined through a financial need formula as established by the federal government.  To apply for a Federal Direct Loan, the student must complete the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) and submit a loan application to the Financial Aid Office.<P>
The current variable interest rate for new borrowers is 7.43%.  A new interest will be evaluated annually in July and will not exceed 8.25%.<P>
<B><A NAME="unsub">Direct Unsubsidized Stafford Loan</A></A></B><BR>
The Unsubsidized Direct Stafford Loan program has terms, interest rate, and an annual limit similar to the Direct Stafford Loan program.  Awards are not based on need and will allow all students who do not qualify for the maximum amount on the Subsidized Direct Stafford Loan financial aid assistance.<P>
Unlike the subsidized Direct Stafford Loan where the Federal government pays the interest on the loan while the student is in school at least half-time, the borrower is responsible for paying the interest on the Unsubsidized Direct Stafford Loan that accrues while they are in school.  Interest can be deferred while in school, but will be capitalized (added to the principle balance of the loan) at the start of repayment.  To apply for assistance, students must first be evaluated for federal need-based funds by filing the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).<P>
The maximum annual award available for the Unsubsidized Direct Stafford Loan, or for the Unsubsidized Direct Stafford Loan <B>combined</B> with the Direct Stafford Loan, is $18,500.<P>
<B><CENTER>STANDARD OF SATISFACTORY ACADEMIC PROGRESS FOR<BR>
PURPOSE OF DETERMINING ELIGIBILITY FOR FEDERAL STUDENT AID<BR>
Graduate Program<BR>
SUNY Potsdam</CENTER></B><P>
<CENTER><IMG  Align=Top SRC="Standard.GIF"><P></CENTER>
<B>NOTE</B>:  The maximum number of semesters to earn a master's degree is four for full-time students or 48 points (the equivalent of four semesters) for part-time graduate students; i.e., 12 points for a full-time semester or one point for each semester hour of part-time or summer study.  The student who accumulates 48 or more points is ineligible for federal financial aid.<P>



</H6></H4><CENTER><H2><B><A NAME="Scholarships">Graduate Scholarships</A></B></H1></CENTER>
<BR>



<B><A NAME="mcgeogh">The Dorothy M. McGeoch Memorial Graduate Student Award</A></B><BR>

An annual award is made during the spring semester to a graduate student in the School of Education in memory of Dorothy M. McGeoch, who was a faculty member in the School of Education.  The Criteria for the award follow:<BR>

<OL><LI> The student must have Full Admission in a registered program at SUNY Potsdam leading to the Master of Science in Education or Master of Science in Teaching degree.<BR> 
<LI> The student must have maintained a cumulative grade point average of 3.75 or higher during graduate study.<BR>
<LI> The student must be in good standing at SUNY Potsdam.<P>
</OL>

<B><A NAME="santway">The Alfred W. Santway Scholarship</A></B><BR>

These scholarships were established in memory of Bella Harris Santway and are available to full-time graduate students in a Master of Science in Education or Master of Science in Teaching degree program.  The criteria for the award follows:
<OL><LI> The student must have Full Admission in a registered program at SUNY Potsdam leading to the Master of Science in Education or Master of Science in Teaching degree.<BR>
<LI> Primary consideration is given to financial need, seriousness of purpose and academic achievement.<BR>
<LI> Preference given to residents of St. Lawrence County.<BR>
<LI> The student must be in good standing at SUNY Potsdam.<BR>
<LI> The minimum amount available for scholarships is approximately $500.
</OL>

<B><A NAME="leitzell">Francis L. Leitzell Award</A></B><BR>

This is awarded to best student teacher based on references from field experience supervisor/sponsor teacher; the criteria for the award follows: <OL><LI> An ability to impart knowledge to student.
<LI> An ability to teach children to use the knowledge.
<LI> An ability to maintain discipline.
</OL>
<B><A NAME="dowd">Dowd Scholarship</A></B><BR>

<OL><LI> The student must be matriculated in a program leading to undergraduate elementary certification, M.S.Ed. (elementary), or M.S.T. (elementary);
<LI> Student must be in process of completing degree requirements when application is made;
<LI> Student must be a graduate of (in order of preference) Canton, Lisbon, or Ogdensburg High School.
</OL>
<B><A NAME="buddington">Winton H. Buddington Award</A></B>
<OL><LI> Student must be matriculated in M.S.Ed degree program.
<LI> Reading specialization.
<LI> Student must have maintained a 3.5 or better average and have completed at least nine hours.
</OL>


<B><A NAME="alumni">Alumni Scholarship Award</A></B><BR>

<OL><LI> Student must be matriculated in a teacher certification program;<BR>
<LI> Student must be completing all degree requirements when application is made.
</OL>
<B><A NAME="annual">Annual Fund Scholarships</A></B><BR>

<OL><LI> Student must be in a graduate or undergraduate teacher certification program.
</OL>
Applications for the aforementioned scholarships/awards may be obtained from and returned to the Chairperson, Teacher Education Department, School of Education.  The schalarships listed are awarded by the SUNY Potsdam Foundation through gifts from alumni and friends of the College.<P>

<B><A NAME="snell">The Helen Snell Cheel Scholarships</A></B><BR>


Scholarships are available to qualified full-time graduate students in The Crane School of Music who are in need of financial assistance.  Selection of recipients is made by the SUNY Potsdam Foundation and the Dean of The Crane School of Music based upon the recommendation of The Crane School of Music Graduate Program Committee.  Upon completing the application materials for admission to the degree program, the applicant for a Helen Snell Cheel Scharlship should submit a separate letter of application to the Graduate Adviser in The Crane School of Music.

