<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>MRSI: A.C. Walker Foundation Guidelines</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BACKGROUND="YELLOW.JPG">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=32 HEIGHT=32 ALIGN=center SRC="logo-red.GIF"></CENTER><P>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>William C. Merwin <BR>
Rural Services Institute</H1><P>
<HR WIDTH=100%><P>
<CENTER><font color='000873'><FONT SIZE=6>A.C. W</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>ALKER </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>F</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>OUNDATION</FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>N</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>ORTH </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>C</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>OUNTRY </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>R</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>ESEARCH </FONT><FONT SIZE=6>F</FONT><FONT SIZE=5>ELLOWSHIPS</FONT></CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5><FONT SIZE=6>G</FONT>UIDELINES</FONT></font>
</CENTER><P><!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->

 <font size=4>
<B>Objective: </B><BR>
The A.C. Walker Foundation and the William C. Merwin Rural Services Institute (MRSI) of SUNY Potsdam seek to encourage faculty from the region's colleges and universities to  research critical problems confronting the North Country.  Faculty investigators are expected to examine the roles which both the private and the public sectors can play in providing solutions to the region's problems.  MRSI will publish and distribute selected completed studies to interested parties.<P>

<B>Eligibility: </B><BR>
Full- or part-time teaching faculty at any of the colleges or universities located in Clinton, Essex, Franklin, Jefferson, Lewis, or St. Lawrence Counties are eligible to apply.  The faculty applicant must be in the employment of his or her current college or university during the period of the Fellowships.  Academic institutions included are:  Clarkson University, Clinton Community College, Jefferson Community College, Mater Dei College, North Country Community College, Paul Smith's College, St. Lawrence University, SUNY Canton, SUNY Plattsburgh, SUNY Potsdam, Wadhams Hall Seminary College, and Wanakena Campus of SUNY ESF.<P>

<B>Community and Business Involvement:</B><BR> 
The Fellowships are designed to assure greater community-academic cooperation than has traditionally been the case in most research programs.  They promote a close working relationship between academic researchers and individuals from local and regional organizations or businesses to jointly investigate critical North Country issues.  Faculty applicants for the Fellowship must identify an individual from a local or regional organization or business who has agreed to sponsor the proposed project.  Proposals which  include a strong statement of support from the sponsoring individual/organization that clearly explains how the community will benefit from the project results, and that commits specific resources to the project, will be given preference.<P>

<B>Procedure:</B><BR> 
(1) Proposals should be submitted according to the prescribed application form and postmarked by March 7, 1997. <BR>
(2) Applications will be evaluated by the Fellowships Advisory Council based on the criteria outlined below. <BR>
(3) The Council's recommendations will be submitted to the president of SUNY Potsdam for final decision.<BR>
(4) Applicants will be notified in May, 1997.<p>

<B>Criteria for Evaluation: </B><BR>
Applications will be evaluated on the following criteria using a point system for evaluation:<BR>
(1)  Nature and magnitude of the problem and focus of the proposed project: (25 pts.)<BR>
(2)  Community support/participation: (35 pts.)<BR>
(3)  Investigation procedure/methodology: (15 pts.)<BR>
(4)  Background and previous research experience: (15 pts.)<BR>
(5)  Funding request: (10 pts.)<P>

<B>Funding:</B><BR> 
Funding for this program comes from the A.C. Walker Foundation. The program provides up to $2,000 per award. Depending on the type(s) of proposals, budget requests  and recommendations of the Fellowships Advisory Council,  lesser amounts may be awarded. Half of the Fellowship funds will be provided to the successful applicant at the time the Fellowships are awarded.  The remaining funds will be provided upon MRSI's receipt of the completed study.<P>

<B>Administration:</B><BR> 
The Fellowships Program is administered by MRSI at SUNY Potsdam with the assistance of the A.C. Walker Foundation Fellowships Advisory Council, whose members come from business, education, government, economic development and other state, local and regional organizations.  Overall responsibility for supervision of the program lies with the president of SUNY Potsdam.<P>

<B>Fellowships Advisory Council:</B><P>

Ram L. Chugh Ph.D.<BR>
SUNY Potsdam, Chair<P>

Frank Alguire <BR>
Massena Industrial Development Corp.<P>

Mark Barie<BR>
