<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>CPR Lesson Plan</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY background="pinkbk.gif" TEXT="#000000">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
<B>
Angie King<BR>
Grade 5<BR>
CPR & First Aid<BR>
<P><P><P>



<B>Rationale: </B> The following lesson will challenge students to learn the mechanics of CPR 	and how to utilize them in an emergency situation.  It is important that students at 	this stage in life learn emergency steps to take care of themselves and others, as 	many students begin to undertake child care roles.  This will also give rise to 	respecting the emergency system, and the people which hold jobs as emergency 	health care providers as well.  This lesson will aid in the better understanding of 	many topics which include:  CPR, heimlick maneuver, first aid, personal safety, 	making emergency phone calls to 911.  This lesson incorporates many subjects as 	well.  These include:  Math, science, and English (vocabulary and communication 	skills).<P><P>



<B>Motivation: </B> due to the hands-on nature of this lesson, the teacher will find the students 	very enthusiastic to learn all the details of emergencies.  The teacher should use this 	excitement to their benefit and incorporate many aspects into the lesson.  The 	students will in turn gain knowledge in mathematics, social skills, vocabulary and 	science.  <P><P>



<B>Target Audience: </B> depending on the complexity of information you wish to incorporate 	into this lesson the audience can range from grade 3-12.  The focus of this lesson is 	for 5-6 grade, with the assumption that the students have prior knowledge of acting 	in emergency situations, utilizing the 911 system, and emergency vocabulary.<P><P>


<B>
Goals and Objectives: </B> My goal in this lesson is to give the students a compact 	understanding of CPR, along with aspects of emergency situations.  They will be 	confident in utilizing the 911 system, and also show confidence in handling life 	threatening situations while waiting for health care providers to arrive.<P><P>


<B>
Materials: </B>  <P>  -blood pressure cuff<BR>
		-stethoscope<BR>
		-latex gloves<BR>
		-bag valve mask<BR>
		-CPR masks<BR>
		-CPR mannequin<BR>
		-EMT jump bag<BR> <P><P>
<B>Procedure: </B><BR> 
	-the teacher will begin the lesson by giving a brief description of the activities 	planned, and incorporate students reactions into a summative rubric.
		-this will be used as a means of evaluation at the end of the lesson.
			
	<B>Making a call to 911</B><BR>
	-The teacher will propose a scenario for the children, enabling them to get the full 	feeling of an emergency situation.  <BR>
		-ex.  Have a student or team teacher pretend to be choking.  Go through the 		         steps for an emergency.<BR>  
			-look for the universal sign for choking<BR>
			-have a student dial 911 and give the system the following 				 information. <BR>
				-what is the emergency<BR>
				-location of the incident (address and town)<BR>
				-phone number where the incident is occurring<BR>
				-name, age, and sex of the patient<BR>
				-hold on the line until help arrives<BR>
	-explain what has just happened among all the termoil, reiterate the steps and go 	 	 over how the scenario was carried out effectively and ineffectively.<BR>
	-ask the students where their emergency numbers are posted in their house.<BR>
		-have them do the Emergency Numbers Worksheet and take it home to post 		 by their phone. <P><P>

	<B>The Heimlick Maneuver</B><BR>
	-the teacher will review the example scenario once again, this time focusing on the 	element of emergency care (ie. heimlick maneuver).<BR>
	-the teacher will show the appropriate steps in performing the heimlick, and 	explain in what situations this action is necessary.<BR>
		-the teacher should stress the importance of doing the procedure properly, 		 and explain the difference between choking and coughing.<BR>
			-choking: no sound perform heimlick<BR>
			-coughing: sound encourage patient to continue coughing <BR>
	-have students practice on eachother locating the correct position of the procedure<BR>
	-question and comment period<BR><P>

	<B>-CPR</B><BR>
	-the teacher will review the example scenario once again, this time focusing on the 	element of emergency care (i.e.. CPR).<BR><P>
	-Introduce CPR<BR>
		-define it<BR>
		-why is it used<BR>
			-to keep oxygen supply to the vital organs it increase the expectancy of 			 survival<BR>
		-when is it used<BR>
			-when there is no pulse, respirations, or breathing<BR>
	-How do you do CPR<BR>
		-introduce the mannequin and explain that they are used to train emergency 		 personnel in CPR<BR>
			-explain why you can't practice on each other<BR>
			-let the kids feel touch and look<BR><P>
		-explain the anatomy of the body and the roles they play in CPR<BR>
			-ribs<BR>
			-xyphoid process<BR>
			-diaphragm<BR>
			-heart<BR>
			-pulse points<BR>
			-mouth<BR>
			-nose<BR><P>
		-Demonstrate how CPR is done on an adult<BR>
			-ratios for one rescuer<BR>
			-ratios for two rescuers<BR>
			-effective and ineffective performance<BR>
			-have kids try it and practice<BR><P>
		-Demonstrate how CPR is done on an child<BR>
			-ratios for one rescuer<BR>
			-effective and ineffective performance<BR>
			-have kids try it and practice<BR><P>
		-Demonstrate how CPR is done on an infant<BR>
			-ratios for one rescuer<BR>
			-effective and ineffective performance<BR>
			-explain how fragile infants are and the importance of being careful<BR>
			-have kids try it and practice<BR>
	-review a handout on CPR<BR> 
	-Question and Comments<BR><P><P>

<B>
Evaluation: </B> the students will perform their abilities in CPR and the Heimlick Maneuver and be able to effectively demonstrate their understanding of the processes.  They should also show good personal safety skills, and act effectively in an emergency situation.  The students  will make a mock phone call to 911 and utilize their skills learned in the beginning of the lesson.  They will complete the Vocabulary Worksheet on the lesson which deals directly with CPR terminology (see appendix D).  In conclusion the students will evaluate themselves using the rubric which they prepared in the beginning of the lesson.



<P><P><HR>


This lesson was deveoped for Kathy Snell's fifth grade class in Parishville-Hopkinton Central School.  It was used as a health science lesson, to aid kids in the better understanding of emergency situations.  </BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
