<html><TITLE>Adirondacks environmental studies semester for first-year students</TITLE><body>
<H2>Adirondacks environmental studies semester for first-year students</H2>
Contact Person:<BR>

John Omohundro, MacVicar 124, 315-267-2053
E-mail: omohunjt@potsdam.edu<P>


	The "Adirondacks" offer a complete semester of five courses taught by a team of professors from various disciplines who share a common environmental studies emphasis and use the Adirondack Park region as case study material. The program investigates the artistic and philosophical questions, the scientific problems, and the social controversies which the Adirondack Park creates for its residents and visitors.<P>

	The "Adirondacks" enrolls 50 first-year (freshman) students who work closely all week with professors and advisers, advanced students, and each other in frequent team projects, labs, field trips and studios. It constitutes a complete semester schedule of approximately 17 credit hours. Because the program stresses coherence and teamwork, it serves students who love art but are less confident about studying the sciences, as well as students who love science but are less confident about studying the arts. It is appropriate for undeclared students as well as those interested in SUNY Potsdams Environmental Sciences and Environmental Studies minors.<P>

	Courses in the package change slightly from year to year, but always include the sciences, social sciences, arts and humanities. The package in fall 1994, for example, featured courses in art history, geology, sociology, literature and writing, and environmental chemistry. Being a complete semester schedule, the program satisfies more than a third of the General Education requirements in an unusually coherent fashion.<P>



<H3>Environmental science minor</H3>

Contact Person:<BR>

Robert Badger, Timerman Hall 230, 315-267-2624
E-mail: badgerrl@potsdam.edu<P>


	Designed primarily for science majors. Some of the following courses have cognate requirements, so the student should check the individual course listing under its department for these prerequisites. A grade of 2.0 or better must be achieved in all courses.<P>


<H4>Science courses</H4>
Four of the following courses, or their equivalent, as approved by the environmental studies committee. One course must be from each of the four sciences.<P>


		
<UL><LI> GEOL-395 	Environmental Problems	3
       or
 GEOL-406	Structural and Field Geology	4
 
<LI> BIOL-300	Ecology	3
 
<LI> PHYS-330	Meterology	3

<LI> CHEM-311	Quantitative Analysis	4
</UL>
<H4>Social Sciences and Humanities courses</H4>
Two of the following courses, or their equivalent, as approved by the environmental studies committee, each from a different department.<P>


<UL><LI> INTD-110	Environmental Issues	4
<LI> SOC-395	Environmental Risks
  and Society	3
<LI> POLS-355	Politics and the Environment	4
<LI> POLS-491	Public Policy Internship	4
<LI> ANTC-155	World Hunger	3
<LI> ANTC-325	Human and Cultural Ecology	3
<LI> ANTC-355	World Food	3
<LI> ECON-411	Natural Resource Economics	3
<LI> PHIL-395	Environmental Ethics	3
</UL>

<H4>Outdoor Experience</H4>
<UL><LI> Star Lake	Outdoor Experience	1
</UL>
			Total	2023<P>



<H3>ENVIRONMENTAL STUDIES MINOR</H3>

Contact Person:<BR>

Robert Badger, Timerman Hall 230, 315-267-2624<P>


	Designed primarily for social sciences and humanities majors. Some of the following courses have cognate requirements, so the student should check the individual course listing under its department for these prerequisites. A grade of 2.0 or better must be achieved in all courses.<P>


<H4>Science courses</H4>
Three of the following courses, or their equivalent, as approved by the environmental studies committee, representing three out of the four sciences. Science majors should consult with the program coordinator for possible substitution of other science courses for the listed non-major science courses.<P>

			
<UL><LI> GEOL-101 	Environmental Geology	3
      or
 GEOL-103	Physical Geology	3
 
<LI> BIOL-106	Environmental Biology	3
 
<LI> PHYS-195	Energy and the Environment	3
      or
<LI> PHYS-330	Meterology	3

<LI>CHEM-395	Chemistry in the Environment	3
</UL>

<H4>Social Sciences and Humanities Courses:</H4>
Three of the following courses, or their equivalent, as approved by the environmental studies committee. At least two of the courses must be upper level, and each course must be from a different department.<P>

			
<UL><LI> INTD-110	Environmental Issues	4
<LI> SOC-395	Environmental Risks 
		and Society	3
<LI> POLS-355	Politics and the Environment	4
<LI> POLS-491	Public Policy Internship	4
<LI> ANTC-155	World Hunger	3
<LI> ANTC-325	Human and Cultural Ecology	3
<LI> ANTC-355	World Food	3
<LI> ECON-411	Natural Resource Economics	3
<LI> PHIL-395	Environmental Ethics	3			
<LI> Outdoor Experience
<LI> Star Lake	Outdoor Experience	1
<LI> 				Total	19-21
</UL>
