<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Feed the World Lesson</Title></HEAD>
<BODY Background="redbkg.gif" TEXT="#FFFFFF">
<FONT SIZE=4>
Nina Teresi<BR>

Lesson Plan - grade 2<BR><P><P>

Materials:<BR><P>
Feeding the World by Janine Amos<BR>
Bread, Bread, Bread by Ann Morris<BR>
Everybody Cooks Rice by Norah Dooley<BR>
How my Parents Learned to Eat Rice by Ina Friedman<BR>
worksheets<BR>
the breads listed in the Bread, Bread, Bread book<BR>
Pencil<BR>
paper<BR>
crayons<BR>
plates<BR>
a rice steamer<BR>
rice<BR>
a world map<BR>
<P><P>
Procedure:<BR><P>
1. Sing - "The World is a Rainbow"  (See attached sheet for the
words).<BR>
2.  Read Feeding the World by Janine Amos and talk about the book.<BR>
3. Read Bread, Bread, Bread by Ann Morris<BR>
4.  Talk about the different types of bread and how no matter where you live in the world everyone eats bread.<BR>
5.  Read Everybody Cooks Rice by Norah Dooley and talk about different ways to ear rice. <BR>
6.  Ask the students what the 7 continents are.  Ask them to point out Asia.  Tell them that we are going to be studying Japan and point it out on the map.<BR> 
7.  and Finally read How my Parents Learned to Eat Rice and talk about the differences between Japanese culture and American<BR>
8.  While these books are being read - the other teacher will be working on getting the rice cooked and the breads cut up.<BR>
9.  Have the students work on the worksheet entitled - Celebrations of Diversity - Have the children color in the pictures and then glue them onto paper with one side being labeled Japan and the other side the United States.<BR>
10. Also have them complete the worksheet entitled - "A world of Numbers" <BR>
11.  When the food is done sit the students in a circle and let them try the different breads and the rice.<BR> 
12.  For the writing activity have the students write 5 facts on the "Japanese Girl" <BR> 
<P><P>
Evaluation: <BR>
The students should be able to list the 5 facts about Japan and tell what two food people eat all over the world.<P>
</Body></HTML>

</DOC>
