<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>MathJournal</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
JOURNAL #1 <BR>
5  September 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I met the students for the first time.  I  think we all were a little nervous. 
 It was a beautiful  day and we went outside to get to know each other.  We played 
a game that helped us all to get to know each other and to see what interests each 
of us.  Since I am assigned to work with the Biology group, I observed the lesson planned. 
 We then did a interest inventory to see what they knew and liked about Biology. 
The time went quickly and they left on the bus.<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #2<BR>
12 September 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I observed the lesson plan done by the Biology group.  The students created 
a make believe city on a river.  They had to name their city and use markers, clay, 
houses and their imaginations to create a city.  I thought they were very interested 
in using their hands to create this project.  Each city was different and I thought the 
lesson a success.<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #3<BR>
18 September 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today was our first field trip at Cranberry Lake.  I had observed the students' mathematics 
class in the morning and rode the bus with them to the site.  Mr. Vandenberg was 
very helpful and I was able to see his discipline management style first hand.  I 
learned a lot today.  I never realized just how many things have to come together just 
to make this trip happen.  It's amazing.  I was in charge of three Biology students 
and we went to a section of the river to choose the quadrants.  We picked a nice 
spot  right off and the students described their quadrants and looked for animals.  I found 
it very interesting.  The Biology team then showed the students how to use a kick 
net.  The day was a success.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
 JOURNAL #4<BR>
19 September 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today we met with the students in Potsdam.  We had all the frogs and all the animals 
we found in Dr. Doody's office.  We had to classify where they all fit in the field 
guides.  Some of the animals escaped during the evening hours.  The students had 
fun classifying the animals that were left.  We then went to the outside classroom to continue 
the discussion on structural relationships.  They were more difficult to keep on 
task when we were outdoors.  I discussed mathematical ways to describe their quadrants and asked them about graphs and charts.  We discussed several different types of 
charts and graphs.  <BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #5<BR>
25 September 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today is another field trip! We went to Fine.  I was at Gouverneur Central School 
early in the morning to observe and assist Mrs. Whitton in her 7th grade mathematics 
class.  I caught the bus with the students.  The trip was shorter this time.  It 
was another beautiful day. We again picked out our quadrants  and the students started their 
journal writing.  They seem to really enjoy the writing this time with a little coaxing. 
 They found more animals and plants and had a great time catching the frogs.  Some of my students were a little more wet than they were last time.  We discussed Invasive 
Species.  I really learned a lot.<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #6<BR>
2 October 1996<BR>
<BR>
I observed Mrs. Whitton in the morning  and rode on the bus with the students to the 
Richville Bridge.  Today was fun but it really tested my discipline ability.  Two 
out of three students actually fell in the river.  One student fell in by accident 
and one was showing off for his girlfriend.  I was glad that no one was hurt.  I really 
had to coaxe them to write in their journals to describe their quadrant.  We then 
all got together to discuss succession and Miss Fobare showed us a gall ball.  I 
was very interested in the material presented.  Miss Plemons also caught a huge bullfrog and 
that was the highlight of the day.  I have never seen one close up before.  There 
were so many frogs around that we had a frog race.  Another fun day!<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #7<BR>
9 October 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today was our trip to Ogdensburg.  It was colder today so we really had to keep moving. 
 I can't believe the difference in the water.  This site is very close to the Canadian 
border and you can see the ships on the St. Lawrence go by.  This is the mouth of the Oswegatichie River.  The students went right to work finding their quadrants 
and describing them in their journals.  They also found mussels and frogs.  We discussed 
the animals we found and then found we had extra time.  We had races and played tag. 
 I had fun and had some time to really talk to the students.  <BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #8    <BR>
17 October 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I taught the students in Potsdam about charts and tables and did a mathematical 
interest inventory for part of the class.  The interest inventory really helped me 
to see what they have learned so far and what to concentrate on in the future.  They 
then played a dice game to create a table of the information.  I had them work in groups. 
 They seemed to like it and I think it was review for the 8th graders.  I let them 
pick their own partners and they worked well together.  I had to stop a little early 
as I shared the class with Miss Plemons.<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #9<BR>
23 October 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I observed Mrs. Whitton's class and used her room to teach my class on mean, 
median and mode in the afternoon.  I used stations so that the students had to move 
around the room.  I think they had a good time.  Station #1 was map reading.  Station 
#2 was measuring.  Station #3 was interpreting charts and graphs.  The students were 
a little loud but I think they got the idea of mean, median and mode.  I shared my 
class time with Mrs. Rivera who teaches Drug Studies to the students.  I thought 
her teaching techniques were excellent.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #10<BR>
30 October 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I taught another math class to the students about more about Graphing.  We actually 
continued with the previous lesson because we ran out of time.  I had them create 
any of the graphs we learned about using the materials I brought.  They did not seem at all interested in doing this activity and I really had to coaxe them to complete 
it.  A couple of the students were arguing and there seemed to be something wrong. 
 They completed the project and went back to class to complete their homework.  I 
felt down after this lesson but Mr. Vandenberg said that some days are bad when the students 
have a bad day.  It was a good experience for me.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #11<BR>
20 November 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today we went on a field trip back to Cranberry Lake.  It was freezing cold and the 
students were eager to get back on the bus after we did our activities.  First we 
found our original quadrants and logged our descriptions in the journals.  The students 
were amazed at the differences in their quadrants.  Some of the students were done early 
and they started skating on the ice with their boots.  I took a lot of pictures. 
  They were having a blast.  Miss Plemons had us pick garbage to clean up the environment and we found quite a bit.  I must say it looked much better after.<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #12<BR>
3 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I went to see Mrs. Rivera teach the students Drug Studies.  I really enjoy watching 
her style and I get a lot of teaching ideas from her.  She had the students practice 
refusal skills and I was able to practice with the students.  She then had them role play with each other and promised to have a video camera the next time to tape 
them.  I helped the students with their mathematics homework afterwards for a short 
time.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
JOURNAL #13<BR>
4 DECEMBER 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today we went back to the Richville Bridge to reexamine our quadrants.  The students 
saw that their quadrants were totally submerged. They didn't even want to write in 
their journals.  It was also cold and they were running around to keep warm  Miss 
Fobare gave us a scavenger hunt to complete.  We got in pairs and had a contest to see who 
would win.  This was the greatest activity.  We went all around to complete our sheets 
and the competition was close.  My group won and we learned much in the process. 
 I will never forget the terms we learned today because it was all hands-on.  For bonus 
points we picked up garbage and got a huge pile.  I left with a great feeling.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
 <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
      
</BODY>
