<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>PROJECT OSWEGATCHIE RIVER</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Water Quality Unit<BR>
Lesson Plan 10<BR>
Pedagogy</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior <BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>


This section is being revised into the above displayed task analysis format.  Please bear with us during this change.  Feel free to look over our thoughts listed below for a full description of our pedagogy according to the New Science Education <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/3.html">Teaching</A> and<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/5.html#as"> Assessment</A> Standards.  Thank you.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>



The students will be describing the potential effects of plastic waste on aquatic 
life.  This lesson is
further continuation of our examination of pollution.  To encourage greater understanding 
of the amount of plastic waste polluting the environment the students will be cleaning 
up the river area visited that Wednesday. <P>

The following Thursday we will be
examining and calculating the amount of waste per area.  The students have been performing 
a litter patrol at each river site throughout our examination of the river, we now
want to take this collection one step further to establish how much trash gets dumped 
in a unit area over a specific time period.  No introduction is necessary in this 
situation due to the fact that we have been discussing this type of pollution during 
our continuous litter patrol activity.<P>


The collected trash from the previous Wednesday should be saved and brought in for 
Thursdays activity.  The students will be working all together at first to obtain 
initial data, they will then be split into smaller groups and we will be installing 
a jigsaw cooperative learning method.  Three small groups will be formed with three 
students 
each, if the groups are uneven, a teacher needs to represent a member of the group; 
one group will perform the calculations, another group will brainstorm, identify, 
and list potential effects of plastic waste on aquatic life, the last group will be 
working 
on an active plan they can put into action that can help to remedy the pollution 
problem in addition to recycling.  These initial groups will be given 15 to 20 minutes 
to complete their individual projects in this activity.  One member from each initial 

group will join a single member from each of the other groups to form a new unit 
of three with a representative from each initial group.  Each member will teach the
other members of the new group the information they calculated, discussed, or worked 
on. 
 Allow 15 to 20 minutes for the new groups to teach each other the information.<P>


Before splitting into groups:
Have the students separate the plastic trash from the paper trash - the students  
   <!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4>MUST</FONT> 
wear gloves!  Encourage all the students to make a mental list of the     different 
things they collected that had been discarded and was polluting the     environment.
<P>

Split the students into three groups, join a group yourself if necessary.<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Group 1: Performing the calculations</FONT><BR>
Have the students mass the trash collected.  They can mass plastic then  paper 
and combine the masses, or they can mass all the trash as one unit.      The units 
the students need to use is grams or kilograms.  The students should know the 
dimensions of the area cleaned, if they do not refresh their     memories from you 
notebook
where you have recorded the information. Using the length and width dimensions, 
the students will calculate the area  using the units meters squared.  The mass 

should be divided by the area to give a final answer of g/m2.  Do not simply spell 
out these steps to the  students.  Tell the students the 
units they want in the end and let them  design a method to analyze the trash
that will give them the needed answer.     If they get stuck, start them off and
allow them more time to proceed from  there.<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Group 2: Potential effects of plastic waste on aquatic life</FONT><BR>
    More guidelines will be given to this group.  The students should      brainstorm 
for a few minutes to determine three effects the trash can have on    the wildlife, 
a list should be constructed by each student recording the     possibilities.  Have 
the students categorize the collected trash on their papers, underneath the 
ideas collected through brainstorming, using three headings relating the collected 
trash to the effect the trash has on wildlife as food. The students  will also 
categorize the trash under similar headings describing the likelihood of wildlife 
becoming tangled in the trash.  The headings to use are :<BR>
								<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Very likely to be perceived as food<BR>
								<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Somewhat likely to be perceived as food<BR>
								<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Unlikely to be perceived as food<BR>

Have the students compare these to given categories with the ideas they developed 
during brainstorming.<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Group 3:  The active plan to help remedy the pollution problem</FONT><BR>
Have the students discuss what actions they can do to help prevent the     pollution 
of the environment.  The students can discuss recycling, but they     must come up 
with an additional method besides recycling.  The students should brainstorm 
to develop a plan they can put into action.  The plan does not need to be elaborate, 
the simpler their plan is the easier it will be to implement their plan.  Each 
student should write out the plan they have devised.    <P>


After the groups have been given ample time to complete their projects, have one member 
from each group form a new group with a single member from each of the other groups. 
 The students will teach the other two members of this new group about the project 
they have just worked on.  Each student should present their portion of the activity 
in about 5 - 6 minutes. <P>

 In closure, give the students time to free - write in their 
journals about their feelings on recycling and personally cleaning up their environment.<P>


If time permits or a student is particularly interested in what they can personally 
do to help their environment assign or encourage investigations in the following 
areas:<BR>

					<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Establish school litter patrol with designated clean-up areas and schedules.<BR>
					<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Investigate what Gouverneur does to recycle plastics and other materials.<BR>
					<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Investigate processes for making plastic biodegradable including any new technology. 
<BR>
							<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Investigate local, state and federal laws which address pollution problems.

</BODY>
</HTML>
