<BODY BACKGROUND="greyone.gif">
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>PROJECT OSWEGATCHIE RIVER</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Water Quality Testing<BR>
Lesson Plan 2<BR>
Pedagogy</CENTER></FONT><P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>
<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>

This section is being revised into the above displayed task analysis format.  Please bear with us during this change.  Feel free to look over our thoughts listed below for a full description of our pedagogy according to the New Science Education <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/3.html">Teaching</A> and<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/5.html#as"> Assessment</A> Standards.  Thank you.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>


This lesson focuses a great deal on communication and working together with our colleagues 
(and superiors).  Dr. Maria Hepel has agreed to give a tour of her Quantitative Analysis 
laboratory.  This laboratory is where the water samples from each test site on the 
test Wednesday will be taken to test for heavy metals.  All the students should 
have a overview of the lab before they are taken there as a team to actually perform 

the test.  Each team will have a chance to explore the lab in more detail when they 
have their turn in the lab during their rotation thru that series of tests.<P>
This activity is the extended activity for Thursday after testing Cranberry Lake, 
our first test site, and it involves a close tour of the Quantitative Lab where the 
students will be completing the analysis of heavy metals in the water.  After arriving
at Potsdam the students will be given a brief description of a quantitative lab.  
The 
students need to be informed of the equipment they will be seeing, as well as cautioned 
to be very careful while in the lab because much of the equipment is very fragile 
and expensive.  We want to explain to the students how heavy metals are tested in 
real-life 
industry and research settings.  It should be emphasized to the students that what 
they will be viewing is a research laboratory.  The students should be brought over 
to the lab and Dr. Maria Hepel will be giving them the tour.<P>


After the visit to the lab the students will be given an opportunity to record their 
ideas and observations of the lab in their journal.  Time can be given right after 
the tour or the journal writing can be a homework assignment if time is getting short 
for the class.  Another homework assignment that needs to be addressed is a Thank 
You 
note from the students to Dr. Hepel for the tour she set up for us.  Different extended 
activities may be performed, as time sees fit, to explore even more the effects of 
heavy metals.  <P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">The students can go to the library to do some research of their own.  The students 
can use the library computers to access the Internet; they can   explore the effects 
of heavy metals on animals if ingested.  <P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">The students can list two heavy metals we will be exploring during our testing   
of 
the river, research those metals, again using the Internet, and find out   any dangers 
that may exist from having those metals in the water system.  <P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">The students can create a food web indicating any places on the web where heavy 
metals may enter into the food chain.  The food chain will allow the   students to 
visualize the effect a heavy metal can have on an enormous amount of animal life 
if it is entered into the food chain at the bottom of the chain.<P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">The students can be taken on a brief tour of the Scanning Electron Microscope lab 
and they can take computerized photographs of their water samples,   if the water 
samples contain any heavy metals.  If none of the samples contain heavy metals, 
the Scanning Electron Microscope can be observed and previously prepared slides 
can be 
used.<P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">The students can perform a heavy metal analysis on a sample of rock collected from 
Cranberry Lake.  The students can devise an experiment that would   imitate acid
rain falling against the rock, washing mercury into the water.    They can test a 
water sample gathered from water washed against the rock collected from Cranberry 
Lake. <P>
 This experiment can effectively be used to blow up an experimental finding into 
a piece of information relevant to an actual body of water.  Using proportionality 
have the students expand the findings of 1 liter of water washed against the   
 mercury 
rock compared to the volume of the lake which washes up against the rocks regularly.<P>
We are encouraging active learning on the part of the student.  They are totally responsible 
for the information they are exploring - we will be there to guide them in their 
searches but the gathering of information is entirely up to the student.  Any information 
they find in their research should be recorded in their journal and a paper
may be assigned.  The students will be presenting the data they are finding to the 
biology group in their regular class with Mike.<P>
To wrap up the lesson, review for a few minutes with the class the importance of 
testing heavy metals.  Summarize the techniques learned on the tour about methods 
used in a research laboratory to test for heavy metals.  Emphasize that the students 
will all be using the lab to test their own water samples from the different sites. 
<P>
 Cap 
the activities that were chosen for the day, and tie those activities into our search 
for heavy metals in the water system.  Explain why we feel it is important that we 
know what heavy metals exist in the water that we drink and that animals we might 
eat 
drink.<BR>

