<HEAD>
<TITLE>pedsix.html - Converted</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../Stacey and Tyna/river/chem//greyone.gif"><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>PROJECT OSWEGATCHIE RIVER</CENTER></FONT><P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Water Quality Unit<BR>
Lesson Plan 6<BR>
Pedagogy</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>



<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior <BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>


This section is being revised into the above displayed task analysis format.  Please bear with us during this change.  Feel free to look over our thoughts listed below for a full description of our pedagogy according to the New Science Education <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/3.html">Teaching</A> and<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/5.html#as"> Assessment</A> Standards.  Thank you.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>


The lesson we have designed for this week was specifically designed to encourage an 
understanding in the student about how much water actually effects their life and 
lifestyles. <P>

 On the first day the students will be tracing their domestic water supply 
to its source prior to human use and to its destination after use.  We want the students 
to understand the potential problems to water habitats following human use of the 
water.<P>

To open this lesson, have the students construct a drawing or art piece that 
demonstrates their domestic water source and the destination of the water after usage. 
 Each student will be doing an individual diagram, they may work closely with each 
other allowing for feedback from their peers but each student must have a diagram 
of their own personal water cycle. <P>
 Brainstorm with the students while 
they are working 
on their diagrams, about the different sources that are available around the county;
the students should be able to identify the village water, private wells, and 
small community wells.<P>


After the students have completed their diagrams have them identify at least 3 potential 
effects from human usage of the water.  Encourage the students to really get involved 
in considering all the effects their personal water use may have on the environment 
around them.  The visual aid of the diagram will allow the students to actually 
see where the water they are using is going, where it will end up, and what habitat 
along the way could be effected.  The students should consider the effects on both 
terrestrial and aquatic habitats; they should be considering detrimental effects to 
animal 
and plant life due to human contamination.  Have the students discuss the different 
habitats that their domestic usage is affecting; what animals and plants are indigenous 
to that area that they may be hurting.  <P>

The students, as a group, should come up 
with 3 potential effects on the habitats they have discussed.  Once the students
have identified these 3 problems, have them identify at least 2 solutions.  Again 
as a large group, have the students evaluate possible solutions to the problems they 
have suggested. 
 The solutions the students come up with should involve responsible water use, such 
as conservation of water and usage of chemicals in cleaning that are environmentally 
safe.<P>


Upon completion of the initial activity which is used to catch the students interest 
in how humans effect the water system, we want the students to investigate how the 
waste water is transported by the sewer system.  The students will be investigating 
whether the Gouverneur sewer system is a separate or combined sewer system. <P>

 Before 
initializing 
the investigation, hand out the worksheets describing septic systems and municipal 
waste water treatment.  Have the students break up into small groups of two or three 
and review their diagrams of their personal domestic use.  The students need 
to add to the diagram whether they are using a septic system or a municipal waste 
water system.  Have them describe briefly, on the diagram, what differences the type 
of waste system used has on contamination.    Have the students include on the diagram 
the
different household products that get washed down the drains, or flushed down the 
toilets.  The students should list at least 5 household hazards directly on the diagram continually adding to their diagrams will allow even more of a visual understanding. 
<P>


Bring the students back together and begin a group investigation into the waste water 
treatment program used in Gouverneur.  The students will recognize quickly that Gouverneur 
uses a municipal waste water system and not a septic system, have them verbally announce 
their recognition of this fact.  Have the students decide whether the system
is separate or combined based on the handouts.  Go over with the students the types 
of treatment performed on the water when it has entered a treatment plant - primary, 
secondary, and tertiary stages.<P>


At this point, wrap up the discussion by recapping the activities performed - discuss 
briefly the diagrams created by the students, tie in the different types of waste 
treatments available and announce that the class will be attending the waste water 
treatment plant the next day. <P>


The following Thursday will be dedicated to a tour of the Gouvernuer waste water treatment 
plant.  After the tour, if time permits, discuss with the students the local guidelines 
they have learned about detailing septic system construction and maintenance; discuss 
the stages the local municipal treatment plant uses.  Have the students
discuss possible consequences if the guidelines are not met, possible questions to 
initiate the discussion are:<P>
is it against the law to construct below standard systems?<BR>
what is the jail sentence for such an act?<BR>
how do below standard systems affect the environment in general?<BR>
how would below standard systems in Gouvernuer effect the local habitat?<BR>
 how would the contamination due to these below standard systems affect the
  data we are collecting at the river?

</BODY>
