<HEAD>
<TITLE>pedone.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="greyone.gif">
</BODY>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Project Oswegatchie River</CENTER></FONT><BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Water Quality Testing<BR>
Lesson Plan 1</CENTER></FONT><BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Pedagogy</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1</FONT><BR>

Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>



<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2</FONT><BR>

Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3</FONT><BR>

Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>




<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>
This section is being revised into the above displayed task analysis format.  Please bear with us during this change.  Feel free to look over our thoughts listed below for a full description of our pedagogy according to the New Science Education <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/3.html">Teaching</A> and<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/5.html#as"> Assessment</A> Standards.  Thank you.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>

The students are required to test the river at different sites every other week.  
These tests will be accumulated to achieve an overall picture of the health of the 
river and the impact of the river on all aspects of life.   Our long term goal for 
the semester is to achieve greater understanding on the part of the student concerning 
the 
impact of river on their lives and the community in which they live.  The completion 

of each set of nine tests at each site during the course of the semester (some sites 

will be visited more than once) are the short term goals we have set for each team 
of 
students.  The details of  the different aspects of the water quality testing will 

be our focus during the off weeks when we do not visit the river.<BR>
The learning that takes place must come from the student, not from us as lecturers. 

  The students will be learning for themselves; as they dispel incorrect theories 

and build upon correct theories the students will be learning for themselves every 

step of the way.  We want to introduce water quality testing to the students by allowing 

them to brainstorm about what they already know about water quality testing, which 

ideas  are misconceptions and which ideas are a good foundation to start from. <BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#0000FF">Questions to facilitate discussion:</FONT><P>
What is water quality?<BR>
How can we go about finding out what the water quality of a particular    river is?<BR>
Why should we bother learning about the water quality of a river?<BR>
How does water affect our lives?<BR>
How does the Oswegatchie River relate to their lives?<BR>
How do impurities and pollutants in the water affect those daily     interactions 
with water?<P>

We want the students to visualize all the ways the water touches their lives.  We 
can start by allowing the students to assess their own preconceptions.  How true 
were those preconceptions?  The students should question all the areas of impact 
the river plays in their lives.   <BR>
One of the activities we have planned to engage the students directly into exploring 

the river is to examine a topographical map and discuss which parts of the river
would be most appropriate for testing and why.  The students should start understanding 

here the effects of different geography and industry on the river.  Are industrialized 

areas of importance?  Are farming communities important?  Does  the starting point 

and ending point of the river have any importance?  The students should come up with 

their own set of guidelines about which parts of the river they would test if it was 

entirely up to them.  Besides just looking at the sites of the river, encourage the 

students to look at and discuss how often testing should be done.  Is just one test 

appropriate?  Is testing every site every week a feasible solution?  After they have 
come 
up with sites and reasons why those sites were chosen, as well as looked at a possible 

time schedule, we will disclose the sites and test dates we chose and let the students 
see for themselves how very right they were to make the choices they did.  We will 

discuss all of their suggestions to stress the importance of brainstorming, contributing 

and analyzing a situation from many viewpoints, many which will be different from 
another.<BR>
The river is a very important aspect of these students lives.  Choosing to plan our 

unit around such a factor in their lives allows us to pull in their interests into 

the sciences as we explore something they are already excited about.  The students 

will be required to keep a thorough journal every time we explore an aspect of the 
river
- through activities or when we actually visit the river.  We will be looking for 

them to record their thoughts about the topic of the day.  The journal is to be a 

sounding board, a device they can use to place their personal thoughts about the project 
we 
are working on.  The journal will also be used explicitly during the test days to 

record information before and after the testing - the actual data as it is collected, 
the data collected by their peers, and the answers to any specific questions posed 
to 
the students about the water testing done for that day.  The specific questions to 

be given to the students will aid the students in bringing together the concepts 
we are focusing on concerning water quality.<BR>
A second activity involves taking the students down to Lehman Park with the water 

quality kits and demonstrating, using student models, how to perform the nine different 

tests.  The use of student models rather than having them simply watch us perform 

the tests will keep the students' attention focused to what we are trying to do.  
Watching 
a demonstration is exactly like sitting and listening to a lecture, and that is exactly 

what we wish to avoid.  By rotating through all the students with us and asking each 
student, or pair of students, to come up and perform the test under the direction 

of the teacher will allow for student involvement and keep the attention level high. 

 To start off the demonstrations, volunteers should be requested, if it appears that 
a trend is beginning that might qualify as substantiating stereotypes, we should 

prompt certain students to volunteer for the next demonstration to break up that 
trend.  It is imperative that the students performing the different test demonstrations 

be random.  We must be very careful not to expand upon a stereotype unintentionally, 
having 
only males to perform the most difficult tests would be an example of this. <P>


* The above portion of the lesson plan should be conducted on our first Thursday meeting. <P>

 At the end of the class meeting we will close the lesson by forming the teams to 

perform the two sets of tests.  Two sets of tests have been categorized and therefore 
two testing teams will be formed.  The two sets of tests consist of the following 

- 1) Dissolved Oxygen, BOD, Fecal Coliform, Turbidity, and Total Solids;       and <BR>
2) pH, Temperature, Total Phosphates, and Nitrates.  The formation of the testing 
teams was determined from the information we collected about the interests of the 
students
using the questionnaire.  Preliminary group formations were submitted to Mike for 

approval to assure that we have not paired up any cliches or students who cannot 
work together.  <BR>
The following pedagogy applies to the testing performed at the river 8 of the 14 weeks.<P>

We will be visiting the test sites on Wednesdays every other week starting September 
11.  The teams have already been chosen and assigned so the students are all set 
to get to the site and begin testing.  Data sheets should be handed out to the students 

on the bus before they arrive to the test site, or when we all arrive at the test 

site.  These data sheets list explicit team jobs and the names of the students assigned 
to a particular job for that test site should be filled in accordingly.  Each test 

site on the river consists of two separate testing spots in order to have a compare 

and contrast opportunity; two data sheets should be given to each group for recording 

of data.  The following Thursday after the data collection the students will be coming 

to Potsdam  to continue any tests that take longer than the 2 hours available on 
Wednesday, to share their test results with each other, to input the data into the 

computer system and determine a water quality index for the site examined.  These 
Thursdays 
may also include additional activities to allow for further exploration of different 

aspects connecting outside influences and water quality.  These additional lesson 

activities can be found in numerical order in the unit plan.<BR>
The most important step emphasized throughout the lessons is the socialization of 

these students as an active, working group.  Every week used to visit and directly 

test the river emphasizes the importance in working together as a cohesive unit.
 We also want to emphasize real-world working relationships especially in the scientific 
field. 
 The students will be learning how to work together and depend upon each other in 

order to complete the assigned tasks.  The students will be split into even groups 

of 4 students to form two separate teams.  Each team will consist of different jobs. 

There will be a manager, a coach, a tracker, and a communicator.  Every week that 

the river is visited these jobs will be rotated amongst the members of the group. 

 We want to de-emphasize any stereotyping among the students about who should be performing 

which job while emphasizing the cooperation of the group in order for all the tasks 

to be done.  The students will be taking turns, during following weeks, at performing 

all of the tasks in the group.  Such rotation means that one week a student will be 
the 
coach, the next week that same student may be the tracker, the following week the 

same student may be assigned the position of communicator and so on until each student 

has been assigned each job and then the rotation begins all over again.  Each student 

will be held directly responsible for the tasks assigned him/her depending on their 

particular job that week - it is imperative that the students understand that they 

are to perform only the jobs they are assigned to do that week; the students should 
not 
try to take over a job which they like better or feel more comfortable doing.  We 

have designed this so that each student can get a feel for every job, we also want 

the students to see that each job in the group has it's own unique importance, as 
do they.<BR>
Besides switching jobs every week, the students will also be switching tests every 

2 weeks or so.  We don't want some of the students to become superior at one set 
of tests and lack knowledge in the other 4 or 5 tests being done by the others.  
The students will perform one set of 4 or 5 tests then switch and perform the other 
set, switching 
back and forth about every two weeks.  It is important that not only do the students 

learn about the different jobs available to them within the test group but they also 
learn about the importance of all the different types of tests being performed 
by them as a large group with one goal - to achieve an accurate measurement of the 

water quality of the river.  The groups will be taking 3 samples at each test site 

to increase our accuracy.  An average of these 3 samples will be reported during the 
group 
discussion and this average will be the figure recorded into the computer.  Although 

an average is being used later on, all data from each of the three samples needs 
to be recorded on the data sheets.<P>


A typical Wednesday would be scheduled as follows:<BR>
-meet students at Gouverneur and travel with them to the test site<BR>
-observe the attendance for the teams and assign jobs according to how many team 
members are there (if a student is absent some jobs  may need to be doubled to 
ensure that everything is done) and according to which positions the student has 

previously been assigned.  Record these assignments yourself and observe the   
 students 
throughout the day to ensure that they are performing only the jobs assigned to 

them for that day.<BR>
-announce that the students must record in their journals the weather    conditions 
for the day, and record them yourself for future use in    assessment.<BR>
-hand out the Water Quality Data Sheet and have each student fill out the top of 

the sheet which lists the jobs in the group as well as description of the job 

to be performed by the member assigned that position.  The name of each student 

assigned to the particular task for that week should be filled in accordingly.<BR>
-begin and finish tests assigned to each group, the fecal coliform and    BOD tests 

will not be completely finished on the original test date,    these two tests should 

be given to a student teacher so it can be brought to Potsdam for the following 

day<BR>
- have the students all come back together as one group and assign areas near and 

around the river to have the students clean up.  They will  be performing a litter 

patrol every week.  In week 10 we will be saving the collected trash for 
furthur use on the following Thursday.<BR>
-return to Gouverneur with students via bus <P>


Thursday following the test day at the river the students will be traveling to Potsdam. 

 The two remaining test will be finished, if possible, and the last data recorded 

into the data sheet.  The groups will get back together and share the data they recorded, 
today and the previous day, with their peers.  The tracker or tracker/communicator 

from each team will record the data they collected to the computer file so that is 

accessible to everyone.  In order for the tracker to transfer the data from notebook 

to computer, Q charts must be used to convert the collected data into data the computer 

will understand and apply to the existing formula.  There are four sets of the Q 
charts laminated for just this purpose.  Each team should receive a set of the Q 
charts to accurately analyze their data.  After that, together as one large group, 
we will 
use all the collected data to come up with a total water quality value for that particular 

test site.  Bringing the students back together into the larger group helps to emphasize 
the importance each test team brings to the whole picture.  We cannot obtain 
an accurate water quality index without the data collected from each team.  <BR>
The students are again facilitating their own learning as they listen and present 

their findings for the day to each other.  An open discussion should be initiated 

so the students can question us and each other about the findings they have from 
the test site.  Comparisons to previous data is very much encouraged - if the discussion 
does
not appear to head in that direction a bit of guidance should be used.  We also want 

to emphasize the importance of social skills in this atmosphere.  The students should 

be learning and maintaining a courteous behavior throughout all the presentations. 

 The students will expect everyone to be quiet during their presentations and it 
is only fair for them to remain silent as well during their peers' presentations. 
<BR>
In closing, comment upon the findings that were collected the previous day and today. 

 The data collected this week should be compared to and linked with the data collected 

in previous weeks to emphasize that a bigger picture then this single test site exists. 
 After focusing so much on this short term goal of finishing the testing for 
this particular site, we need to draw the attention of the student back to the larger 

picture of the river as a whole.  Any questions and comments from the students should 

be addressed at this time before dismissal.<P>



