<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>melisone.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Gov. Journal #1<BR>
Monday Sept. 9, 1996<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
My first day of teaching is over.  I found myself to be extremely nervous, even though 
I wasn't by myself.  When I first began talking to the class, my nervousness was 
evident.  I'm not sure if it was because I was with Ms. Fobare, or because it was 
my first time in front of an entire class, instead of only one student.  After the first 
ten minutes or so, my nervousness came to pass, but I still felt very awkward in 
front of them.  Another thing I  am not so keen on is the fact that the majority 
of my instruction focused on straight lecture.  I could sense the boredom, even though I was 
asking the students for their thoughts.  The instant pleasure was evident when Ms. 
Fobare asked them to practice using a field guide, by identifying the various plants 
she had brought in.  They loved it and it was reflected in the quality of work they did.<BR>
I am very excited to begin the "real" lesson plans.  Today was only an introductory 
and I have to admit, quite boring.  I believe that once the kids begin the actual 
Hands-on activities, they will find it much more enjoyable, because I certainly will. 
 They really are a great bunch of kids, with only a few minor problems, which I assume 
will be ironed out eventually.  There is only one that I am seriously worried about 
and I don't think it will disappear without some hard work and patience.  Maybe a 
lot of hurt feelings along the way too.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, I think this is going to work out just fine in the long run.  I had my doubts 
in the beginning, but once you actually get with the students and interact on a personal 
level, it suddenly becomes clear that they are just as vulnerable as we are- if not more so.<BR>
<CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="melistwo.html">Journal 2</A></CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>
