<TITLE>melisthr.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Journal #3<BR>
Monday Sept. 23,1996<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Today went well, considering that I had a terrible headache.The students were very 
cooperative though.  They settled down in only a few minutes and I guess you could 
say that they didn't misbehave too terribly.  I did tell them that I had a headache 
and that I wanted no fooling around so we could get the lesson over in under an hour.  But 
they must not have wanted to leave me, because it took us an hour and a half to finish 
the whole thing.  I am impressed by how well they work in groups.  I really only 
had to talk to one student about how to work in the group, and he promised to try, but 
I have to reread about how to teach the social skills necessary for cooperative learning. 
 Also, I was surprised by the intensity of work that a particular student performed today.  Usually he always fools around, but I now know that he can do that level 
of work and I expect it from him every day. <BR>
<BR>
The major aspect of today's work was the talk afterward with Mr. Vandenberg.  He suggested 
that I use a rubric scale to hang over the students heads when they started acting 
up.  He said that grades were extremely important to the students and that it stressed the importance of actually doing the work, instead of slacking to get by on as 
little as possible.  I don't know if Rita and Donna are going to do it, but I certainly 
am, even in the field.  I also didn't realize that our grades that we give them determine a huge amount of their grade for Mike's class.  I am starting to get a bit more 
organized through this whole thing and am anticipating the "under control" feeling. 
 My biggest hopes are that the rubric will force them to take this "class" seriously.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, I would like to express my feelings about the field trip to Cranberry Lake 
last Wednesday.  I could literally feel the excitement and enthusiasm from the kids. 
 They put their whole heart and sole into the trip, and actually went above and beyond 
the call of duty by getting right into the water and soaking their pants up to their 
knees.  I wish we could get them like that in the classroom.<BR>
<CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="melisfor.html">Journal 4</A></CENTER><BR>

</BODY>
