<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Journal #6<BR>
Thursday October 17, 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today I am "subbing" for Donna.  Her husband is in the hospital, therefore she is 
unable to teach and asked me if I would.  So, I did and was in disbelief at how unruly 
they were.  Valerie had them for the first 45 minutes, and I was in and out of her 
class several times.  They were not bouncing off the walls for her as they did for me. 
 The difference may be attributable to the fact that she did an actual lesson, and 
I had them play a game as a method of review for a test we are giving them on Monday. 
 They were loud and obnoxious, and very antsy to leave.  They lined up at the door before 
they left- I felt that maybe I had done something to make them want to leave so bad.<BR>
The game was fun though.  I thought maybe a little competition between groups would 
be good; they played the game in their groups and boy were they blurting out the 
answer.  Although I had told them that they could discuss the answers with their 
partners, they rarely did.  One time I heard a student say to her partner, "You can talk to 
me about it ya know".  That was good, but they shouldn't have to be reminded that 
they are allowed to do it as partners.  I'm sure it is only because they are not 
accustomed to working with other people, and that the routine of it will only become second 
nature when they do it over and over. <BR>
I am surprised that they didn't moan about the Exam when I announced it.  They were 
only given 1 days notice (it was supposed to be given on Friday, but I just found 
out that Mike is taking them to a farm, so they won't be in school).  I had a study 
guide prepared for them, and they accepted that without any complaints, considering it 
was rather lengthy.  I am curious about their performance on the test.  You can always 
pick out the few that you know will do well, but I also expect to be surprised by 
some too!<BR>
<CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="milessev.html">Journal 7</A></CENTER>
</BODY>
