<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Journal #7<BR>
Monday October 21, 1996<BR>
<BR>
I was bowled over today!!!  The students were given a test that I had all set up before 
they entered the room.  When they got in the room, several began reading all the 
questions that were taped on the desk.  Maybe first I better explain how the test 
was implemented:  There were twenty questions, one question on each index card.  Several 
of the questions required you to look at various objects (zebra mussel, exoskeleton, 
a branch with leaves that needed to be identified, and a plant that had tiny balls 
on it which contained a worm inside it). Each desk was considered a "station" and the 
students were spread throughout the room at various stations.  They were given three 
minutes at each station and then they had to switch.  I created problems for myself 
when I didn't arrange the cards in order throughout the room.  I ran out of room, so I 
put them along the sides and up front, they basically lost their order then.  Next, 
when I told them to move, I told them to go to the station at their right.  Well, 
some of them did not have a station to their right, so I tried to get them all rotating the 
same way.  They got all screwed up when they got to the front of the room- instead 
of going to the very back, they went to the row behind it.  It  finally got to the 
point where each person had to search for questions they had not already answered.  I was 
confused even.  At the end, some people had already finished, while others still 
had two or three questions left.  Regardless,  that wasn't the worst of it.<BR>
There was one student who thought the test was a joke!  He kept clicking his pen, 
talking about the answers, laughing at other people, and fooling around at his seat. 
 I was amazed at how flippantly he was processing this test.  I finally got to the 
point where I took his test away from him and threatened to tear it up.  Well, he got mad 
and shouted that he didn't care, and other things, which slip my mind.  I had no 
idea how to handle the situation, so I gave him another chance and told him that 
the next time he was after school.  The next time, I took him right to Mike.  Mike was with 
him awhile and then he brought him back- and he still continued to be disruptive. 
 I was in disbelief by this time.  Then the other students got mad because I was 
hollering at them for something only one person  had done.  But, it wasn't just one person, 
they all began to joke and fool around.  I got so frustrated that I ended up in a 
lecture, which wasted my time that I had prepared for an introduction.  I was just 
flustered beyond all ends!  The bell finally rang, and I gave them their homework, which I 
didn't get to explain to them, or cover the material they needed to complete the 
homework.  I told them this and also explained to them that it was their own fault 
they didn't get to cover the necessary material.<BR>
At the end I gave them the opportunity to comment on my method of teaching, whether 
they liked the class or not and any suggestions they might have.  I expected to get 
some brown- nosing, which I did, but I also got some serious information which was 
right, and I definitely need to work on some things.<BR>
Mike spoke to me after class and suggested that I not let my frustration show.  A 
possible solution to this would be to just remain quiet and put them on the clock. 
 This would give me the chance to recollect myself and also punish the students by 
having them lose time for the time they continue to talk and to take away my time.  I will 
try this because my method does not work!  I have noticed that the more frustrated 
I get, the more the students act up.  Maybe if they feel that they aren't bothering 
me, they will give up!  <BR>
I feel discouraged, especially about my ability to teach, because I don't want to 
ruin the opportunities for the students.  But then I think that it was just a bad 
day and that I will learn from my mistakes.<BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="meliseig.html">Journal 8</A></H4>

</BODY>
