<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritaeigh.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Wednesday, October 2nd</STRONG>
<BR>
<BR>
Today we went on a field trip to Richville. The initial part of the day when the students 
chose a quadrant and described it in their journals went very well. The students 
are continually improving in their journal writing. Everyone gets really involved 
in trying to find living organisms now. Ms. Plemmons found a large bull frog but eventually 
lost it. It was histerical watching the students trying to recatch the frog before 
it reached the water. While we had the bull frog, it started to make a crying noise as a defense tactic and it startled the kids. That led into a nice discussion on 
how animals protect themselves. I think Mrs. Plemmons was more disappointed than 
the students that her prized frog got away. Later we went into a plowed field and 
an abandoned field to discussion succession. The students just could not get over how many frogs 
there were in the field. At the end I wanted to encourage everyone to become comfortable 
handling frogs, because some of the students are timid towards frogs, so we had a frog race where each student had to get their own frog to race. This was a big hit! 
<BR>
There was one downside to this day. One student found an aerosol container and started 
to inhale the fumes from the can. I had just learned about kids doing that in my 
drug studies class the night before and was shocked to see it happening the very 
next day. I was thankful that I was knowledgeable of the effects of inhaling fumes so I 
had some confidence in explaining why it was not a healthy nor appropriate behavior.<BR>
I learned two valuable lessons today, it is best to over plan as much as possible 
so that you do not have down time and you can never be sure what your students are 
going to do next so you next to roll with the punches.<BR><H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ritanine.html">Journal 9</A></H4>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
