<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>meliseig</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Journal #8<BR>
Monday October 28, 1996<BR>
<BR>
Considering how last week went, I was unusually calm when I first entered the classroom 
today.   I planned an activity which involved going outside and finding different 
colored strips that  I had spread around a large area on the school grounds.  Before 
we went outside though, I made them do a KWL in their journal.  They did not know 
what a KWL was and were intrigued by it.  There were so many questions about what 
it was, and when I finally told them, they wrote without complaints.  Then I did 
a quick review of the previous weeks lessons.  I called on one to tell me one thing and then 
I gave them the choice of who was to tell another thing.  I found out that they knew 
what had been covered the week before, but they had no idea of what it demonstrated, 
or how it could be applied to find out other information.  I am not quite sure how to 
remedy that as of yet.  <BR>
When we finally got outside, the students were so glad to be out of the classroom 
that they looked really hard for the strips, and they did not fool around at all. 
 I was so surprised, especially since the last time I took them out, they <STRONG>only</STRONG>
 fooled around.  I was quite pleased at the seriousness with which they perceived 
this activity that I could have handled any situation after that.  Fortunately, there 
was not one.  The only incident that bothered me was when one of the students asked 
me if they had to write about the strips when we returned to the classroom.  When I replied 
with a YES, there was a lot of groaning and then they told the others not to find 
a lot because they would have to write about it.  I do not understand the complete 
hate some have for writing even a few paragraphs.  Maybe my next journal assignment will 
revolve around a personal experience of the student.  Hopefully that will help.<BR>
We ended on a very "up" note, and achieved more than I hoped to.  A note about my 
classroom management technique:  I tried the "put them on the clock" and it worked 
extremely well.  Mr. Vandenberg said he would keep them from gym, or after school 
along with his time.  We only got up to 50 seconds; not bad at all.
<BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="melisnin.html">Journal 9</A></H4>
</BODY>
