<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritanine.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Friday, October 4th</STRONG>
<BR>
<BR>
Today I started the class by having each student write in their journal why they felt 
plants are important. I have them write in their journals every week and through 
experience I found it more successful to provide students with a specific question 
to answer as a starting point for journal writing. If I left the writing too open, then 
the students seemed confused and did not produce quality work.  After discussing 
their journal responses, the class was divided into two groups. The students were 
then allowed to choose roles within the group. The roles were: leader, spokesperson, recorder, 
and gatherer. The two groups could only talk via the spokesperson. The gatherer was 
the only one who could leave the group to get supplies. The recorder worked more 
like a designer in producing the layout of a poster and the leader kept everyone working 
together. I brought in numerous magazines, leaves , seeds, and two blank poster boards. 
One group task was to create a poster identifying the different types of trees and 
seeds found in our area. The other group focused on depicting how seeds travel. The 
activity went very well and I was proud of the results. Giving each individual a 
particular job helps to ensure participation. The students seemed to feel very comfortable 
describing their posters to other students. After class I asked students how they liked 
the activity and received a lot of positive feedback. I think kids enjoy making collages. 
There was one student who liked the activity but disliked the group saying that not everyone worked equally. I think that this problem is bound to happen sometimes, 
we discussed with the group that everyone must do their job in order to successfully 
complete the project and we discussed future actions that may help that group to 
work together better. Overall, I was pleased with todays results.<BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ritaelev.html">Journal 10</A></H4>
</BODY>
