<HEAD>
<TITLE>melissan.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Melissa Plemons<BR>
Gov. Journal #9<BR>
Monday November 4, 1996<BR>
<BR>
I was supposed to share my day with Valerie, but she called last night and said she 
was sick and would not be able to able to be there.  My lesson plan needed to be 
extended  for the full time.  As it turned out, I did not need to make any alterations 
because what I thought would only take 20 minutes to do, actually took them 40, then they 
still did not finish.  I actually tried to implement cooperative learning and had 
originally planned for 2 groups of 3, and one group of 2, but 2 people were absent 
and I ended up splitting them into 3 groups of 2.  I had some resistance because there 
was only one girl among 5 guys, and none of the guys wanted to work with a girl. 
 I tried to group them according to achievement, but they wanted to choose who they 
worked with.  Not because I allowed them to, but because they did it on their own and I left 
them as they were.  The two students who do not like to work were together and they 
constantly asked me questions about the assignment.  At one point, I had one of them 
say " The more we ask you, the more you will tell us".  Basically, they wanted me to 
do the work for them.  I planned the activity in the most simplistic and straightforward 
way, at least I thought, but I underestimated their ability to go beyond the literal.  I had a little writing assignment that went along with that activity, and they moaned 
about it (it was only 2 paragraphs).  Only one group got to finish it- is it because 
they have problems reading, or because they are hard to get motivated?  I wish I 
knew.  Tomorrow  I plan on speaking to Lucille Waterson about some ideas on how to get 
the students more involved, so at least it does not feel like I am pulling teeth. 
 Dr. Doody and I think that next semester a writing project should be done to help 
them learn to like to write.  Possibly a News Report- not work, but a fun thing that involved 
writing.  I find it really hard to force students to do something they really hate. 
 Their journal entries were nonexistent, and it even involved writing a personal 
narrative.  I get so frustrated!<BR>
<BR>
The other Activity I had planned was a role play enacting members of the community 
that were involved in certain interest groups, defending the environment against 
a person that wanted to do something that may have a negative effect on the environment. 
 Each student had a role and they sat on opposite sides of the room, in a debate setting. 
 They were really enthusiastic about it and a lot of good points were made.  The 
previous activity was designed to help them, but they were not very interested in 
doing that, so many other good arguments were missed.  <BR>
<BR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
