<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritaelev.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Monday, October 7th<BR>
</STRONG>
<BR>
Today was a special treat for me because I switched with Ms. Plemmons so that she 
could attend a wedding. I enjoy doing the Monday intro to the week rather than the 
Friday wrap-up. I am not merely reviewing but covering new material. Today we learned 
about invasive species, focusing primarily on zebra mussels which have recently invaded 
the area. I started the lesson by placing the daily objectives on the board so that 
the students knew exactly what was to be done. Then I asked the students what they 
felt invasive or exotic species were. This was a short introduction to a lesson on exotic 
species. I used an example of an island inhabited only by mice for years then suddenly 
a cat was introduced to help explain the effects of introduced species. I learned 
later that I need to be careful in giving examples because when I asked individual students 
what introduced species where I was frequently retold my story of cats and mice. 
I had the students pick an exotic species out of a hat to research. I provided each 
student with a study guide to assist them in their research. Then I had each student 
do a practice research project in class on zebra mussels. I provided each student 
with a study guide and a copy of an article on zebra mussels. The students performed 
very well on this. I find providing study guides to be helpful to both the students and 
myself. By allowing the students to practice their assignment in class I was able 
to clear up a lot of questions and provide the students with some ideas of possible 
resources. I was really pleased with this lesson and received a lot of positive feedback 
from the students.<BR><H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ritael.html">Journal 11</A></H4>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
