<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritatwel.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Wednesday, October 9th<BR>
</STRONG>
<STRONG><BR>
</STRONG>
<STRONG></STRONG>
Today the class went to the city of Ogdensburg where the Oswegatchie River drains 
into the St. Lawrence River.  It was a perfect site to observe the effects of urbanization 
on the river. It was also a great site to find some exotic species. We found zebra 
mussels and purple loose strife. The field work went well and the students were once 
again enthusiastic. One student found a small snapping turtle while others found 
clumps of fish eggs under rocks. We finished early again as the students become more 
efficient in making their quadrants and searching for specimens. There was a large park 
where we were working so once we finished we let the students play in the park. We 
all became engaged in a game of tag. I love being able to participate in their games 
and I think it builds a good sense of trust and teamwork among the class.<BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ritatwel.html">Journal 12</A></H4>
</BODY>
