<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritathir.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Friday, October 25th</STRONG>
<BR>
<BR>
Today I did a conclusion activity to the weeks lessons pertaining to animals. I wanted 
to pull together all of the material covered for the week (limiting factors, adaptations, 
and  evolution). I chose to start the class by review the previous weeks lessons to see what the students learned. I feel that I am becoming better in my skills 
of assessing the students knowledge through questioning. After a discussion on evolution 
I asked the students how we know what organisms looked like millions of years ago. 
The students provided a list of possibilities. Then without providing them with an 
answer I passed out an article on the history of horses and gave a study guide to 
help them answer the questions. Once the students had worked on the activity for 
a while I stopped them and we talked about the changes which have occurred over millions of years. 
The students were once again asked how we know that horses hooves have changed. We 
decided as a group that one way we knew of the changes in the hoof is via preserved 
foot tracks. I took the class outside where they conveniently have a horse track behind 
the school to look for prints. I brought some plaster of Paris to make a mold of 
the track. Unfortunately, it had rained the night before and most of the tracks were 
too worn to be of any use,so I improvised by making a mold of one students foot. The 
students loved this activity and I think they will remember the lesson contents for 
a long time. After we made the mold I took the students to the horse barns to see 
some of the horses that are boarded there. This lesson was a big hit! <BR>
I learned that it is difficult to work with props sometimes as our mold was unsuccessful. 
By the time we walked to the track and decided to make a human foot mold the plaster 
was too hard. The students enjoyed the activity anyway and we decided to try it again some other day.<BR><H4 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="ritathir.html">Journal 13</A></H4>

</BODY>
</HTML>
