<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ritathir.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Wednesday, November 6th<BR>
</STRONG>
<STRONG><BR>
</STRONG>
Today was a great learning experience for me. I was not scheduled to teach today but 
Mrs. Pond called me at 8:00 am to inform me she was ill and could not teach. The 
students do not have school on Friday in honor of Veterans Day and I did not want 
to loose two days this week so I hurried looked over my lesson plan on pesticides and other 
pollutants for Friday and modified it to fit earlier in the week. I was really happy 
with the results. I had the students do an activity where they acted out the role 
of grasshopper foraging for  food, shrew hunting for grasshopper and finally hawk hunting 
for shrew. I spread colored papers on the gym floor to represent food and gave the 
grasshoppers a brown bag to represent their stomachs. After the hunting was over 
I asked the students who were still alive and the hawks boasted that they were. I then had 
the hawks open the contents of the "stomachs" to to find many white and colored pieces 
of paper. I informed the students that the colored paper represented food that was 
heavily contaminated with pesticides. Then I again asked the students who were alive 
and the noisy room suddenly feel silent. It was wild to see how powerful the activity 
was. From this point we discussed effects of pollutants, how they get into the environment, and alternatives to using pesticides. I got my ideas from "Deadly Links" out 
of the book Project Wild. The class went very well. I really prefer to be prepared 
days in advance but I know that there will be times when I will have to whip-up a 
lesson with little notice.    <BR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
