<BR>

<A NAME="VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS"><CENTER><B>VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS</B></CENTER></A>
<br><br>
<dt>
<dt><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E"><b>E</A>.	THE SUNY TIAA-CREF OPTIONAL RETIREMENT PROGRAM (ORP)</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E1"><i>1</A>.	THE PROGRAM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Teachers' Insurance and Annuity Association and College Retirement Equities Fund (TIAA-CREF) also known as THE OPTIONAL RETIREMENT (ORP) PROGRAM, established by law, under which the State University has designated TIAA-CREF as the insurer.  The program provides a nationwide, non-profit retirement system for colleges, universities, private schools and certain other non-profit educational and research organizations.  This is a retirement program under which individual contracts, providing retirement and death benefits for or on behalf of electing employees, are purchased from TIAA-CREF.  Benefits are designed for retirement at age 65, although retirement is possible at any age.  You may direct that the combined employee and University contribution be used to purchase a TIAA fixed annuity or you may choose to allocate any portion or all of the contribution to the purchase of a CREF variable annuities with the remainder, if any, going toward the purchase of a TIAA annuity.  THE OPTIONAL RETIREMENT PROGRAM is funded through individually owned annuities issued by TIAA-CREF.
<dt><br>
		<dt>In addition, there are now three Alternate Funding Vehicles approved under the Optional Retirement Program to which you may direct and or transfer your retirement accumulations during your employment.  These alternate funding vehicles (AFV) are:
<dt><br>
		<dd>a.	Aetna Life Insurance and Annuity Company (AETNA)<br>
		<dd>b.	Metropolitan Life and Affiliated Companies<br>
		<dd>c.	The Variable Annuity Life Insurance Company (VALIC)<br>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Each of these alternate funding vehicles offer a variety of investment instruments.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Note:	Due to limitations in the State's payroll systems, employees who wish to participate in one of the Alternate Funding Vehicles (AFV) must also elect to participate in CREF.  All AFV funds will be transmitted from your CREF account.  Once a month CREF will forward, to the AFV, the amount you have designated.  There is no charge for external transfers from CREF to AFV.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Participation is effective as of your entry into service for those new persons who, at the time of employment, have TIAA-CREF contracts, and who elect the Optional Retirement Program.  University contributions will start immediately and together with employee contributions will be transmitted to TIAA-CREF.  For those new employees electing the Optional Retirement Program, who do not at time of employment have TIAA-CREF contracts, University contributions will be made upon the completion of 13 months of service.  At the end of the initial 13 months of service, the University will make a single lump sum contribution with interest to TIAA-CREF for this initial period, and will make regular monthly contributions thereafter.  If you do not serve for at least 13 months, no contributions on the part of the University will be made.
<dt><br>
<dt>The amount of the employee 3% contributions deducted during the initial 13 months of service, with interest, will be transmitted to TIAA-CREF at the end of the 13-month period.  If services do not continue for at least 13 months, an employee's contribution, with interest, will be refunded to the employee.  In this case, no University contributions will have been made on behalf of the employee for the purchase of TIAA-CREF contracts.  
<dt><br>
<dt>Participation is available to full-time professional staff and part-time employees with term contracts.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E2"><i>2</A>.	CONTRIBUTION RATES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Under present New York State law, the total contribution to TIAA- CREF for each employee electing the Optional Retirement Program will be the following percentages of the employee's calendar year salary:		
<br><BR>

			<dd>a.	For employees hired prior to July 16, 1992:<br>
<center>
			12% of state salary up to $16,500
                               plus
			15% of state salary in excess of $16,500.
</center>
<dt><br>
		<dt><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	For employees hired on or after July 17, 1992:</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
			<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>1.	8% of state salary for the first seven years of 
university service
<dt><br>
			<dd>2.	10% of state salary thereafter</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
			<dd>c.	For employees hired on or after January 1, 1996:
<dt><br>
<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>1.	8% of state salary, based upon a maximum state salary of $150,000, for the first seven years of university service
<dt><br>
<dd>2.	10% of state salary, based upon a maximum state salary of $150,000 thereafter</BLOCKQUOTE>

		<dt><BLOCKQUOTE>accomplished as follows:</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
		<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>a)	For Employees Appointed To State Service Before July 1, 1976 And Choosing the ORP, the entire contribution to TIAA-CREF will be made by the State University of New York.
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	For Employees Appointed To State Service On Or After July 1, 1976 And Choosing The ORP Program
<dt><br>
<dd>Three percent (3%) of salary will be deducted from each paycheck as part of this contribution.  The balance will be contributed by the State University of New York.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
<dd<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>NOTE:	For employees appointed to State service on or after July 1, 1973 and participating in the ORP program the total University contribution to the Optional Retirement Program (as a percentage of salary) cannot exceed the higher of the current service cost (as a percentage of salary) of the New York State Employees' Retirement or Teachers' Retirement Systems.  This figure may be rounded up to the next highest whole percentage.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>

	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E3"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>3</A>.	TAX DEFERRAL</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Your contributions may be made on a salary deduction (after-tax) or on a salary reduction (tax-deferred) basis.  Contributions made by salary deduction will be taxed the year in which they are made; whereas contributions made by salary reduction will be taxed the year in which the benefit payments are received.  If you make your contributions through salary reduction, you must  complete a Salary Reduction Agreement with the State University of New York for the amount of your contributions.  Only one Salary Reduction Agreement may be effective in a calendar year.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Under present law, the part of your annuity income that represents your own contributions made on a salary deduction (after-tax) basis will not be taxed as you receive it.  This amount is called your "Investment in the Contract."  The balance of your annuity income-- your own contributions that were made by salary reduction, employer contributions, and investment earnings--will be subject to federal income taxes as you receive it.</BLOCKQUOTE>

	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E4"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>4</A>.	VESTING</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Vesting refers to the retention by an employee who terminates service prior to retirement (for reasons other than death or disability) of eligibility for retirement benefits at a later date.
<dt><br>
<dt>All contributions, including those made by the University, will be applied upon the completion of thirteen months of service to individually owned annuities that provide for full and immediate ownership of the retirement and survivor benefits.
<dt><br>
<Dt>Vesting is immediate for employees who already own TIAA-CREF retirement annuities and choose to participate in the ORP.
<dt><br>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E5"><i>5</A>.	RETIREMENT ALLOWANCE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Under the TIAA-CREF program, retirement benefits are derived from an annuity based on the accumulated value of employee and University contributions.  At the age of retirement, this will be a fixed and variable annuity if both TIAA and CREF FUNDS are selected.  The booklet TIAA-CREF Retirement Annuities offers detailed information regarding retirement income.  TIAA-CREF participants receive a yearly report which includes an estimate of the amount of annuity income payable at age 65.  

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E6"><i>6</A>.	DISABILITY RETIREMENT BENEFITS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Under the TIAA-CREF retirement program there is no special disability provision, but the employee may elect to receive an annuity from the accumulated value of employee and University contributions, based on his/her age at the time disability begins.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E7"><i>7</A>.	RETIREMENT OPTIONS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Just before you retire, you will choose from among several types of income options available.  If you are married at the time you elect to begin annuity income, your right to choose an income option may be subject to your spouse's right, under federal pension law, to be named as a Second Annuitant under a Survivor Annuity Option.  All retirement income options provide a lifetime income for you, and all but one provide income protection for your spouse or other beneficiary in the event of your early death.  A summary of the options available may be obtained from the Office of Human Resources or TIAA-CREF.
<dt><br>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6D8"><i>8</A>.	TRANSFER AND PORTABILITY</i>
 <dt><br>
		<dt>As TIAA-CREF benefits provided by contract are vested immediately with the individual, transfer among more than 4,000 public and private universities, colleges, private schools, foundations and other educational and research organizations throughout the country is possible.  Individual premiums may be continued by direct payment to TIAA-CREF if you leave the University, regardless of future employment.  Such premiums may be made in any amount, subject to a minimum payment of $100 per year.
<dt><br>
<dt>Options available to you upon termination of service with the University are:
<dt><br>
<dd>a)	continue in a TIAA-CREF retirement plan through employment with another TIAA-CREF participating institution;
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	continue making contributions to your contracts by sending premiums directly to TIAA-CREF;
<dt><br>
		<dd>c)	leave the accumulation in your contracts;
<dt><br>
		<dd>d)	begin to receive a lifetime income from your annuities; or,
<dt><br>
		<dd>e)	request the return of the accumulation if specific requirements are satisfied.
<dt><br>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6E9"><i>9</A>.	SRA LOANS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>An employee, who is an SRA participant, may call TIAA-CREF at 1-800-842-2776 to inquire about a loan.  A participant counselor will take the call and forward to the employee a loan application and other appropriate forms.
<Dt><br>
<dt>Participating employees may take an SRA Loan, generally up to 45% of their total TIAA/CREF SRA accumulations.  Maximum amount an employee may borrow is $50,000.  Employees must have 110% of the amount they wish to borrow in their TIAA accumulation as security for the loan.  The repayment period is from 1 to 5 years (10 years if the money is for the purchase of a house).
</dl>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6F"><b>F</A>.	RETIREMENT INCOME OPTIONS - TRS, ERS, AND ORP</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>When you are ready to retire, you will receive information from the retirement system you have elected as to the options available and the amount of income available under each option.  There are a number of different options offered by each program, but they all fall into the following general categories:
<dt><br>
<dd>1.	Income for the life of the participant and ceasing at participant's death.
<dt><br>
	<dd>2.	Income for the life of the participant and continued in the same or a reduced amount to a surviving beneficiary.
<dt><br>
	<dd>3.	Income for the life of the participant, but guaranteed for a period of years.
<dt><br>
	<dd>The amount of periodic payments to the retiree under 2 or 3 above will be smaller than under 1 in  order to provide benefits for surviving beneficiaries.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6G"><b>G</A>.	EMPLOYMENT IN NEW YORK STATE IN PUBLIC SERVICE AFTER RETIREMENT STATE SERVICE</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><i><A NAME="6G1">1</A>.	SERVICE RETIREMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dd>a)	Commencing with the calendar year in which a member attains age 70, a member retired for service is not subject to earnings restrictions.  Any member under age 70 retired for service may return to public employment in this State and earn up to $11,280 in a calendar year without jeopardizing her/his retirement allowance.  (S)he is required to file a statement with the System electing to have the provisions of Section 212 of Article 7 of the Retirement and Social Security Law applied to the employment and must report gross earnings and employers to the System each month in which employment occurs.  Forms for filing and reporting are available from the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
<dd>If earnings in New York State public employment of more than $11,280 are anticipated in a calendar year, a retired member who will not attain age 70 in that calendar year must comply with Section 211 of Article 7 of the Retirement and Social Security Law to continue receiving her/his retirement allowance.  In this case, the employer must obtain approval of the employment from the Commissioner of Education, the Chancellor of the State University or the State Civil Service Commission, depending upon the specific employment.
<dt><br>
			<dd>Approvals may be granted for periods not exceeding two years.  A request for renewal is subject to the same requirements as the original application.
<dt><br>
<dd>Should the request for approval for employment under Section 211 be denied, and he/she were to exceed the allowable earnings of $11,280 in a calendar year, the retired member would have to repay to the System any retirement allowance received retroactive to the first date of employment within the calendar year.
<dt><br>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6G2"><i>2</A>.	DISABILITY RETIREMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dd>a)	A member who has been retired for disability and who returns to full-time teaching service will be reinstated as an active member of the System.
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	A member retired for disability, under certain circumstances, may be allowed to earn in any capacity in a calendar year the difference between the disability retirement allowance including any supplemental benefit and the final average salary, or the salary (s)he would have been receiving if continuing in service, whichever is greater.  If it is determined that a member retired for disability is able to hold a full-time teaching position, the disability allowance will be discontinued.
<dt><br>
		<dd>c)	Those retired for disability must report all employment earnings (regardless of source) to the System each month in which compensation is earned.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
</dl>
<br><br>
