<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>IX. ACADEMIC AFFAIRS</strong></center>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>B.  ACADEMIC POLICIES</B>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B4"><i>4</A>.	GRADUATE ADMISSION CATEGORIES</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B4a">a</A>)	Matriculated Status                    
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B4a1">1</A>)	Provisional Admission - Granted to students who have applied and been reviewed for admission to a graduate degree program but who do not meet certain minimum requirements; e.g., submission of satisfactory scores on the LAST and ATS-W portions of the New York State Teacher Certification Exams (NYSTCE) where required, undergraduate prerequisites, etc.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B4a2">2</A>)	Full Admission - Granted to students who have satisfied all admission requirements.
<dt><br>
In order to be considered for matriculated status (Provisional Admission or Full Admission) students must fulfill the following criteria:
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5"><i>5</A>.	COLLEGE CREDIT</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5a">a</A>)	Earning College Credit
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students nominally earn course credits at the rate of one credit for each hour of time spent in class per week over the period of one semester.  The actual formula, however, is based upon minutes spent in class (i.e., a minimum of 15 meetings x 50' = 750').  Thus to earn 3 credits for completing a 3 hour course, a student must pass the course and the class itself must meet 2250 minutes or 37.5 hours.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5b">b</A>)	Liberal Arts Credit
<dt><br>
			<dt>A course carrying liberal arts credit is a course of college-level work designed to contribute to students' intellectual and cultural development.  In such a course, an important and substantial portion of the study is devoted to analytic, synthetic and theoretical treatment of the content of the disciplines represented.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5c">c</A>)	Non-liberal Arts Credit
<dt><br>
			<dt>A college-level course bearing non-liberal arts credit is one designed primarily to help students develop appropriate skills, knowledge and attitudes necessary for the pursuit of specific professions or vocations.

		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5d">d</A>)	Credit Loads

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5di">i</A>)	Undergraduate Student

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5dia">(a)</A> Regular Session
<dt><br>
				    <dd>Part-time = 0-11 credit hours	<br>			    		    <dd>Minimum full-time = 12 credit hours<br>
				    <dd>Normal = 15 credit hours<br>
				    <dd>Maximum = 19 credit hours (excluding P.E.          activities)<br>
<dt><br>
    <dt>Overload = 20 or more (Requires consent of advisor and Dean's office, plus completion of an overload form).  Students may register for academic course credits over 19 only during the add/drop period following registration.<BR><BR>

(b)  Summer Session<BR><BR>

The maximum study load for the Pre-Session and the Regular Session is seven (7) credit hours (two courses) in each session.  Exceptions to allow additional hours may be made with the written permission of the Dean of the appropriate school.<BR>

				</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5dii">ii</A>)	Graduate Student

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5diia">(a)</A> Regular Session
<dt><br>
				    <dt>Twelve (12) credit hours constitute the normal load     for a full-time graduate student.  A graduate student may register for a maximum of fifteen (15) credit hours.  Any course work registered for beyond the 15-credit limit must have written approval of the advisor and the Dean of Graduate Studies.

</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5diib">(b)</A> Summer Session
<dt><br>
    <dt>The normal full study load for the five week summer session is (7) credit hours.  Permission to carry more than seven (7) credit hours in a five week summer session may be granted in exceptional cases with the approval of the Dean of the appropriate school.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
</dl></BLOCKQUOTE>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5e">e</A>)	Course Levels
               <dt><br>
			<dt>Courses are numbered to provide a nominal measure of required prior knowledge and experience. For instance, it would normally be unwise for a freshman, without previous experience in a discipline, to register for a 400-level course.  These course levels are listed as follows:
<dt><br>
			<dd>100-299	Undergraduate lower division<br>
			<dd>300-499	Undergraduate upper division<br>
			<dd>500-599	Graduate (advanced undergraduates may take them with permission, for undergraduate credit)<br>
			<dd>600-699	Graduate (limited to graduate students only)<br>  

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5f">f</A>)	Repeating Courses
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students may repeat, only once, a course in which a grade has been recorded.  Permission to repeat a course will be further limited by the concept of "space availability," providing priority for first-time registrants.  In extraordinary circumstances a student may repeat a course more than once with permission of the appropriate Dean.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5g">g)	Transfer Credit
<dt><br>
			<dt>Credits earned for instruction not under the direct control of SUNY Potsdam are transfer credits.

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gi">i</A>)	Undergraduate Transfer Credit

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gia">(a)</A> Limitations
<dt><br>
				    <dt>Candidates for a baccalaureate degree must complete a minimum of thirty semester hours, exclusive of physical education, in residence at the College.   Exceptions to this rule may be granted by the Academic Services Center but only in cases of extreme hardship.
<dt><br>
    <dt>Also a minimum of 15 semester hours of the major program must be completed in residence.
<dt><br>
    <dt>Courses offered by the College at off-campus locations are included in residence credit.

				</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gib">(b)</A> Acceptance of Credit
<dt><br>
    <dt>The Director of Academic Transfer Services is responsible for evaluation of transfer credits.  Credits normally will be accepted for course work completed with a grade of D, or better, at an accredited institution of higher education, i.e., college, junior college, technical institute, seminary, Armed Forces Institute or foreign institution.  Guidelines issued by the American Association of College Registrars and Admissions Offices (AACRAO) will be used where necessary and applicable to assist in evaluation.

				</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gic">(c)</A> Upper Division Credit
<dt><br>
				    <dt>No two-year college course may be transferred for upper division credit.  
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gid">(d)</A> Major Field Credit
<dt><br>
    <dt>The decision as to whether and how transferred credits apply toward completion of a major at SUNY Potsdam rests with the major field     department.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gie">(e)</A> Liberal Studies Credit
<dt><br>
    <dt>In general, credits earned in a department corresponding to a liberal studies department at SUNY Potsdam will be considered liberal studies.   Should the liberal studies content of a particular course be questioned the decision will be made by the Transfer Services Office in consultation with the department concerned.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B5gif">(f)</A> Other
<dt><br>
    <dt>Transfer credit may also be granted from each of the     following programs:
<dt><br>
                              <dd>Empire State College Contracts<br>
                              <dd>College Board Advanced Placement                                 Examinations<br>
                             <dd>College Proficiency Examinations<br>
                              <dd>College Level Examinations<br>
                              <dd>Credit By Examination<br>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B6"><i>6</A>.	CROSS-REGISTRATION</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Cross-registration through the Associated Colleges of the St. Lawrence Valley provides an opportunity for full-time students at SUNY Canton, Clarkson University, SUNY Potsdam and St. Lawrence University to take up to two (2) courses per academic year (including summer session(s)) at any of the other institutions on a space-available basis.  Through cross-registration full-time matriculated students have access to courses in both major and elective areas representing specialties unavailable or closed at their home institution.  There also exist formal curricular arrangements among institutions. 
<dt><br>
<dt>The objectives are to expand the educational opportunities available to students and provide an academic program which offers the strengths of each institution.  Thus, a matriculated full-time student of one may enroll in a course offered by another college in order to improve the depth and variety of his/her academic program.
<dt><br>
<dt>The responsibility for ascertaining that a particular course will satisfy requirements for a major or for graduation is the responsibility of the student.  Prior approval from the academic advisor must be obtained before the student registers for the course(s).
<dt><br>
<dt>All credit will be residence credit.  The four colleges' schedules may differ.  The student is responsible for course work despite differences in the calendars and sometimes may need to arrange for food and lodging when dormitories of the home campus are closed.
<dt><br>
<dt>Certain courses of each college may not be open to cross- registration.
<dt><br>
<dt>Registration for any course is on the basis of available space and subject to the approval of the department offering the course.  A course must have a sufficient number of home students to warrant its offering.  In courses which become fully subscribed, home students are given priority.
<dt><br>
<dt>Prerequisites prevailing for home students must be satisfied by cross-registrants.  The instructor or the chairperson of the department offering the course will judge the applicant's qualifications.
<dt><br>
<dt>A student taking a course on another campus must abide by appropriate attendance regulations, honor systems, parking regulations, and other rules of the receiving college. No tuition will be charged either the registrant or his/her home college by the receiving institution, provided that the student is already paying full tuition at his/her home college.
<dt><br>          
<dt>Students must pay any special course fees.
<dt><br>
<dt>The receiving college will provide the home college with a grade and credit (or unit) report, on completion of the course.
</dl>
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>7</A>.	GRADING POLICIES</i>

<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7a"><BLOCKQUOTE>a</A>)	Undergraduate Grading System</BLOCKQUOTE>

<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7ai"><BLOCKQUOTE>i</A>)	A Numerical System
<dt><br>
				<dt>Grades are entered on the student's transcript and calculated into the cumulative GPA.  Levels of achievement are indicated according to the following intervals:
<dt><br>
<table>
<tr><td>4.0 = A</td>    <td>Excellent</td></tr>
<tr><td>3.5</td></tr>
<tr><td>3.0 = B</td>    <td>Good</td></tr>
<tr><td>2.5</td></tr>
<tr><td>2.0 = C</td>    <td>Satisfactory</td></tr>
<tr><td>1.5</td></tr>
<tr><td>1.0 = D</td>    <td>Minimum for which credit is awarded</td></tr>
<tr><td>0.0 = F</td>    <td>Failure</td></tr>
</table>

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7aii">ii</A>)	An Alternate Grading System:
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students may opt to be graded by an alternative grading system (S/U) in individual courses.
<dt><br>
<dt>"S" is recorded for a grade of 2.0 or higher.<br>
<dt>"U" is recorded for a grade lower than 2.0.<br>
<dt><br>
<dt>Both "S" and "U" are recorded on the transcript, but neither is calculated in the cumulative grade point average.  "S" confers credit for a course; "U" does not.
<dt><br>
<dt>Students may consider this option for a maximum of 14 semester hours during an entire college career.  Each time students choose this option, that choice must be recorded with the Registrar before the end of the appropriate ADD period.  Instructors will continue to report achievement in the numerical system.  Disclosure of this grading option to the instructor is at the student's discretion only.
<dt><br>
<dt>In addition, in certain courses the College may award an S* or U* (e.g., P. E. activities, student teaching, music studio courses).  An S* denotes satisfactory performance. A U* denotes unsatisfactory performance.  Students graded in this manner will not have such credits considered as part of the 14 semester hour maximum.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7aiii">iii</A>)	Incompletes
<dt><br>
				<dt>The grade of "Incomplete", noted as "I" on the transcript, may be reported by an instructor only under the following circumstances:
<dt><br>
<dt>Course requirements have not been completed for reasons beyond the student's control (i.e., illness, family emergency).
<dt><br>
<dt>Remaining requirements can be accomplished without further registration by the student.
<dt><br>
<dt>A grade of "Inc" will ordinarily be initiated by the student through a request to the instructor.  The conditions for changing the grade of "Incomplete" to a final grade must be fulfilled by the end of the next regular semester following issuance of the grade.  Incompletes, not completed by the appropriate time, will automatically be converted to Failure, U or U*, depending upon the student's choice of grading option or the faculty designation of the courses at the time of the original registration.
<dt><br>
<dt>In the event that an individual student's grade is not received in the Registrar's Office in time for grades to be processed, a delayed grade code (DGR) will appear on the student record and will remain until a grade is reported by the instructor.
<BR></BLOCKQUOTE>

<dl><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Academic Forgiveness Policy">iv)  Academic Forgiveness Policy</A><BR>
Approved by the Academic Policies, Standards, and Advising Committee - October 27, 1995<BR>

<BR>

The intent of this policy is to allow readmitted students who previously accrued a record with a substantial number of grades below the 2.0 level to be "forgiven" for their earlier performance, if they meet the stated criteria.
<BR>
<BR>
Academic Forgiveness in this context means that the student's previous college work shall be treated as if it had been transferred to SUNY Potsdam from another college:  none of the grades received would be counted in the current GPA, but the student would receive credit for any courses in which he/she earned a 1.0 or above grade (or S, S*, or Cr).  Courses for which credit was received could be used to fulfill General Education requirements, but could not be counted towards a major or minor degree unless passed with a 2.0 or higher grade, at the discretion of the chair of the department.
<BR>
<BR>
The criteria for being granted Academic Forgiveness and the stipulations of the policy follow:<BR>

1.  The student must have not taken any coursework at SUNY Potsdam for a minimum of four calendar years at the time of readmission.
<BR>
<BR>
2.  The student must not have attempted more than four semesters of full time work at SUNY Potsdam previous to readmission.  If Academic Forgiveness is granted, all previous work will be treated as transfer work; the student cannot choose to retain the grades from a particular semester.
<BR>
<BR>
3.  The student is not eligible to apply for Academic Forgiveness until he/she has completed one full-time semester of 12 hours of credit as a readmitted student; in this first semester or 12 hours of credit, the student must have completed every course with a minimum 2.0 grade, and have received a minimum cumulative GPA of 3.0 for this work.
<BR>
<BR>
4.  To be considered under this policy, the student must file a petition for Academic Forgiveness in the office of the chief academic officer of the college within one calendar year of readmission, and the petition must be approved by a designated committee.
<BR>
<BR>
5.  If approved for Academic Forgiveness, a notation to this effect will be made on the student's SUNY Potsdam transcript, and a new cumulative GPA will be calculated for all work beginning with the semeter of readmission.  This new GPA will be printed on the official transcript, and used for computing the student's academic standing, and for meeting the minimum 2.0 GPA requirement for graduation.  However, the previous SUNY Potdam work will continue to be listed on the transcript with the original grades received.
<BR>
<BR>
6.  Once Academic Forgiveness has been granted, the student will be eligible for Graduation with Honors based on the same criteria as those applied to transfer students.
<BR>
<BR>
7.  Academic Forgiveness may be granted only once in a student's college career.
<BR>
<BR>
8.  The chief academic officer of the college (or designee) will condider exceptions to any of the above requirements.
			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Standards of Satisfactory Academic Performance">v)	Standards Of Satisfactory Academic Performance</A></A>
<dt><br>
				<dt>The minimal acceptable level of academic achievement in a given semester is:  
<dt><br>
<dt>- A semester grade point average of 2.0<br>
<dt>- A cumulative grade point average of 2.0<br>
<dt>- For a full-time student, passing 12 credit hours; -   For a part-time student, passing half or more of the   registered credits
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7b">b</A>)	Graduate Grading System

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7bi">i</A>)	A Numerical System
<dt><br>
				<dt>Course work in the graduate program is graded as follows:
<dt><br>
<dt>4.0 - superior attainment       <br>
<dt>3.5 - high attainment           <br>
<dt>3.0 - satisfactory attainment    <br>
<dt>2.5 - below average attainment  <br>
<dt>2.0 - minimum passing grade<br>
<dt>0.0 - failure
<BR>
<BR>
<dt>S - Satisfactory (student elected)<BR>
<dt>U - Unsatisfactory (student elected)<BR>
<dt>S* - Satisfactory (college designated)<BR>
<dt>U* - Unsatisfactory (college designated)<BR>
<dt>I - Incomplete<BR>
<dt>IP - In Progress<BR>

<dt>
			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7bii">ii</A>)	Incompletes
<dt><br>
				<dt>A report of Incomplete may be submitted for any course at the discretion of the instructor.  Records of Incompletes will be carried for a period of one (1) semester.  If an Incomplete has not been removed after the specified period of time, the Incomplete will be changed to a grade of failure (0).  It is the responsibility of the student to take the initiative in removing a grade of Incomplete.  Such arrangements should be made with the instructor.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B7biii">iii</A>)	Credit/No Credit
<dt><br>
				<dt>A graduate student with Full Graduate Status and a graduate cumulative average of 3.0 or better may, with the approval of the advisor and the instructor concerned, select a maximum of six (6) credit hours of elective courses (either in residence or to be taken elsewhere for transfer to a graduate program at this College) on a credit/no credit (or pass/fail) basis.  Applicability to the total program of credits earned on a credit/no credit basis prior to the achievement of Full Graduate Status is determined only after the student has achieved Full Graduate Status.  The student must indicate to the instructor(s) concerned his or her desire to be evaluated on a credit/no credit basis by the end of the sixth week of classes in a regular semester or by the end of   the first week of summer session.  Any decision to change the evaluation from a credit/no credit basis to conventional basis (or vice versa) after the end of the sixth week of classes in the regular semester or the end of the first week of classes in the summer session can be made only with the permission of the instructor(s) concerned.  Credit is given for the equivalent of a numerical grade of 2.0 or above.  No credit is given for grades below 2.0.  The student receives the specified number of credit hours for such course, but the credits are not included in the computation of any grade point average.  
<dt><br>
<dt>Upon the petition of a department or school, the grade of credit/no credit may be given for specific graduate courses.   

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Grade Requirements">iv)	Grade Requirements</A>
<dt><br>
				<dt>An average of 3.0 or a cumulative "B" average in all graduate work taken at SUNY Potsdam is required for admission to candidacy for the master's degree and for the degree itself.  This includes all graduate work taken in residence, off-campus, or accepted for transfer credit.
</dl>
</dl>
	</dl></BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B8"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>8</A>.	AUDITING COURSES </i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B8a">a</A>)	By Regularly-Enrolled Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Auditing courses by regularly-enrolled students is possible under certain limitations.  The instructor must signify approval by written notification to the Dean of the appropriate school, submitted through the department  chairperson.  Auditors attend without credit or formal recognition.  They are not enrolled or listed in rosters for the course.  They are not responsible for meeting requirements of the course nor will they be charged tuition or fees.  No one may be an auditor in a foreign study program or in courses in which studio, observation or other participation are involved.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B8b">b</A>)	By Senior Citizens
<dt><br>
			<dt>By State law, citizens of New York State who are 60 years of age may audit courses on State University campuses at no expense.  Certain regulations apply, according to University guidelines.
<dt><br>
<dt>Advice on procedures and available courses may be obtained from the Office of Graduate and Continuing Education.  Lecture and discussion courses are particularly recommended.  Auditing depends on the availability of space, and auditors should, whenever possible, discuss their interests with the instructor.
<dt><br>
<dt>Registration is to be completed in the Office of Graduate and Continuing Education.  Auditors will not pay fees, take examinations, receive materials given to credit- earning students, be recorded in class lists, or receive grades.
<dt>
<dt>A file of course auditors is maintained in the Office of Graduate and Continuing Education.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B9"><i>9</A>.	DEADLINES FOR COURSE SCHEDULE ADJUSTMENTS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09Ba">a</A>)	Regular Session

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09Bai">i</A>)	ADD/DROP Period
<dt><br>
				<dt>The ADD/DROP period extends five class days into each semester.  A student may adjust courses during these periods without a permanent record notation of "W" for courses dropped. 

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B9aii">ii</A>)	Withdrawing From Courses
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students may elect to withdraw for any reason from courses for a maximum of 14 semester hours during an entire college career at Potsdam.  Students may exercise this right only before the end of the 8th week of classes in the appropriate semester.  In such cases a "W" is noted on the permanent record.
<dt><br>
<dt>Withdrawal for medical or other emergency may be granted by an appropriate academic Dean or the Academic Services Center at any time.  It will be noted on the transcript as W* and will not be considered as part of the 14-hour maximum.
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B9b">b</A>)	Summer Session

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B9bi">i</A>)	ADD/DROP Period
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students may ADD a regular six-week course from the 1st through the 4th day of classes and may drop a six-week course through the 6th day of classes.  

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B9bii">ii</A>)	Withdrawing From Courses
<dt><br>
				<dt>A student withdrawing from a six-week course after five class days will receive a grade of "W".
</dl></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
