<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter 9 C</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>IX. ACADEMIC AFFAIRS</strong></center><BR>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C"><b>C</A>.	ACADEMIC CALENDAR</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C1"><i>1</A>.	UNIVERSITY GUIDELINES</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C1a">a</a>)	General
<dt><br>
			<dt>Guidelines to be observed in the development of campus instructional calendars were issued in a letter from Chancellor Boyer, March 26, 1971.
<dt><br>
<dt>The following guidelines should be observed in the development of campus instructional calendars.  While pressure continues to mount for establishment of a uniform University-wide calendar, such a rigid plan would seriously inhibit the flexibility required for the creation of imaginative and responsive academic programs.  Thus the guidelines are not addressed to the issue of uniformity, nor do they attempt to prescribe specific numbers of days or hours of instruction.  Course requirements have been described by the Regents and by normative academic practice.  Rather, these guidelines specify common procedure in several areas, specifically length of instructional year, observance of holidays, and utilization of campus facilities.
<dt><br>
<dt>These guidelines are intended to apply to normative campus-based situations of regular instruction.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Each campus should give careful attention to the relation between calendar and the number of hours of weekly obligation of faculty and student, and should take into consideration in calendar development the effect of the suggested holiday guidelines upon the total period of instruction.
<dt><br>
<dd>i)	The instructional year shall include a minimum of 30 weeks instruction, exclusive of periods for registration and examination.  If the conventional semester plan is followed, no single semester shall consist of fewer than 14 weeks of instruction, with a total of 30 weeks instruction for two semesters, exclusive of periods for registration and examination.  Other patterns may be developed subject to approval of the Chancellor.
<dt><br>
<dd>ii)	In cases where the campus, for academic reasons, plans for the period of academic instruction (exclusive of periods for registration and examinations) to begin after September 15 or to end earlier than May 15, the expressed written approval of the Chancellor is required.
<dt><br>
			<dd>iii)	On those religious holy days when members of a faith typically observe the expectation of church or synagogue that they be absent from school or work, campuses will avoid the scheduling of such events as registration, the first day of classes, or student convocations, and individual students will be excused from class without penalty if expressly requested.
<dt><br>
			<dd>iv)	In developing the instructional calendar, attention should be given to the possibility of closing all College offices and not scheduling classes on those days observed by the State as holidays which fall on a Monday or Friday.
<dt><br>
			<dd>v)	Attention shall be given to optimal utilization of campus facilities with special consideration given  to the summer period(s) of instruction.
<dt><br>
			<dd>vi)	These guidelines shall be effective for the academic year beginning September 1, 1972.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C1b">b</a>)	Adherence To The Calendar
<dt><br>
			<dt>A resolution of the Board of Trustees of the University, and a letter from Chancellor Boyer, May 23, 1972, stipulate that it is the policy of State University to fulfill its teaching commitment on each class day of the academic calendar.  Students who withdraw from academic work to participate, for example, in public affairs, do so by their own decision alone.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C1c">c</a>)	Religious Holidays
<dt><br>
			<dt>A letter from the Chancellor Gould, November 23, 1965, establishes University policy for religious holidays, which are defined to mean a situation in which absence for a half day or more from school or work is expected by a church or synagogue and is observed by most members of the faith.
<dt><br>
<dt>New York State Education Law Section 224-a requires campuses to excuse without penalty individual students absent from class because of religious beliefs and to provide equivalent opportunity to make up study or work requirements missed because of such absences.  Faculty are advised not to give examinations or require that papers be due on those holidays.  Students are required to notify faculty of their impending absence for religious purposes at least one class session in advance so that arrangements can be made for making up missed assignments, quizzes or tests.  Students are responsible for material presented  during their absence.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2"><i>2</A>.	LOCAL GUIDELINES</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2a">a</A>)	Faculty Assembly Guidelines For Both Semesters
<dt><br>
			<dd>i)	academically responsible calendar<br>
			<dd>ii)	at least 15 of each class day each semester<br>
			<dd>iii)	exams may be scheduled Saturday and Sunday

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2b">b)	Faculty Assembly Guidelines For Fall
<dt><br>
			<dd>i)	start after Labor Day<br>
			<dd>ii)	Thanksgiving break - 3 days<br>
			<dd>iii)	October recess - 2 days<br>
			<dd>iv)	finals exams end first semester - on or before December 22

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2c">c</A>)	Faculty Assembly Guidelines for Spring
<dt><br>
			<dd>i)	at least three weeks between semesters<br>
			<dd>ii)	two day spring break at 1/3 point of semester<br>
			<dd>iii)	week-long spring break at 2/3 point of semester<br>
			<dd>iv)	consideration given to establishing two senior farewell days before graduation
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2d">d</A>)	Reporting Final Grades
    <dt><br>
			<dt>The deadlines for reporting final grades will be included in published calendars.  Even though this deadline will be within forty-eight hours after the last scheduled exam, submission of grades within forty-eight hours after each instructor's exam is hereby encouraged.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C2e">e</A>)	Off-Campus (Extension) Courses
<dt><br>
			<dt>Off-campus extension courses do not follow the regular calendar and the number of meetings for graduate courses is determined by the Director of Graduate and Continuing Education.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09C3"><i>3</A>.	APPROVED ACADEMIC CALENDARS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Approved academic calendars are found in <A HREF="../Appendices/appen11.html">Appendix XI</A>.
<dt><br></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
<B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="S9D.html">Continue to next section</A></B>
