<BR>
<center><strong>IX. ACADEMIC AFFAIRS</strong></center>
<dt><br><BR>

	<dt><A NAME="09B"><b>B</A>.	ACADEMIC POLICIES</b>
     <dt><br>
	<BLOCKQUOTE><dt>NOTE:	Complete details and specifics as well as additional academic policies and procedures may be found in the Undergraduate Catalog, the Graduate Catalog, and the Advising Manual.

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
	<dt><A NAME="09A1"><i>1</A>.	REQUIREMENTS FOR UNDERGRADUATE ADMISSION</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><A NAME="09B1a">a</A>)	Standard Freshman Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Admissions process at SUNY Potsdam is highly individualized.  Each application is thoroughly evaluated by Admissions officers to discover the wide variety of skills and talent sought in members of the freshman class.  Applications are judged on the basis of objective criteria, such as grade- point average, class rank and SAT or ACT scores.  Applicants are also judged on their capacity to enrich college life in some fashion - be it scholastically or through extracurricular activities.  We welcome your application and encourage you to visit the College.
<dt><br>
<dt>SUNY Potsdam operates on a rolling admission policy whereby applications are reviewed beginning in January and when all required credentials have been received.  Students are informed of acceptance soon thereafter.

		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1b">b</A>)	Transfer Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students applying for transfer admission should:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Be graduates of fully accredited high schools or private secondary schools (a General Equivalency Diploma satisfies this requirement).
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Have a minimum college grade point average of C/2.0 or better for all academic work attempted at the college level.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Have completed 24 or more semester hours of college-level liberal arts courses.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Be in good academic standing and eligible to return to all previously attended colleges and universities.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1c">c</A>)	Education Opportunity Program (EOP) Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>EOP is a special SUNY-sponsored program established to provide capable students with limited financial resources and inadequate academic preparation the opportunity to pursue a college education.
<dt><br>
<dt>To be considered for admission to EOP the student must:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Be a New York State resident.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Have earned a New York State high school diploma or                     its equivalent.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Be ineligible for admission under normal standards                     but able to show the campus EOP admission committee                     potential for completing a college program.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Be in need of financial assistance. 
</dl>
		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1d">d</A>)	Non-Traditional Student Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>SUNY Potsdam is committed to the ideals and goals of lifelong learning.  In keeping with this philosophy, admission of non- traditional students is based more on current potential for successful completion of a college program than on high school records or test scores.

<dt><br>
<dt>Prospective students should possess a high school diploma (or  equivalent) and the desire and motivation to pursue a college education.  Although official high school and/or college transcripts are required, greater emphasis is placed on current potential.
<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1e">e</A>)	Deferred Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students admitted to the college in a curriculum other than Music who elect not to enter in the semester for which they are admitted may request that admission be deferred.  This request may be granted for a mzximum of one year.  Application files will be held in inactive status during periods of deferral and will be reactivated without payment of additional application fees.

		<dt><br>
		<dt>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1f">f</A>)	Early Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>SUNY Potsdam will offer early admission to exceptionally well-qualified high school juniors and seniors.  Students applying for early admission must possess a "B" average or above in their course work and test scores indicating strong potential for college-level work.  They should have 14 or more academic units from high school in the areas of social studies, English, foreign language, science and mathematics.  In addition, applicants for early admission must demonstrate the necessary maturity to adjust to college life.  This is accomplished through submission of at least two letters of recommendation (including one from the high school principal or guidance counselor and one from a teacher of an academic subject).  Any course work taken at SUNY Potsdam that is applicable to high school graduation requirements must be approved by the high school principal or school counselor.

		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1g">g</A>)	Crane School of Music Admission
<dt><br>
			<dt>In addition to the above special procedures for admission to Crane School of Music apply and are found in the Undergraduate Catalog as appropriate.

		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1h">h</A>)	Admission To A Second Baccalaureate Degree
<dt><br>
			<dt>A student may be admitted to SUNY Potsdam in matriculated status to pursue a second bachelor's degree, which major shall be declared at the time of admission.  Requirements for completion of a second bachelor's degree include the following:

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
	<dt>i)	A second bachelor's degree may be earned when a student  completes at least 30 semester hours of degree.  These credits shall be exclusive of any earned in physical education or recreational activity courses.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Matriculation for a second bachelor's degree requires completion of all major and cognate requirements for the second major.  Liberal Arts courses taken in satisfaction of General Education distribution requirements in the first degree will apply to the second degree as appropriate.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Of the additional hours of coursework for the second bachelor's degree, at least 15 must be taken at the upper division level in the major.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Of the additional hours of course work required for the second bachelor's degree, at least 30 must be taken in residence at SUNY Potsdam.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="09B1i">i</A>)	Admission Of A Non-Matriculated Student
<dt><br>
			<Dt>Non-matriculated students are those who are pursuing courses for reasons other than to obtain a SUNY Potsdam degree.  The three categories of guest students are listed below, along with the corresponding admissions requirements.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt><A NAME="09B1ii">i</A>)	Current High School Students
<dt><br>
				<dt>Admission is contingent upon:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a) possessing a minimum 80 grade point average in a Regents/college preparatory curriculum as reported on an official high school transcript.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b) a letter of endorsement (from either the high school principal or guidance counselor) that addresses the academic, emotional and social development of the student.
</dl>
			<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B1iiii">ii</A>)	High School Graduates
<dt><br>
				<dt>High school graduates who do not meet the admissions criteria for matriculated status or who wish only casual enrollment may be admitted as non-matriculated students by submitting evidence of having received a high school diploma (or equivalent).  If such students have attended other postsecondary institutions, evidence of a 2.0 GPA or better must also be submitted from all previously attended institutions.

			<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B1iiii">iii</A>)	College Graduates
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students who present evidence of having earned the baccalaureate degree may enroll for further study.  Those seeking personal or career enrichment are admitted on a space-available basis.  Those who have been denied admission to graduate school may enroll to pursue remedial or prerequisite courses up to a maximum of 30 semester hours.

			<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B1iiv">iv</A>)	Students matriculated in other Colleges or Universities
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
		</dl>	<dt><A NAME="09B2"><i>2</A>.	REQUIREMENTS FOR GRADUATE ADMISSION</i>

	<dl>	<dt>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
			<dt><A NAME="09B2a">a</A>)	Matriculated Status

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt><A NAME="09B2a1">1</A>)	Provisional Admission - Granted to students who have applied and been reviewed for admission to a graduate degree program but who do not meet certain minimum requirements; e.g., submission of satisfactory scores on the LAST and ATS-W portions of the New York State Teacher Certification Exams (NYSTCE) where required, undergraduate prerequisites, etc.                          

			<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B2a2">2</A>)	Full Admission - Granted to students who have satisfied all admission requirements.
</dl>
<dt><br>
		<dt>In order to be considered for matriculated status (Provisional Admission or Full Admission) students must fulfill the following criteria:
<dt><br>
		<dt><b>Master of Science in Education</b>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>1.	submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university
<dt><br>
			<dt>2.	a minimum undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale or A=4.0); if the applicant's GPA is below the minumum, he or she will be required to take further undergraduate course work in order to raise the GPA to 2.75.
<dt><br>
			<dt>3.	a "Letter of Intent" written by the applicant including professional goals as applied to the program indicated
<dt><br>
			<dt>4.	non-refundable processing fee of $50.00
<dt><br>
			<dt>5.	submission of proof of current provisional or permanent certification in teaching consistent with that of the proposed graduate study.
</dl>
<dt><br>
		<dt><b>Master of Science in Teaching</b>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>1.	submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university
<dt><br>
			<dt>2.	a minimum undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale of A=4.0); if the applicant's GPA is below the minimum, he or she will be required to take further undergraduate course work in order to raise the GPA to 2.75.
<dt><br>
			<dt>3.	a "Letter of Intent" written by the applicant including professional goals as applied to the program indicated
<dt><br>
			<dt>4.	non-refundable processing fee of $50.00
<dt><br>
			<dt>5.	submission of three letters of recommendation
</dl>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Note:	a satisfactory score on the LAST portion of the New York State Teacher Certification Exam (NYSTCE) is required for Full Admission; the ATS-W portion of the NYSTCE is required prior to being placed in a student teaching position
<dt><br>
		<dt><b>Master of Arts</b>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>1.	submission of an offical transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university
<dt><br>
			<dt>2.	a minimum undergraduate GPA of 2.75 in the final 60 semester hours of undergraduate study (based on a scale of A=4.0)
<dt><br>
			<dt>3.	a "Letter of Intent" written by the applicant including professional goals as applied to the program indicated
<dt><br>
			<dt>4.	non-refundable processing fee of $50.00
<dt><br>
			<dt>5.	submission of three letters of recommendation
</dl>
<dt><br>
		<dt><b>Master of Music</b>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>1.	Submission of an official transcript of an earned baccalaureate degree from an accredited college or university
<dt><br>
			<dt>2.	Submission of two letters of recommendation
<dt><br>
			<dt>3.	Non-refundable processing fee of $50.00
<dt><br>
			<dt>4.	A minimum undergraduate GPA of 3.0 (A=4.0).  Applicants with a GPA between 2.75 and 3.0 may be considered for Provisional Admission upon the recommendation of the Graduate Program Committee.  A student admitted into the graduate program with provisional status is limited in the amount of course work taken during the first semester (12 credits for fall or spring semester, six credits for summer session).  The student's progress will be reviewed by the Graduate Program Committee after which time the student may be considered for Full Admission, continue provisionally, or be dismissed from the program.
<dt><br>
			<Dt>5.	Applicants must demonstrate competence in their area of concentration.
<dt><br>
			<dt>6.	Submission of three letters of recommendation
</dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><br>
	<dt>b)	Non-matriculated or Non-Degree Status
<dt><br>
	<dt>Granted to students who have an interest in graduate study but who have not yet applied for admission into amaster's degree program.  A non-matriculated graduate student is limited to taking a maximum of 12 graduate credits on a non-matriculated basis.  Upon completion of the 12 graduate credits, if not before, the student is required to apply for formal admission to a master's degree program and must be granted Provisional or Full Admission before being allowed to register for further course work.
<dt><br>
<Dt><b>Seniors Admitted to Course Work for Graduate Credit Space-available basis only</b>
<dt><br>
<dt>A senior may apply to enroll in course work for graduate credit during the final portion of undergraduate study.  An application must be received by the Office of Graduate and Continuing Education at least two weeks prior to registration.  In addition, applicants from institutions other than SUNY Potsdam must submit a certified statement of approval from their college registrar.  If approved, students may not register for the graduate course work until after all graduate students have registered.
<dt><br>
<dt>Conditions for approval include the following:
<dt><br>
	<dt>1)	A 3.0 cumulative average with at least 75 credits earned on a numerical basis.
<dt><br>
	<dt>2)	No more than nine credit hours needed to complete the baccalaureate program.
<dt><br>
	<dt>3)	No more than six credits of graduate study may be attempted prior to completion of the baccalaureate program.
<Dt><br>
	<dt>4)	Total course load, graduate and undergraduate, not to exceed 15 credit hours.
<dt><br>
	<dt>In exceptional circumstances, waivers to the above may be granted by the Dean of Education and Graduate Programs.
<dt><br>
	<dt><b>Foreign Graduate Student</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>In addition to the requirements for Full Admission, a foreign student must submit satisfactory scores from the Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL).  The Office of Graduate and Continuing Education will mail Foreign Student Application (FSA) forms.  TOEFL scores must be submitted before Federal Form I-20 can be issued.  There, unfortunately, is no funding available for foreign students.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3"><i>3</A>.	UNDERGRADUATE STUDENT CLASSIFICATIONS</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
			<dt><A NAME="09B3a">a</A>)	Matriculated Students
<dt><br>
			<Dt>These students have completed the SUNY application form, paid an application fee, had credentials reviewed by the Admissions Office, been accepted as a degree candidate in a particular curriculum, registered for classes and attended them at least one day.  Such students are considered to be matriculated until they graduate, thus the phrase "Once a matriculant, always a matriculant."  Matriculated students may not become non- matriculated students before completion of the degree, except at another college or university.  

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3b">b</A>)	Non-Matriculated Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>These students also go by other informal names (e.g., guest, casual, special, non-degree, etc.).  They have not been formally admitted to the College and are not degree candidates.  Normally 30 semester hours taken at SUNY Potsdam as a non-matriculated undergraduate may be applied toward the requirements for a baccalaureate.  Acceptance of more than 30 semester hours taken as a student in this status may be approved by the dean of the school in which the student is accepted for matriculation.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3c">c</A>)	Full-Time Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students who are registered for 12 or more credit hours in a given semester are considered full-time.  These students pay a uniform tuition and college fee.  Full- time students may subsequently become part-time students and vice versa.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3d">d</A>)	Part-Time Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students who are registered for less than 12 credit hours in a given semester are considered part-time.  These students pay tuition and fees by the credit hour.  Part-time students may subsequently become full-time students and vice versa.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3e">e</A>)	Class Standing
                    <dt><br>
			<dt>Matriculated students are classified according to the                number of credits earned as follows:
<center>
<table width=100>
<tr><td>Class 1  (Freshman)</td>              <td>0-23 semester hours</td></tr>
<tr><td>Class 2  (Sophomore)</td>            <td>24-56 semester hours</td></tr>
<tr><td>Class 3  (Junior)</td>               <td>57-87 semester hours</td></tr>
<tr><td>Class 4  (Senior)</td>               <td>88-   semester hours</td></tr>
</table>
</center>
		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3f">f</A>)	Lower Division
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students who have earned fewer than 57 hours are traditionally known as freshmen or sophomores.  Such students normally register for course work designated at either the 100 or 200 level.  Likewise, courses offered at the 100 or 200 level are described as lower division offerings.  It should be noted that all work taken at a two-year, community, or junior college is considered to be lower division work.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3g">g</A>)	Upper Division
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students who have earned 57 or more credits are traditionally known as juniors or seniors.  Such students typically register for courses at the 300 and 400 levels and occasionally (with special permission) may register for courses at the 500 level.  Courses designated at the 300 and 400 levels are likewise designated upper division offerings.  It should be noted that graduation requirements mandate completion of at least 45 credits of upper division work, 15 of which must be in the major.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3h">h</A>)	Transfer Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students completing a minimum of 12 semester hours of course work at another regionally accredited college or university subsequent to the summer following secondary school graduation, who are accepted and in turn apply that course work toward receiving a degree from SUNY Potsdam, are considered transfer students.
<dt><br>
<dt>Every student accepted in a SUNY Potsdam Bachelor of Arts of Bachelor of Music degree program, regardless of whether enrolling as a freshman or transfer, is bound by the same academic policies and procedures and must satisfactorily complete all specified requirements for the degree.
<dt><br>
<dt>Requirements for graduation are binding for six years from the date of one's initial college matriculation.  For transfer students, this date coincides with the initial matriculation date at the first college attended. This assures continuity of the academic advising process between two- and four-year programs.  Every student pursuing the Bachelor of Arts degree at SUNY Potsdam must complete a minimum of 30 semester hours of SUNY Potsdam course work, which includes 15 semester hours of the academic major.  Forty-five upper-division hours are also required for the bachelor's degree.  (Music majors should consult requirements specified for the Bachelor of Music degree.)
<dt><br>
<dt>Transfer students who complete the Associate in Arts degree (A.A.) or Associate in Science degree (A.S.), including an academic program considered parallel to that which they pursue at SUNY Potsdam, will, assuming satisfactory progress, be guaranteed the opportunity to complete the Bachelor of Arts degree within four semesters of full-time enrollment.  Students who pursue New York State teacher certification may, in some cases, need to enroll for one additional semester in order to complete the professional semester component (student teaching).
<dt><br>
<dt>Class standing is determined by the number of semester hours completed by an individual (includes both Potsdam and transfer course work).  Transfer students entering SUNY Potsdam upon completion of the A.A. or A.S. degree are granted full junior class standing.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt>1)	All students transferring to SUNY Potsdam from a regionally accredited two-year college and graduating with an Associate in Arts (AA) or an Associate in Science (AS) degree will be admitted with full junior standing.  The Freshman Experience and Modes of Inquiry components of the SUNY Potsdam General Education Program will be considered complete for these students.  In addition, the Freshman Experience component of the SUNY Potsdam General Education Program will be considered complete for a transfer student admitted to SUNY Potsdam having previously completed a minimum of 45 semester hours of liberal arts course work.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3i">i</A>)	Undeclared Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>All students matriculating in curricula offered by the School of Liberal Studies and leading to the B.A. degree are initially designated as undeclared students.  Their status changes only when they formally choose and declare a major by completing a major declaration form with a department.

		<dt><br>
			<dt><A NAME="09B3j">j</A>)	Non-traditional Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students entering or returning to College after a break in their education (e.g., after raising a family, serving in the Armed Forces, etc.) are termed non-traditional students or adult learners.  They may be matriculated or new freshman etc.
<dt><br>
<dt>For the purpose of housing exemptions, non-traditional status will be interpreted by a combination of age and post-secondary life experiences.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 2 -->
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<BR>
