<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>IX. ACADEMIC AFFAIRS</strong></center>
<BR>

<dt><br>
<B>B.  ACADEMIC POLICIES</B>
<dd><dl>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B10"><i>10</A>.	DEADLINES FOR WITHDRAWAL FROM COLLEGE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>For students withdrawing from college after registration but before the end of the Add/Drop period - no notation of W or W* necessary.
<dt><br>
<dt>For students withdrawing from college after the ADD/DROP  period but before the "withdrawal deadline (end of eighth week)" - notations of W for all coursework or W* with appropriate documentation of an emergency and approval by the Academic Services Center or dean.
<dt><br>
		<dt>For students withdrawing from college after the end of the eighth week but before the end of the semester - notation     of earned grades, unless an emergency withdrawal (W*) has been approved.
<dt><br>
<dt>Students withdrawing from college after completion of the semester - receive earned grades only.
<dt><br>
<dt>For the student who finds that he/she must interrupt or terminate college studies, the Academic Services Center provides counseling assistance and requests an exit interview.  Withdrawal from college is perceived as a significant and major decision in a student's life, and is treated accordingly.  Withdrawing students must initiate withdrawal procedures in the Academic Services Center.  A student who fails to register in any semester is administratively withdrawn. 

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B11"><i>11</A>.	FINAL EXAMINATION POLICY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dd>i)	A final examination is a comprehensive written test administered at the end of a course.  It is designed to assess a student's knowledge of, and familiarity with, all, or a substantial part, of the content and/or skills associated with a given course in a given semester.
       <dt><br>
		<dd>ii)	At the conclusion of every semester, a two-hour period will be arranged for each class to provide time for summation and evaluation.  Except as specified below, a final examination may be administered only at this arranged two-hour period.
<dt><br>
		<dd>iii)	No test of any kind may be given during the last week of classes unless a final examination is also scheduled during the regular final examination period.
<dt><br>
		<dd>iv)	No student shall be required to take more than two    examinations in one day if they file an appropriate request in a timely manner.
<dt><br>
<dd>(a)	If a student has more than two examinations in one day, the middle examinations(s) must be rescheduled if the student requests.
<dt><br>
			<dd>(b)	A student must request rescheduling two weeks before the last day of classes.  This request must be in written form and must be filed with the professor with copies to the department  chair and the dean of the School(s) under whose  jurisdiction the course(s) in question is (are) offered.
<dt><br>
			<dd>(c)	The appropriate dean has the final responsibility for the rescheduling of the examination(s).  The rescheduled examination(s)  must normally occur at a time during the final examination week.
<dt><br>
		<dd>v)	Provision will be made for the scheduling of examinations for combined sections of courses involving at least three sections or one hundred students.  The request for such scheduling must be made at the time the semester class schedule is submitted by the department.
<dt><br>
		<dd>vi)	The above policy does not apply to so-called take- home examinations or term papers.  Questions relating to the possible applicability of the policy to oral examinations, studio classes, laboratory tests and other forms of testing should, in cases of doubt, be referred to the appropriate deans.  The deans shall make exceptions to the policy wherever circumstances justify them.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B12"><i>12</A>.	CHANGING RECORDED GRADES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Any change in grades already recorded in the Registrar's Office must be made by the instructor who awarded the grade or by the department chairperson if the instructor is not able to do so (for example, because of leave, resignation, etc.), or by the department chairperson acting in accordance with departmental procedures concerning grade appeal.
<dt><br>
<dt>The only permissible reasons for changing a grade are (a) an error in recording or computation, (b) removal of a grade of "Incomplete," (c) to reflect the judgment of a department acting in accordance with established departmental procedures concerning grade appeal.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B13"><i>13</A>.	ACADEMIC HONESTY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Students have an obligation to themselves and to their fellow students to uphold the integrity of their institution and of higher learning itself by a) refusing to participate, either directly or indirectly, in acts of dishonesty, and b) discouraging such acts by others.  One who collaborates with another in an act of dishonesty shares the guilt of the offense.  Cheating, in all of its manifestations, is a deplorable and dishonest activity, a betrayal of personal values, and contrary to the basic goals of learning and individual development to which students, teachers, and the College are committed.  Students must be fully aware of what constitutes academic dishonesty; claims of ignorance cannot be used to justify or rationalize dishonest acts. Plagiarism, a form of cheating, is the most prevalent expression of academic dishonesty.  Plagiarism is the misrepresentation of any part of another's work as one's own, and is equivalent to fraud.  It involves giving or receiving non permitted or unacknowledged aid on any assignment of self-initiated endeavor, such as examinations, papers, research reports, laboratory exercises, and computer programs, as well as art, music, and theater projects and compositions.  Of special note and concern is the fraudulent use of purchased research papers.  Specific information concerning prescribed conduct and judicial procedures is provided in the Code of Student Rights, Responsibilities and Conduct, the Student Government Constitution, and other relevant documents prepared by individual departments and faculty members.
<dt><br>
<dt>The form of plagiarism called "cribbing" when performed in tests and examinations is theft, no less serious than any other theft because it involves words or ideas rather than material property.  It is also unethical to try to obtain details of a quiz or examination ahead of time.  The temptation is greatest perhaps in multiple-section courses, where an instructor may use the same questions for different sections.  In such case, the instructor will take reasonable precautions to discourage dishonesty, but the prime responsibility rests with the student.
<dt><br>
		<dt>In the preparation of research papers, book reports, essays, compositions and speeches the student will generally utilize  information gained from others.  It is absolutely necessary to acknowledge this help and information.  Manuals of instruction in the technique of preparing reports and papers are available in the Library and the College Bookstore; such writer's guides as Writing:  A College Handbook or the Harbrace College Handbook contain sections on proper form for documentation.  The student's responsibility is to learn and apply the general and specific requirements.
<dt><br>
<dt>Disciplinary action against those who have been judged guilty of any breach of academic honesty may include:  a) grade reduction on the assignment in question, b) a failing grade in the course, and/or c) suspension or dismissal from the College.
<dt><br>
<dt>Note:	It is a violation of New York State law for a student to utilize the services of a term paper writer.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B14"><i>14</A>.	COURSE SYLLABI STATEMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Beginning on the first day of each class the instructor shall make available to each student (and deposit in the Office of the Dean) a current syllabus containing information on course objectives, general description of course material, listing of course activities, evaluation procedures, grading policy, office hours and office phone number.  Departments are encouraged to publish pamphlets with detailed course descriptions in time for students to consult them before Advance Registration.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B15"><i>15</A>.	CLASS ATTENDANCE REQUIREMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Instructors are responsible for determining the details of attendance for their courses according to their own philosophy and the nature of their courses.  Instructors may wish to consult with their students in this matter.  Attendance requirements should be made explicit at the opening sessions of each course.
<dt><br>
<dt>Students should be evaluated on the basis of achievement.  Students are responsible for meeting all academic requirements of a course and to follow the attendance policy announced by individual instructors.
<dt><br>
<dt>Students should be allowed to make up work in the case of absences beyond their control.
<dt><br>
<dt>An assignment to attend a specific event (lecture, concert, special event, field trip) made by one instructor may conflict with the student's schedule in other courses or with other curricular-related obligations.  Assignments of a general nature may avoid the scheduling problem, for example, requiring a student in a music class to attend a certain number of concerts or recitals in the course of a semester.  College policy is not to limit the instructor's option to direct his/her students to special resources.  However, the instructor should keep in mind the total obligations of the student, as well as the expenses that may be incurred.
<dt><br>
<dt>Students may not be charged for transportation on field trips required as part of their curriculum, unless such charges are classified as special service with the approval of the University Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs.
<dt><br>
<dt>Attendance alone should not be a factor in determining the final grade in a course except where direct participation and/or performance are included among the instructional methods being used.  In such a course, the relation of attendance to achievement should be made clear at the first meeting.
<dt><br>
<dt>Under New York State Education Law (subsection 224-A) the following is also applicable:  S224-A.  Students unable because of religious beliefs to attend classes on certain days.
<dt><br>
		<dd>a)	No person shall be expelled from or be refused admission as a student to an institution of higher education for the reason that he/she is unable, because of his/her religious beliefs, to attend classes or to participate in any examination, study or work requirements on a particular day or days.
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	Any student in an institution of higher education who is unable, because of his/her religious beliefs, to attend  classes on a particular day or days shall, because of such absence on the particular day or days, be excused from any examination or any study or work requirements.
<dt><br>
		<dd>c)	It shall be the responsibility of the faculty and of the administrative officials of each institution of higher education to make available to each student who is absent from school, because of his/her religious beliefs, an equivalent opportunity to make up any examination, study or work requirements which he/she may have missed because of such absence on any particular day or days.  No fees of any kind shall be charged by the institution for making available to the said student such equivalent opportunity.
<dt><br>
		<dd>d)	If classes, examinations, study or work requirements are held on Friday after four o'clock post meridian or on Saturday, similar or makeup classes, examinations, study or work requirements shall be made available on other days, where it is possible and practicable to do so.  No special fees shall be charged to the student for these classes, examinations, study or work requirements held on other days.
<dt><br>
		<dd>e)	In effectuating the provisions of this section, it shall be the duty of the faculty and of the administrative officials of each institution of higher education to exercise the fullest measure of good faith.  No adverse or prejudicial effects shall result to any student because of his/her availing himself/herself of the provisions of this section.
<dt><br>
		<dd>f)	Any student, who is aggrieved by the alleged failure of any faculty or administrative officials to comply in good faith with the provisions of this section, shall be entitled to maintain an action or proceeding in the supreme court of the county in which such institution of higher education is located for the enforcement of his/her rights under this section.
<dt><br>
		<dd>g)	A copy of this section shall be published by each institution of higher education in the catalog of such institution containing the listing of available courses.
<dt><br>
		<dd>h)	As used in this section, the term "institution of higher education" shall mean schools under the control of the Board of Trustees of the State University of New York or of the Board of Higher Education of the City of New York or any Community College.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B16"><i>16</A>.	DENIAL OF CONTINUATION IN MAJOR OR PROGRAM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>With the approval of the appropriate committee of the School and its Dean, and the Provost, departments of the Crane School of Music, the School of Arts and Sciences, and the School of Education may establish academic standards for their majors and may deny continuance in the major to a student who does not meet the standards.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B17"><i>17</A>.	TIME LIMITS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B17a">a</A>)	Bachelor's Degree
<dt><br>
			<dt>Requirements for graduation as stated in the Undergraduate Catalog, in effect at the time of the student's matriculation, shall not be binding on the College for more than six years after the date of matriculation.  A student who has not completed the degree during that time period must pursue graduation requirements as stated by the current Undergraduate Catalog, in effect at the beginning of the seventh year.
<dt><br>
<dt>Also a student may elect to follow later graduation requirements in effect subsequent to matriculation, but must then finish those requirements completely.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B18"><i>18</A>.	ACADEMIC GRIEVANCES AND STUDENT APPEALS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The student grievance procedure to provide a prompt, equitable and efficient method for the resolution of a student grievance is given in <A HREF="../Appendices/APPEN17.html">Appendix XVII.</a>

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B19"><i>19</A>.	ACADEMIC HONORS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B19a">a</A>)	Undergraduate Students

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B19ai">i</A>)	President's List
<dt><br>
				<dt>At the end of each semester the College will compile a list of students who have satisfactorily completed a minimum of fifteen credit hours in that semester, of which at least twelve were numerically graded with an average of 3.5 or better.

			</dl>
<BLOCKQUOTE><dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="ii)  Dean's List">ii )	Dean's List</A>
<dt><br>
				<dt>At the end of each semester, the College will compile a list of students who have satisfactorily completed a minimum of fifteen credit hours in that semester, of which at least twelve were numerically graded with an average between 3.25 and 3.49.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Graduation With Honors">iii)	Graduation With Honors</A>
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students qualifying for degrees of distinction must have completed a minimum of 60 academic semester hours at SUNY Potsdam, of which at least 75% must have been taken under the numerical grading system.  Such students will receive a degree of cum laude for a cumulative average of 3.25 to 3.49; a degree magna cum laude for a cumulative average of 3.5 to 3.74; and a degree summa cum laude for a cumulative average of 3.75 or above.
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B19b">b</A>)	Graduate Students
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students completing master's degree requirements with a cumulative grade point average of 3.90 or higher are granted the degree WITH DISTINCTION.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20"><i>20</A>.	REFUND POLICY</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20a">a</A>)	Tuition
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students who withdraw from the College will be refunded tuition and room payment in accordance with the following schedule:
<dt><br>
<dt>See refund policy chart in catalog.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20b">b</A>)	Financial Aid
<dt><br>
			<dt>If financial aid exceeds the student's College bill, a refund will be issued to the student.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20c">c)	College Fee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College Fee is not refundable under ordinary circumstances.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20d">d</A>)	Student Government Association (SGA) Fee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The SGA Fee is refunded upon request and in accordance with the organization's regulations.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20e">e</A>)	New Student And Musical Equipment Maintenance
<dt><br>
			<dt>The New Student Fee and the Musical Equipment Maintenance Fee are refunded only if a student does not register or has paid the fee previously.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20f">f</A>)	Room
<dt><br>
			<dt>The following policies shall apply to tuition liabilities and refunds for students cancelling their registration at units of the State University.  A student who is given permission to cancel his or her registration shall be liable for payment of tuition in accodance with the following schedule.<BR>
<BR>

<TABLE CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 BORDER=3><CAPTION ALIGN=TOP>LIABILITY DURING INDICATED WEEK</CAPTION>
