		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20g">g)	Board
<dt><br>
			<dt>Board refunds are made in accordance with the policies of P.A.C.E.S. dining service.
</dl><BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE><dt><A NAME="09B20h">h)	Educational Technology Fee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Educational Technology Fee is refunded upon request and in accordance with the Telemedia Office's regulations.
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20i">i)	Intercollegiate Athletic Fee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Intercollegiate Athletic Fee is not refundable under ordinary circumstances.
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B20j">j)	Health Fee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Health Fee is refunded upon request and in accordance with the Health Office's regulations.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<BLOCKQUOTE><dt><A NAME="09B21"><i>21</A>.	GRADUATE ASSISTANTS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B21a">a</A>)	Graduate Assistantships</BLOCKQUOTE>



Graduate Assistantships (GA's) are awarded annually to students who have demonstrated a high degree of academic excellence and professional competence.  A limited number of GA's with a stipend of $3,000 ($1,500/semester) and a tuition scholarship are available for the academic year based on the availability of funding.  Graduate Assistantships are awarded typically on the basis of merit, and it is assumed that GA's will be associated with their major departments and/or School to supplement their graduate degree program.
<BR>
<BR>
Graduate Assistantships in The Crane School of Music are available to qualified full-time graduate students.  Upon completing the application materials for admission to the degree program, the applicant for a Graduate Assistantship in music must submit a separate letter of application, resume, and appropriate supporting materials (i.e., letter of recommendation, documentation of skill/experience/achievement in areas of expertise) to the Graduate Advisor in The Crane School of Music by March 15.  Assistantships will be awarded on the basis of student admission to the program, academic credentials, and skill/experience in the area of each designated assistantship.
<BR>
<BR>
Residence Life assistantships are available each year for qualified applicants capable of serving as the director of a residence hall of some 200 students.  Remuneration consists of a stipend of $5,000, a board plan, a benefits package, and a furnished apartment for the academic year.</BLOCKQUOTE>
		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><dt><A NAME="09B21b">b</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>Consideration is given only to applicants who plan to earn a graduate degree at SUNY Potsdam.  Assistantships cannot be awarded to part- time students or to non-matriculated students. 
<BR>
<BR>
<dt>Candidates for an assistantship must submit applications for both an assistantship and for a graduate degree program.  Official transcripts of all previous collegiate-level work and three letters of recommendation must be submitted.
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B21c">c</A>)	Work Guidelines
<dt><br>
			<dt>Full-time graduate assistants receiving the stipend plus tuition scholarship may be associated with their major departments for an average of 20 hours each week.  Their responsibilities will be determined by each of the academic departments involved.

<dt><br>
<dt>The number of credit hours for which a graduate assistant is registered ordinarily shall be at least nine semester hours and shall not exceed 15 semester hours without the approval of the department and/or School.  Graduate Assistants who wish to take advantage of the full tuition scholarship must be registerd full-time (at least 12 credit hours).
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09B21d">d</A>)	Applications
<dt><br>
			<dt>All inquiries and application requests should be directed to the Graduate Studies Office, SUNY Potsdam, Potsdam, New York 13676.  Applications and all supporting materials must be received by April 1.  If interested in a Residence Life assistantship, applicants must contact the Office of Residence Life, Sisson Hall.
<BR>
<BR>
<dt>Announcement of awards will be made on or about May 1. 
<BR>
<BR>
<dt><A NAME="09B21e">e</A>)	Graduate Reading Internships
<BR>
<BR>
A limited number of graduate reading internships are awarded annually to students who enroll in the Master of Science in Education degree program in Reading.  Students who qualify for the annual stipend of $5,000 work in an elementary or secondary school 15 hours per week and gain practical hands-on experience under the guidance of the school's reading specialist.  Students graduating from this program become eligible for permanent certification in their area of certification and qualify for provisional certification (K-12) as a reading specialist.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>
