<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter 9  D</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>IX. ACADEMIC AFFAIRS</strong></center><br>
<dd><dl><BR>

<dt><A NAME="09D"><b>D</A>.	ACADEMIC SERVICES AND FACILITIES</b>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D1"><i>1</A>.	COLLEGE LIBRARIES</i>

		<dt><br>

	<dd><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="9D1a">a)</A>	Crumb Library, which seats up to 600 persons, is located in the center of the academic quadrangle.  It is open 96 hours a week and houses more than 955,000 items, including 350,000 bound volumes, 605,000 microforms and other non-book materials, 23,000 federal and state documents and 1,200 active periodicals, all of which are accessible through the libraries' on-line catalog.  An array of specialized equipment, such as copiers, microform readers, and reader-printers, audio equipment and aids for handicapped users, are available for use with materials in various formats.  The professional staff is dedicated to helping students find and use information sources of all kinds.
<dt><br>
		<dd><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="9D1b">b)</A>	The Crane Music Library maintains the most extensive music collection in Northern New York State.  The collection includes 16,800 books, 24,000 music scores, 16,000 sound recordings and tapes of performances at Crane dating back to the late 1940s.  The library's audio facilities include ten listening rooms and 29 listening carrels.  Also located in the library are a computer lab and Computer Resource Center.
</dl>
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D2"><i>2.	ARTS AND PERFORMANCE FACILITIES</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D2a">a</A>)	College Theater
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College Theater for drama productions is divided into a main stage, a modified proscenium format that seats 300, and a Black Box Theater which seats about 100 and provides the opportunity for non-traditional theatrical events.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D2b">b</A>)	Dance Facilities
<dt><br>
			<dt>Facilities for dance include studios for rehearsals and workshops equipped with accompaniment instruments, sound equipment, and a costume shop, special classroom for dance history and access to the College Theater and Snell Music Theater for performances.  

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D2c">c</A>)	Brainerd Hall (Fine Arts)
<dt><br>
			<dt>This building houses separate studios for pottery, sculpture, printmaking, painting, design, drawing, and photography, special classrooms for art history, a student computer graphics lab, and a gallery for displaying exhibitions by students, faculty, and guest artists.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D2d">d</A>)	The Julia E. Crane Music Center
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Julia E. Crane Music Center is a five structure complex - featuring the Helen M. Hosmer Concert Hall, a performance facility that will accommodate an audience of 1,400 and the Sara M. Snell Music Theater, a facility for production of lyric theater and dance which seats 450 persons.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D3"><i>3</A>.	LABORATORIES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Laboratory facilities are maintained by the Departments of Anthropology, English, Modern Languages, Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Geology, Mathematics, and Psychology.  The School of Education maintains a computer lab.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D4"><i>4</A>.	COMPUTER FACILITIES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Information Services Division provides support for academic and administrative computing services through the Distributed Computing/Telemedia and Central Computing departments.  Consultation and problem-solving services, as well as many other support services and computing resources, are available to faculty, staff and students.  Information regarding Banner, our student information and campus administration system (SICAS), should be directed to Central Computing (x2089).  Information regarding academic and administrative desktop computing, campus network services and student facilities should be directed to Distributed Computing/Telemedia (x2083).

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D5"><i>5</A>.	ACADEMIC SERVICES CENTER</i>
<Dt><br>
		<Dt>The Academic Services Center provides a variety of academic support services for students and faculty.  The Center oversees the following offices and programs.
<BR>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>ACADEMIC SERVICES
<BR>
This Office coordinates academic advising on campus, assigns faculty advisers for undeclared students, conducts academic review and responds to questions regarding senior audits, graduation status checks, graduation waivers, overloads, late adds, drops, S/U options and withdrawals, and medical withdrawals for Arts and Sciences students.  It also processes withdrawals from the college and coordinates the Learning to Learn program and the Tutoring Center.
<BR>
<BR>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="ACADEMIC TRANSFER SERVICES">ACADEMIC TRANSFER SERVICES</A>
<BR>
This office evaluates the transcripts of all courses transferred into SUNY Potsdam and does the initial advisement for incoming transfer students.
<BR>
<BR>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Disabled Student Services">DISABLED STUDENT SERVICES</A>
<BR>
This office is set up to assist students with physical or learning disabilities by working out appropriate academic accommodations and strategies for success.  It can assist even those students who are temporarily disabled by injuries or illness.
<BR>
<BR>
<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="Student Support Services">STUDENT SUPPORT SERVICES</A>
<BR>
This office provides academic, personal, financial, and career counseling and mentoring for students who qualify under the guidelines of the TRIO grant.  These qualifications include low income, disability, minority status, and first generation college students.</BLOCKQUOTE>

	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D6"><i>6</A>.	THE ASSOCIATED COLLEGES OF THE ST. LAWRENCE VALLEY</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D6a">a</A>)	Charter And Function
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Associated Colleges of the St. Lawrence Valley was chartered as a not-for-profit educational consortium by the Board of Regents of the University of the State of New York in January, 1970.  The Consortium's function is to develop cooperative relations among four institutions:  Clarkson University, SUNY Canton, Potsdam College and St. Lawrence University.  In creating the Associated Colleges, the four institutions sought:
<dt><br>
			<dd>.  To expand their students' educational opportunities<br>
			<dd>.  To share resources<br>			
			<dd>.  To avoid needless duplication<br>
			<dd>.  To make the best use of resources<br>
			<dd>.  To innovate through joint action

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D6b">b</A>)	Major Programs
<dt><br>
			<dd>Major programs include:
<dt><br>
			<dd>. Cross-registration for full-time undergraduates, full-time   graduate students and full-time faculty and staff  <br>
			<dd>. Cooperative curricula<br>
			<dd>. Performing Arts Series<br>
			<dd>. Library cooperation and delivery services<br>
			<dd>. Coordination of chemical waste removal<br>
			<dd>. Shared faculty<br>
			<dd>. Workshops on innovation and improvement in teaching for   faculty of the four campuses<br>
			<dd>. International student programs bringing international and American students of the four institutions together.<br>
			<dd>. Cooperative admissions offices' programs<br>
			<dd>. Annual Science Teachers Conference for college faculty and public school teachers<br>
			<dd>. Grant administration in relevant educational and cultural   areas.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D6c">c</A>)	Resources
<dt><br>
			<dt>The pooled resources of the Associated Colleges are comparable to those of many universities and include:
<dt><br>
			<dd>. 1,100+ faculty and administrative staff<br>
			<dd>. 900,000 volumes in four libraries<br>
			<dd>. 12,000 undergraduates<br>
			<dd>. Associate, baccalaureate, master's and doctoral programs<br>
			<dd>. Over 600 major cultural and special events yearly<br>
			<dd>. Over 80 academic departments<br>
			<dd>. Four computer centers<br>
			<dd>. Seven theaters and concert halls

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D6d">d</A>)	Office Location
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Office of the Associated College is located in Merritt Hall on the SUNY Potsdam campus.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="09D7"><i>7</A>.	THE COUNCIL OF EMERITUS PROFESSORS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>A Council of Emeritus Professors has been established at Potsdam College.  The goals of the Council are:
<dt><br>
		<dd>a)	To provide a forum and means of communication among the emeritus professors and between the emeritus professors and the College.
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	To act as a consultative body providing advice to the College, and specifically to the President, from time to time on the affairs of the College.
<dt><br>
		<dd>c)	To perform such other functions as may be deemed appropriate by the President of the College and the Council.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Council will consist of six emeritus professors, to serve on a rotating basis, with two members replaced each year.  The President of the College will appoint the chair on an annual basis from among the membership of the Council.  The initial members of the Council will be appointed by the President in consultation with colleagues.
<dt><br>
<dt>The Council will meet with the President at least once a semester, and more frequently if the President and the Council so desire.  The Council will also maintain contact with the emeritus professors on a regular basis, arrange social gatherings of the emeritus professors from time to time, represent the interests of the emeritus professors with respect to the College, and assist the College in drawing on the services and expertise of the emeritus professors.
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>
