[Please note.  These bylaws are continued in a second section.  There is a link at the end of this section for your convenience.]<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER><B>APPENDIX I
<BR>
<BR>
BYLAWS OF THE FACULTY OF THE<BR>
STATE UNIVERSITY COLLEGE AT POTSDAM</CENTER></B>
<BR>

<CENTER>PREAMBLE</CENTER>
<BR>


In recognition of the desirability of achieving maximum participation on the part of the Faculty in the decision-making process of this College, a process which affects the quality of the educational opportunities offered; in recognition of the need for establishing a system whereby each faculty member's voice may be heard through a representative body and whereby students may participate to a significant degree; in recognition of the requirement of the Policies of the Board of Trustees of the State University of New York that articles of governance which are consistent with the guidelines and policies set forth in said Policies be formulated by each faculty; and in accord with our belief that a system which includes a Faculty Assembly working with and through faculty committees is the most appropriate way to achieve a workable, flexible system capable of meeting the needs of this college; we, the faculty, do establish these by-laws.
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>Article I:  Name</CENTER>
<BR>


The name of this organization shall be the Faculty of the State University College at Potsdam.
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>Article II:   Membership</CENTER>
<BR>


Member shall be limited to the voting faculty.  Voting faculty shall consist of:
<BR>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>a.	The Chancellor and the Chief Administrative Officer of the college, and;
<BR>
<BR>

	b.	Members of the college community who are either "academic employees" or "professional staff," as defined in the Policies.</BLOCKQUOTE>
         
<CENTER>Article III:  Graduate Faculty</CENTER>
<BR>

The Graduate Faculty shall consist of those faculty members holding academic appointments who possess an earned doctorate or its equivalent as determined and justified by the department concerned, and who  have been recommended for membership in the Graduate Faculty by the department chairperson, the  appropriate deans, the Vice President for Academic Affairs, and appointed by the President of the College.  For faculty holding continuing appointment, any appointment to the Graduate Faculty shall be considered a permanent appointment to the Graduate Faculty; for faculty holding any other type of appointment, an appointment to the Graduate Faculty shall be for a period not to exceed the duration of their appointment to the University. 
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>Article IV:  Power</CENTER> 
<BR>

The Faculty shall be empowered to discuss and to recommend policy in all matters related to the College, and to make recommendations through the Faculty Assembly or by referendum of the Faculty to officers and administrative divisions of the State University and of the College at all levels.  The Faculty shall be empowered to act upon matters referred to it by the President of the College or the Faculty Assembly, to review the actions of the Faculty Assembly, to entertain petitions of faculty members who desire hearings, and to establish and amend these by-laws.
<BR>
<BR>


<CENTER>Article V:  Meetings</CENTER>
<BR>

Section 1.  Regular and Special Meetings
<BR>
<BR>

The Faculty shall be convened not less often than three times per year by the Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly.  In addition to these regular meetings, special meetings of the Faculty may be convened by either the President of the College or the Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly.  Such special meetings are to be limited in their business to the item(s) specified in the call of the meeting.  A special meeting of the Faculty shall be called by the Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly upon written petition of at least ten members of the voting faculty.
<BR>
<BR>


Section 2.  Agenda
<BR>
<BR>

An agenda pertinent to the business of the meeting shall be circulated one week prior to a scheduled meeting of the Faculty or as soon as practical in the case of a special meeting.  Non-agenda business may be introduced from the floor once the meeting's stated agenda is complete, but no non-agenda business may be introduced from the floor in the case of a special meeting.
<BR>
<BR>

Section 3.  Quorum
<BR>
<BR>

A quorum shall be required prior to the conduct of any business requiring a vote; a quorum shall be seventy-five members.  At meetings where ballots are signed for and received, as specified elsewhere in these by-laws, once
seventy-five members have signed for and received ballots, the number of 
signatures shall be the sole determinant of the presence of a quorum for consideration of those items of agenda for which such ballots have been provided.  A call for or direction of a secret ballot on any item of agenda for which ballots were not signed for and received shall be subject to the ordinary quorum requirements.
<BR>
<BR>

Section 4.  Parliamentarian
<BR>
<BR>

The Parliamentarian of the Faculty Assembly shall serve as Parliamentarian of the Faculty as well.
<BR>
<BR>

<CENTER>Article VI:  Committees</CENTER>
<BR>


Section 1.	Grievance Committee
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 1.	The Committee on Grievances will be a standing committee of the Faculty, with the power to hear and act on grievances in accordance with the policies and procedures stipulated in the Grievance Procedures of the State University College at Potsdam, except that this power shall not be exercised at such times as there is in force at collective bargaining agreement between representatives of the Professional Services Negotiating Unit and the State of New York incorporating grievance procedures.
<BR>
<BR>

	Subsection 2.	Duties of the Committee on Grievances will be to hear and act on grievances in accordance with the policies and procedures stipulated in the Grievance Procedures of the State University College at Potsdam.</BLOCKQUOTE>



Section 2.	Ad Hoc Committees
<BR>
<BR>

Ad hoc committees of the Faculty may be appointed by the Chairperson of 
the Faculty.  
<BR>
<BR>

Section 3.	Permanent Committees
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 1.	Permanent committees, with membership either appointed by the presiding officer or elected by the Faculty or the Faculty Assembly, as appropriate, may be established as ongoing bodies to insure faculty participation in matters which are neither ad-hoc nor policy- developing in nature.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 2.	Where the actions of a permanent committee lead to the development of policy proposals, such proposals shall be referred to the Executive Committee of the Faculty Assembly for referral or action.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<CENTER>Article VII:  The Faculty Assembly</CENTER>
<BR>

The Faculty Assembly is the representative governing body of the Faculty.  It is empowered to recommend to the Faculty policy relating to academic affairs, student affairs, personnel, facilities and any other matters of general faculty concern; to act on college policy relating to such matters; to organize itself with officers elected from voting faculty members; to receive and act upon reports of its committees; and to recommend to and communicate with President of the College, the College Council, the Chancellor of the University, the Board of Trustees, the University Senate or any other appropriate individual or body.
<BR>
<BR>

Section 1.	Name
<BR>
<BR>

This organization shall be known as the Faculty Assembly of the State University College at Potsdam.
<BR>
<BR>

Section 2.	Membership
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 1.	Subdivision delegates.  Each Subdivision of the College shall be represented in the following ratios:  One Faculty delegate for each subdivision having one to nine faculty members, and an additional delegate for each additional nine voting faculty members or major fraction thereof, except that for the purposes of determining the number of delegates from each subdivision, faculty serving less than full time shall be counted as one-half equivalents, and that by reason of their non-voting membership in the Assembly, the Vice Presidents and the Academic Deans shall not be counted in nor represented in any Subdivision.  "Subdivisions" shall mean each of those departments or divisions reporting to an Academic Dean, the Libraries, the Student, Educational and Administrative Services Division, the Division of Institutional Advancement, and General Administration.  Nothing herein contained shall prevent two or more Subdivisions, as defined above, from nominating and/or electing their delegates on a clustered or joint basis, provided that a majority of the voting faculty in each such Subdivision have voted in favor of such form of nomination and/or election at least thirty calendar days prior to the holding of such nominations and/or elections, and provided further, that the results ofsuch vote have been reported to the Secretary of the Faculty Assembly; the total number of positions to be filled under such clustering shall neither exceed nor be less than the number which the affected Subdivisions would otherwise have been entitled to elect.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 2.	Election of Subdivision delegates.</BLOCKQUOTE>

     
				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	The Executive Committee of the Faculty Assembly shall publish a list of Subdivisions, the number of delegates to which each Subdivision is entitled, a list of elections which are to be held under the clustering provisions of Subsection 1 of this Article VII, Section 3, no later than 1 February of odd-numbered years; appeals from the determination of the Executive Committee establishing the list of Subdivisions shall be filed with the Secretary of the Faculty Assembly no later than 1 March of the year in which the list was published and shall be heard by the Faculty Assembly following the reading of the Minutes at its March meeting; such appeal shall be sustained by a majority vote in the affirmative at said meeting.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	Each delegate shall be elected by secret ballot by the members of the respective subdivision or clustered subdivisions who are voting faculty; elections shall be held during February, March, or April of odd-numbered years, and shall be concluded no later than 30 April of such years, with the results of the elections reported to the Secretary of the Faculty Assembly, or designee, at their conclusion; initial elections in newly-created subdivisions shall be held at the time of formation of such subdivisions.  Terms shall be for two years and members are eligible for re-election, except that the initial terms of office of delegates representing newly-created subdivisions shall expire at the same time as those of already existing subdivisions.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	Delegate nominees shall either be nominated from the floor during a meeting of the Subdivision called for that purpose or by procedures established by majority vote of the Subdivision in accordance with the provisions.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>d.	Candidates who are the first to receive a majority of the votes cast shall be declared elected.  Subdivisions shall establish procedures to be followed therein should no candidate receive a majority of votes on the first ballot.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>e.	A vacancy shall be filled by special election within thirty days following the creation of the vacancy.  A delegate so elected shall serve out the unexpired term of office of the delegate replaced.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>f. Each Subdivision shall elect sufficient alternate delegates to act as delegate should the latter be unable to attend a meeting of the Faculty Assembly.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 3.	Faculty Delegates-at-Large.  There shall be ten faculty delegates elected at large; five delegates from the Faculty with five years' completed service at State University College at Potsdam at the time of beginning service in this office, and five delegates from the Faculty of five or fewer years service at the State University College at Potsdam.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 4.	Election of Faculty Delegates-at-Large</BLOCKQUOTE>


			<BLOCKQUOTE>	<BLOCKQUOTE>a.	Delegates-at-large shall be elected by secret ballot from the nominees offered from the floor of a Faculty meeting, said election to be held in (May) the spring of even-numbered years or by mail ballot from a slate of nominees prepared by the Nominating Committee with at least a two- week period provided for submission of nominations by the Faculty.  Terms shall be for two years and members are eligible for re- election.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	Candidates who are the first to receive a plurality of the votes cast shall be declared elected.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	A vacancy in the office of a Delegate-at-Large shall be filled by election by the Faculty Assembly.  A delegate so elected shall serve out the unexpired term of office of the delegate replaced.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 5.	State University Faculty Senator.  The duly elected representative of the Faculty of the State University College at Potsdam to the State University Faculty Senate shall be a Delegate-at- Large by reason of the office.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 6.	Chairpersons of Standing Committees.  Chairpersons of Standing Committees of the Assembly who are not already delegates shall be delegates-at-large for the duration of their term as Chairperson.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<BLOCKQUOTE>	Subsection 7.	Terms of Office of Newly Elected Faculty Assembly Delegates.  Terms of office of all newly elected Faculty Assembly delegates shall commence at the initial fall meeting of the Faculty Assembly.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 8.	List of Delegates.  A list of delegates shall be published within 6 weeks following Fall registration.</BLOCKQUOTE>


Section 3.	Officers:  Duties, Terms of Office
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 1.	Officers.  The officers of the Faculty Assembly shall be its Chairperson, Vice-Chairperson, and Secretary.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 2.	Duties of the Officers</BLOCKQUOTE>


			<BLOCKQUOTE>	<BLOCKQUOTE>a.	The Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly shall preside at all meetings of the Faculty, The Faculty Assembly, and the Faculty Assembly Executive Committee.  The Chairperson shall circulate to the Faculty an agenda one week prior to the meetings of both the Faculty and the Faculty Assembly.  Furthermore, s/he shall represent the Faculty at appropriate college functions and serve as liaison officer to the local College Council.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	The Vice Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly shall, in the absence of the Chairperson, preside at meetings of the Faculty, the Faculty Assembly, and the Executive Committee and may represent the Faculty at appropriate college functions.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


			<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	The Secretary of the Faculty Assembly shall record the minutes of meetings of the Faculty, meetings of the Faculty Assembly, and meetings of the Faculty Assembly Executive Committee.  S/he shall publish the minutes of these meetings and distribute them to the entire faculty not later than ten days after the meeting.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 3.	Terms of Office</BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	The Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly shall be elected for a two-year term, the election to be held in odd-numbered years.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	The Vice-Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly shall be elected for a two-year term, the election to be held in even-numbered years.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	The Secretary of the Faculty Assembly shall be elected for a two-year term, the election to be held in even-numbered years.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>d.	Terms of office shall commence on the June 1st following their election.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


			<BLOCKQUOTE>	<BLOCKQUOTE>e.	Any member of the Faculty is eligible for nomination and election to the offices of Chairperson, Vice-Chairperson, and Secretary, with the exception of persons holding a position of Dean or its equivalent, or higher, and the Faculty representative to the Faculty Senate of the State University of New York.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>f.	In the event of a vacancy in the office of Chairperson, the Vice-Chairperson shall become Chairperson and shall serve out the unexpired balance of the term to which the Chairperson was elected.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>g.	A vacancy in the office of Vice-Chairperson shall be filled by a special election within thirty days after the creation of the vacancy or at the next regularly scheduled election of officers, whichever occurs first.  The Vice- Chairperson so elected shall serve the unexpired balance of the term to which the Vice- Chairperson was elected.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 4.	Elective Procedure for Officers</BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	Nominations to the offices of Chairperson, Vice- Chairperson and Secretary shall be by written petition, said petition specifying the name of the nominee, her/his academic rank or equivalent, the department or sub-division in which s/he is being nominated, and the signature of the nominee indicating her/his willingness to serve if elected.  The petition shall bear the signature of at least 25 members of the Faculty and shall be presented to the Chairperson of the Nominating Committee not later than seven days before the date of the election or the date previously announced for the mailing of ballots.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	The Chairperson of the Nominating Committee shall, in cooperation with the Secretary, prepare for the election written ballots containing the names of all nominees, their academic rank or equivalent, and the department or subdivision in which they serve.  In the event that no petition is received for a particular office, the Nominating Committee shall propose a minimum of two candidates for such office.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	Election of officers shall be held at a Spring meeting of the Faculty or by referendum election.  If the elections are held at ameeting, ballots shall be counted and the results announced before that meeting is adjourned.  Such election shall be the first item of business on the agenda of such meeting after the proposed amendments to the by-laws.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>d.	In the event that no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast for a particular office, a run-off election shall be held immediately following the announcement of the results of the initial ballot, said run-off to be between the two candidates receiving the largest number of votes for the office.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


Section 4.	Meetings
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection l.	Regular meetings of the Faculty Assembly shall be held                     at least monthly during the academic year.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 2.	Regular meetings of the Faculty Assembly shall be called by the Chairperson or, in his/her absence from the College, by the Vice- Chairperson or, in the absence of both, by any member of the Executive Committee.  A special meeting shall be called within one week of receipt of a petition signed by  at least five delegates of the Faculty Assembly.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 3.	All meetings of the Faculty Assembly shall be open to the College Community.  Non-delegates may address the Faculty Assembly when requested by the Chair.</BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 4.	A quorum shall be required to conduct business requiring a vote; said quorum shall consist of a majority of the Faculty Assembly.</BLOCKQUOTE>


Section 5.	Committees
<BR>
<BR>

The officers of the Faculty Assembly, Assembly delegates and any other members of the Faculty may be called upon at various times to serve on Committees of the Faculty Assembly.
<BR>
<BR>

	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection l.	The Executive Committee</BLOCKQUOTE>      


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	Membership:  The Executive Committee shall include the officers of the Faculty Assembly, the Chairperson of each of the Faculty Assembly Standing Committees, the University Faculty Senator (ex-officio), and an                         additional member from each school of the College not otherwise represented in the aforementioned categories of members.  A representative of the collective bargaining agent will be invited to attend as a non-voting member.  A quorum of this committee shall consist of a majority of its membership and is required for the conduct of business.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	Duties:  The Executive Committee shall:</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>l.	assign the business of the Faculty Assembly to the  Standing Committees.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>2.	appoint ad-hoc committees composed of voting faculty to consider matters not appropriate to any Standing Committee.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>3.	fill vacancies which occur in the office of Secretary by appointment; such appointee shall serve until the next election of officers by the voting faculty.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>4.	fill committee vacancies by  appointment.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>5.	receive reports of Standing Committee activities and conduct a continuing review of Standing Committee work.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>6.	grant or deny the written request of any individual faculty member who wishes to appear before or appeal directly to the Faculty Assembly.  When such a petition is accompanied by signatures of a least l0 members of the voting faculty the Committee's compliance with the request shall be mandatory.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>7.	create an agenda of business in cooperation with the Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly to be considered by the Faculty Assembly.  Said agenda shall include tems proposed by 5 members of the voting faculty or by any three members of the Faculty Assembly.  The agenda shall be distributed to all members of the Faculty prior to the meeting.  In case of an emergency meeting, the members of the Faculty Assembly shall be informed as to the nature of the emergency as soon as possible so that maximal time is allowed for the thoughtful consideration of the business.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>8.	confirm or deny the eligibility of all persons proposed for inclusion as 'voting faculty' according to the definition of the same under Article II and III of these by-laws.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>9a. 	The Executive Committee of the Faculty Assembly shall have primary responsibility for the conduct of elections of the Faculty and/or    Faculty Assembly not otherwise provided for in these By-laws.  The Executive Committee shall set the time, place, and mode of the    nominations and elections and shall publish this information to the Faculty one week prior to such nominations and/or elections.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


						<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>9b. Balloting shall be at meetings and/or through                                    establishment of supervised polling places.   Each member of the faculty shall sign for and vote his/her own ballot.  Neither of these procedures shall preclude the use of machine-counted ballots.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>10.		act on behalf of the Faculty or Faculty Assembly in appropriate matters, subject to the review of the Faculty or Faculty Assembly, as appropriate.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 2.	The Standing Committees</BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	The Standing Committees of the Faculty Assembly are advisory groups which make policy recommendations to the Faculty Assembly through the Executive Committee.  All Standing Committees shall have a majority as their quorum and a quorum is required for the conduct of business.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	The Standing Committees of the Faculty Assembly shall be:</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>1.	The Nominating Committee<BR>

					2.	The Academic Programs and Curriculum Committee <BR>

					3.	The Admissions Committee  <BR>

					4.	The Academic Policies, Standards, and Advising Committee<BR>

					5.	The Graduate Affairs Committee<BR>

					6.	The Business Affairs Committee<BR>

					7.	The Student Affairs Committee<BR>

					8.	The Goals and Planning Committee</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>

   
				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>c.	Membership in the Standing Committees:  each committee, with the exceptions noted in (d) below, shall be composed of the following, all of whom have a vote:</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>1.	seven faculty members elected by and from the Faculty of the college;
<BR>
<BR>

					2.	two students, chosen by the student body, invited to serve as voting members on the  Academic Affairs Committee, the Business Affairs Committee, and the Student Affairs Committee, with the provision that such students serving on the Graduate Affairs Committee shall be graduate students;
<BR>
<BR>

					3.	two or more additional members of the Faculty as required in order that the Committee shall include at least one member from each school of the College and as many additional members as deemed necessary by the Committee to facilitate the conduct of business.
<BR>
<BR>

					4.	two additional students as deemed necessary by the committee to facilitate the conduct of business with the provision that such students serving on the Graduate Affairs Committee shall be graduate students.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


			<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>d.	Special Membership Provisions</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


					<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>1.	Faculty memberships on the Graduate Affairs Committee shall be limited to members of the Graduate Faculty as determined in Article III.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>e.	Membership on all Standing Committees shall be for two years.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>f.	Each Standing Committee, except the Nominating Committee, shall meet at least once a month  during the period from September 1 to May 31.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>g.	Items may be placed on the agenda of a Faculty Assembly Standing Committee by any member of the particular committee.  The agenda for each meeting and the minutes of the previous meeting shall be distributed to all committee members and to all Subdivisions of the College to be made available to all faculty at least one day prior to the meeting.  The utilization of an agenda shall not preclude the introduction of new business during the meeting.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>h.	At the initial meeting of each Standing Committee its members shall elect a chairperson and a recorder from among its membership.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>Subsection 3.	Ad Hoc Committees</BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a.	Each Standing Committee Chairperson shall be empowered to appoint ad hoc sub-committees whose duties and responsibilities shall be described by the individual committee.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>


				<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>b.	The Chairperson of the Faculty Assembly may appoint additional ad hoc committees to report to the Faculty Assembly on special matters.  The appointment of these additional committees shall be subject to the approval of the Faculty Assembly.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<br>
<BR>
<br>           
