<BR>

<A NAME="VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS"><CENTER><B>VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS</B></CENTER></A>
<br>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6H><b>H</A>.	DEATH BENEFITS</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>If an employee dies while in State service, beneficiaries may receive death benefits from the retirement plan elected by the employee, from the Social Security Administration, and from the Survivor's Benefit Program for State Employees.

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I1"><i>1</A>.	RETIREMENT SYSTEM DEATH BENEFITS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I1a">a</A>)	TRS And ERS
<dt><br>
		<dt>Both State retirement systems provide death benefits (if death occurs while in State service) to members' beneficiaries, the amount and type of which vary according to the cause of death, age, years of service, and tier membership.
<dt><br>
<dt>If an employee's death is not caused by a job-related accident TRS or ERS, as appropriate, pays a lump sum (an ORDINARY DEATH BENEFIT) based on the employee's age, years of service, and other factors.
<dt><br>
<dt>When death results from an accident occurring on the job (provided the accident did not result from the employee's negligence), a continuous benefit (ACCIDENTAL DEATH BENEFIT) of half the employee's final average salary is paid to an eligible beneficiary.  No minimum period of service is required for eligibility.  The award may be reduced by the amount of any Workers' Compensation benefit paid.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I1b">b</A>)	TIAA-CREF
<Dt><br>
			<dt>The full current value of the annuity accumulation, including the portion bought by University contributions may be paid as income to the beneficiary named.  If the beneficiary is a corporation, association or estate, a single sum payment will be made.  A single sum payment is available to a named beneficiary, such as a spouse or child, unless a written election selecting some other option has been filed.  A form for this election may be obtained from the Office of Human Resources Development.
<dt><br>
<dt>Death benefits specific to each retirement system and Tier (as appropriate) are described in detail under the retirement plans of this section.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I2"><i>2</A>.	SOCIAL SECURITY DEATH BENEFITS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The U.S. Social Security Administration provides a one-time lump sum death benefit for those who have paid into the system.  Generally, a beneficiary receives 75% of the primary insurance benefit the  employee would have received if he or she retired at age 65.  The exact amount payable is determined by such factors as salary at the time of death, number and age of dependents, and whether any of the dependents has a disability.  A widow or widower with children may be entitled to additional benefits.     

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3"><i>3</A>.	SURVIVOR'S BENEFIT PROGRAMS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3a">a</A>)	For Academic And Professional Employees

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3ai">i</A>)	The Program
<dt><br>
				<dt>The Survivor's Benefit Program for active academic and professional employees is a plan to provide for payment of minimum death benefits to survivors of New York State employees.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3aii">ii</A>)	Eligibility

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3aiia">(a)</A>	For Participation In The Program
<dt><br>
	<dt>You are automatically eligible to participate in the program if you                   
<dt><br>
<dd>(1) are paid directly from State funds;
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) have been employed by the State for 90 days and die prior to the effective date of retirement; and
<dt><br>
<dd>(3) are either on a regularly scheduled work week of 20 hours or more and are paid on an annual salary basis at the rate of at least $2,000.
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you enter State service at age 65 or older, you need at least one year of continuous service in order to qualify.
<dt><br>
<Dt>If your death should occur as a result of occupational injury, you are eligible to qualify regardless of length of service provided an accidental death benefit is paid on your behalf by your retirement system.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3aiib">(b)</A>	For A Survivor's Benefit Payment
<dt><br>
					<dt>In order to be eligible to have a benefit paid to your beneficiary, your death must occur before the effective date of your retirement.  You must also at the time of death meet one of the following conditions:
<dt><br>
<dd>(1) have been on the State payroll for 90 or more of the 120 days immediately preceding your death;
<dt><br>
			<dd>(2) have at least one year of State service and die while on the payroll following your return from an authorized leave of absence without pay;
<dt><br>
			<dd>(3) have at least one year of State service since the date of last entry and die while on authorized leave of absence without pay, provided you were not otherwise gainfully employed while on leave, and provided you were on the State payroll within six months prior to death;
<dt><br>
			<dd>(4) have at least five years of State service since the date of last entry and die while on authorized leave of absence without pay, provided you were not otherwise gainfully employed while on leave, and provided you were on the State payroll within one year prior to death;
<Dt><br>
			<dd>(5) have been a member of a public pension  plan on whose account an accidental death benefit is paid.
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you die within 30 days after you separate from State service, you may also be eligible to have a benefit paid to your beneficiary.
</dl>
			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3aiii">iii</A>)	Amount Of The Survivor's Benefit Payment
<dt><br>
<dd>(a)	In the case of an ordinary death, the total death benefit is at least one-half your annual salary with a minimum payment of $2,000.  Here's how it works:
<Dt><br>
<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>(1) if you do not belong to a retirement system, or if your retirement system does not provide an ordinary death benefit, the beneficiary's     payment will come entirely from the Survivor's Benefit Program.  The maximum survivor's benefit payment is $10,000;
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) if you belong to a retirement system that pays an ordinary death benefit, but do not qualify for a benefit of one-half your annual salary, or at least $2,000, the Survivor's Benefit Program  will supplement the death benefit payment made by your retirement system.
<dt><br>
(b)	In the case of an accidental death benefit payment made by your retirement system, the Survivor's Benefit Program will supplement the retirement system's benefit with a lump sum payment of $2,000 to your beneficiary.</BLOCKQUOTE>

			</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3aiv">iv</A>)	The Beneficiary
<dt><br>
				<dt>If you are a member of a retirement system that provides an ordinary death benefit, you designated your beneficiary at the time you joined.  You do not need to file another designation of beneficiary.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you are not a retirement system member, or if you belong to a system that does not provide an ordinary death benefit, you should fill out a Designation of Beneficiary card, Form PS-151 available from the Office of Human Resources.  This is ordinarily done at the time of your initial appointment to the College.
<dt><br>
<Dt>No action by your beneficiary is necessary to initiate payment under this program.  The College automatically notifies the Program of your death.

		</dl>
<dt><br>

<A NAME="6I3b">b</A>)	For Managerial/Confidential Employees (M/C)

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3bi">i</A>)	The Program
<dt><br>
				<dt>The M/C Survivor's Benefit Program is a plan to provide for payment of a minimum death benefit to survivors of New York State Managerial/Confidential employees.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3bii">ii</A>)	Eligibility

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3biia">(a)</A>	For Participation In The Program
<dt><br>
		<dt>You are automatically eligible to participate in the program if you
<Dt><br>
<Dd>(1) are paid directly from State funds;
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) have been employed by the State in a M/C capacity for 30 days; and
<dt><br>
<dd>(3) are on a regularly scheduled work week of 20 hours or more and are paid a salary at least equal to the minimum annual salary for a M/C-3 employee.			
<dt><br>
	<dt>If your death should occur as a result of occupational injury, you are eligible to qualify regardless of length of service provided an accidental death benefit is paid on your behalf by your retirement system.
<dt><br>
			<dt>NOTE:	M/C employees who do not meet the eligibility requirements for the M/C survivor's benefit may be eligible for a survivor's benefit as described above for academic and professional employees.  M/C employees who meet the eligibility requirements under both programs will be paid under the program which will yield the greater benefit.

				</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3biib">(b)</A>	For A Survivor's Benefit Payment
<dt><br>
<dt>In order to be eligible to have a benefit paid to your beneficiary, your death must occur before the effective date of your retirement.  You must also at the time of death meet one of the following conditions:
<dt><br>
<dd>(1) have been on the State payroll as a M/C employee for 30 or more of the 60 days immediately preceding your death;
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) have at least one year of M/C State service and     die while on the payroll following your return from an authorized leave of absence without pay;
<dt><br>
<dd>(3) have at least one year of M/C State service since the date of last entry and die while on authorized leave of absence without pay, provided you were not otherwise gainfully     employed while on leave, and provided you were on the State payroll as a M/C employee within six months prior to death;
<dt><br>
<dd>(4) have at least five years of M/C State service since the date of last entry and die while on authorized leave of absence without pay, provided you were not otherwise gainfully employed while on leave, and provided you were on the State payroll as a M/C employee within one year prior to death;
<dt><br>
<dd>(5) have been a member of a public pension plan on whose account an accidental death benefit is paid.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you die within 30 days after you separate from a managerial position, you may also be eligible to have a benefit paid to your beneficiary.
</dl>
			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3biii">iii</A>)	Amount Of The Survivor's Benefit Payment
<dt><br>
				<dd>(a)	In the case of an ordinary death, the total death benefit is normally equal to your annual salary.  Here's how it works:
<dt>
<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>(1) If an ordinary death benefit is not payable by your retirement system, the beneficiary's payment will come entirely from the survivor's benefit program and will normally equal annual salary.  However, the maximum survivor's benefit payment must not exceed the lesser of $50,000 or five times the ordinary death benefit payable by the retirement system had you rendered the required service.
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) If you do not belong to a retirement system, the survivor's benefit will be calculated in the manner described in (1) above.  However, for purposes of determining the maximum benefit payable, the benefit must not exceed the lesser of $50,000 or five times the ordinary death benefit which would have been paid by ERS had you joined that system and rendered the required member service.
<dt><br>
<dd>(3) If you belong to a retirement system that pays an ordinary death benefit but do not qualify for a benefit equal to your annual salary, the Survivor's Benefit Program will supplement the death benefit payment made by your retirement system.  The maximum total payment (ordinary death benefit plus survivor's benefit) must not exceed the lesser of $50,000 or five times the ordinary death benefit payable by the retirement system when the benefit is reduced to your age.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
				<dd>(b)	In the case of an accidental death benefit payment made by your retirement system, the Survivor's Benefit Program will supplement the retirement system's benefit with a lump sum payment of $5,000 to your beneficiary.
<BR>
<BR>

			</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3biv">iv</A>)	The Beneficiary
<dt><br>
				<dt>If you are member of a retirement system that provides an ordinary death benefit, you designated your beneficiary at the time you joined.  You do not need to file another designation of beneficiary.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you are not a retirement system member, or if you belong to a system that does not provide an ordinary death benefit, you should fill out a Designation of Beneficiary card, Form PS-151 available from the Office of Human Resources.  This is ordinarily done at the time of your initial appointment to the College.
<dt><br>
<dt>No action by your beneficiary is necessary to initiate payment under this program.  The College automatically notifies the Program of your death.
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3c">c</A>)	For Retired State Employees

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3ci">i</A>)	The Program
<dt><br>
				<dt>In 1966 Legislation was enacted establishing a $2,000 death benefit for State employees who retired on or after October 1, 1966.  In 1970 the benefit was increased to $3,000 for those who retire on or after April 1, 1970.  Payment is made from State funds without cost to the employee.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3cii">ii</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
				<dt>As a retired State employee, you will be eligible to have survivor's benefit paid on your behalf if
<dt><br>
<dd>(a)	while in State service, you either:
<dt><br>
	<dd><BLOCKQUOTE>(1) retire from any retirement system or pension plan supported by State funds other than the State University optional retirement program, or
<dt><br>
<dd>(2) retire from the State University Optional Retirement Program after age 55, or
<dt><br>
<dd>(3) leave State service after age 62</BLOCKQUOTE>.
<dt>
 <dd>                                            AND
<dt><br>
				<dd>(b)	if you had at least 10 years of full-time State service within the 15 years immediately prior to leaving or retiring from State service. State service includes only employment for which salary is paid directly by the State.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3ciii">iii</A>)	Amount Of Survivor's Benefit Payment
<dt><br>
				<dt>For State employees who retired between October 1, 1966 and March 31, 1970, the survivor's benefit is $2,000.  For State employees who retire on or after April 1, 1970, the benefit is $3,000.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3civ">iv</A>)	The Beneficiary
<dt><br>
				<dt>If you are a member of a retirement system and have selected a retirement option for which you designated a beneficiary to receive retirement benefits after you die, the survivor's benefits will be paid to that beneficiary.
<Dt><br>
<dt>If you are not a member of a retirement system or if you are a member but you have not designated a beneficiary with such system, you must designate a beneficiary for this program on a Form PS-160, Eligibility of Retired Employee for Survivor's Benefit.  This is provided by the Office of Human Resources at the time of retirement.
<dt><br>
<dt>If the beneficiary you designated to your retirement system dies or you wish to change your beneficiary for any other reason, write to your retirement system for instructions.
<dt><br>
<dt>If your beneficiary dies and your retirement option does not allow you to designate a new beneficiary, you can still designate a new beneficiary for the survivor's benefit program.  Fill out Form PS-161.1 (Change of Beneficiary) and send it to the Department of Civil Service.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you have designated a beneficiary on Form PS-160 you may change your beneficiary at any time by completing Form PS-161.1 (Change of Beneficiary) and sending it to the Department of Civil Service.

<dt><br>
<dt>Upon your death, your beneficiary should immediately complete Form PS-161.2 (Beneficiary's Application for Benefits) and send it to the Department of Civil Service, Employee Relations Section, The State Campus, Albany, New York 12239.  If you were not a member of a retirement system, the beneficiary should also send an original or certified copy of the Certificate of Death.  Forms PS 161.1 and PS 161.2 are also available from the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
<Dt>Any questions you or your beneficiary have may be directed to the Office of Human Resources or to the Employee Relations Section of the Department of Civil Service, The State Campus, Albany, New York  12239.      
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6I3d">d</A>)	Information For Survivors Of New York State Employees
<dt><br>
			<Dt>An information brochure for survivors of State employees (active or retired) describing matters needing attention after a death is available to each survivor from the Office of Human Resources.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<br><br>
