<HEAD>
<TITLE>tynatwo.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
September 13, 1996<BR>
We were supposed to meet for the first time at the river this week    , but the kids 
had other plans to visit the local penitentiary.  Thursday night Stacey and Eric 
gave me all the information they had used in class with them and I made up worksheets 
for the chemistry sub-group.  I was originally going to be working with both subgroups 
alone, but Rita will be joining me to work with the biology subgroup.  We had agreed 
to use the worksheets and at the end of class we would ask the students how they 
felt about continuing the worksheets in comparison to trying another method.  The worksheets 
were slow going.  Keeping the kids on task was challenging.  I knew that filling 
out worksheets wasn't going to be a whole lot of fun, but it seemed to be the best 
way to review all the material with the kids.  <BR>
They did work hard on them , and I got volunteers from the groups to present the worksheets 
to the biology group when we all got back together.  WOW!  Rita had her teams finish 
a project they had started the day before and never got to the worksheets she had prepared at all.  The bi    ology group presented the towns they had built, my 
students presented their worksheets, and I knew instantly I had been blown right 
out of the water.  The projects took precedence, or seemed to, over my worksheets, 
and I felt bad for the kids.  Right away I approached them and asked them if they would prefer 
to work on projects instead of worksheets. I warned them it would be more difficult 
and they would have to stay on task better but they were up to the challenge - time 
will tell if I am!  Today did go well, and I have ideas running around inside my head 
- activities that I could try to do with them to help bring home a point or topic 
of focus for the weeks to come.<BR><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="tynathree.html"><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#084842"> Journal 3 </A>
<BR>

</BODY>
