<TITLE>tynafour.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
September 20, 1996<BR>
This week we were focusing on heavy metals, I discussed with Stacey and Eric the possibility 
of having them diagram the atoms of some of the heavy metals we might find in the 
river.  They felt it was a great idea so I went ahead with it.  I started off by telling them what we would be doing, but before getting started we reviewed (and 
boy was it review for them!) the subatomic particles, the shells, and how many 
electrons went into each shell.  I kept it as basic as I knew how, in fact I'm a 
bit worried that I missed something simply because I kept it so basic.  I was floored by how 
much they already knew - how little there was for me to teach to them.  I felt a 
bit under prepared because I hadn't given consideration to this factor.  Well . . 
. make the mistake once - learn from it!!<BR>
The projects went really well.  They had no difficulty at all staying on task, I continuously 
quizzed them to keep them thinking about science rather then seeing this as a simple 
art project.  They really got into the activity and did a fantastic job when they presented the posters to the biology subgroup.  Before letting them sit down, 
I asked them questions very similar to the ones I had been asking them as they prepared 
their posters - they answered them all superbly while at the same time giving all 
the information I had suppled them directly back to their peers in the other subgroup. 
 I h    ave high hopes about continuing with projects similar to this - projects 
which will focus on the major point of the week while bringing a close to the week 
by allowing for review of all the material presented.<BR>
Rita and I are going to begin staying into the second period with them and just help 
tutor them in any of their subjects to make sure they are keeping up all of their 
grades.  If their grades slip we could lose them from the project - it also gives 
us a chance to work more closely with the students.      One of the students gave me my 
first real compliment today (from a student perspective!) and I must say - THIS FEELING 
is exactly why I want to teach, I am more sure of it now then I ever have been before.<BR><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="tynafive.html"><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#084842">Journal 5</A>

</BODY>
</HTML>
