<TITLE>tynasix.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
September 27, 1996<BR>
GAME WEEK!  Whoa, what a blast we had today!  Stacey and Eric helped to give me fantastic 
review questions about the different test we are performing and the importance reasons 
why and how we perform them.  I threw in some questions about heavy metals and items I had talked to them about on my own time.  We played TIC-T    AC-TOE; Rita 
and I split the subgroups in half making sure each team had biology and chemistry 
members on them.  I took it one step further and made sure that each team had members 
from each formal chemistry group so that each group had experts from all the nine different 
tests.  Rita and I each bought a bag of candy and hid them in paper sacks.  The winner 
of the game was allowed to choose which bag of candy they wanted.  <BR>
The games went really well.  I was a bit discouraged about how little they seemed 
to recall at first, but they really started to work together as teams to attempt 
to come up with the correct answers.  Sometimes we had to offer clues, but that only 
incited more effort as teams and that in itself is a rare and important lesson to be learned. 
 I was worried that the questions were too difficult for them, but if they didn't 
recall it from a previous lesson, I can console myself with the fact that they have 
now been exposed to them again.  I will keep these questions and add to them for the 
ne    xt game week.  In a longer term goal, these questions may play an important 
part in the mid-term or final we devise for the students - I can rest assured that 
they will  have heard and discussed these questions several times before that happens.<BR>
The class also had a substitute today, it was very interesting for me to observe how 
she handled herself with the students.  It was obvious this wasn't the first time 
she had subbed for the class.  They had gotten themselves into a very large mess 
and were adequately punished for it, I still felt really bad for them.  I realize that classroom 
management is an important lesson I will learn, and I can see myself portraying all 
the right traits to becoming a stern teacher - but I am still too soft-hearted as 
yet and I felt so sorry for them. . ..<BR>
