<TITLE>tynaten.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
October 11, 1996<BR>
Whoa, today was nuts!  Talk about these kids having a lot of energy!  There is a three day weekend coming up and they were just bouncing off the walls!  To put things mildly, we did not go down for dodge ball today! <BR>
Today was the first half of their midterm - the lab practicum and it is worth 50% of the grade.  I was sitting on one side of a partition with the students on one on one interviews so I could administer their exams, and the kids were on the other side of this partition working (SUPPOSEDLY) on their study guides for the second half of the 
exams.  They did not sit still and focus as well as I would have liked!  The kids all did fantastic on their examinations with me, but when they were left unsupervised directly - wow did I feel as though I had lost them!<BR>
I really had a chance to pra    ctice my teacher "I am NOT happy" tone!  I think I am getting pretty good at this stuff!  I had to get up 5 times to ask them to knock of the antics in a 90 minute period, although it was a lot, I can't help but feel I got off easier then the other teachers in my group did the day before!  I continued to threaten them with no dodge ball until they didn't even care about it any more - then we went directly to staying after school with Mr. Vandenberg - and that REALLY 
worked well.<BR>
I helped the kids with their math as well and that felt great!  I really hope to get my Mathematics credential along with my Chemistry credential!  i am bringing this up because one of the students was being punished and did not want to be left in the room alone so I stayed to keep company and assure that he stayed on the task assigned as punishment.  We had a pretty good talk, and I learned a lot about him in just the few things that he mentioned.  It is the first time any of the kids has really opened up and discussed what they wanted to do with their futures and how their pasts has affected that decision.  These kids are phenomenal and I am getting awfully attached to them!  I worry that I am caring to much about how they are doing and hoping too hard that they will just make it through one year at a time until they graduate.  <P>

