<HEAD>
<TITLE>tyna1018.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
October 18, 1996<BR>
<BR>
Today was pretty simple. I gave the kids the second half of the midterm.  We used the entire period to work on the midterm so I saved the activity I had planned for Monday.  I learned an important and different teaching style that I have.  One of my students was picking up the desk and balancing it across his knees.  I asked him to put it back on the floor and he asked me if he could leave it as it was.  He explained that he thought better that way.  I told him fine and simply asked that he not disturb anybody else in the classroom. The minute I felt he was acting up or out of control I stopped it.   For about 45 minutes, he worked very hard on the exam and didn't bother any other person. <BR>
 Upon returning to the main classroom and joining both groups (Bio and Chem) back together, Mike performed an activity about the water cycle called the Incredible Journey.  The final portion of the activity dealt with the students creating stories about being water drops.  The same student I had that had requested leniency with propriety before was, within minutes of being released to work on the paper, leaning way across a table with his knees in the chair.  The teachers assistant immediately asked the student to sit properly.  Again he beseeched that he be allowed to remain in what was, for him, a creative thinking position.  The assistants answer was no.  This student lost complete interest in the paper and didn't resume work until he was in the position he had been in before.  He looked at me during his reprimand, but I did not say a word about the leniency I had showed him.  His paper reflected intense creativity and I have a hard time finding fault with a student simply because he is not residing in a chair with both feet firmly planted on the floor in front of him.  Am I wrong?  Do I push the student and risk the loss of intensity?<P>

